52748704212804575332663623363920| archivedate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n| Chairman\n|-\n!\n| [[International Labour Organization]]\n| [[Juan Somav\u00eda]]<ref name=\"ilo\">{{cite web| title=Biography of Juan Somavia, Director-General| url=http://www.ilo.org/public/english/bureau/dgo/biography.htm| publisher=International Labour Organization| date=4 November 2011| accessdate=2012-03-23| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405024604/http://www.ilo.org/public/english/bureau/dgo/biography.htm| archivedate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n| Director-General\n|-\n!\n| [[International Monetary Fund]]\n| [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]]<ref name=\"gubert\"/>\n| Managing Director\n|-\n!\n| [[New Partnership for Africa's Development|NEPAD]]\n| [[Meles Zenawi]]<ref name=\"macleans_arrive\"/>\n| Chairman\n|-\n!\n| [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]]\n| [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Gurr\u00eda]]<ref name=\"simon\">{{cite journal| title=Angel Gurr\u00eda, OECD Secretary-General (CV)| publisher=OCED}}</ref>\n| Secretary General\n|-\n! {{flagicon|United Nations}}\n| [[United Nations]]\n| [[Ban Ki-moon]]<ref name=\"ward\">{{cite news| author=Olivia Ward| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/829237--ban-ki-moon-at-g20-as-defender-of-the-defenceless| title=Ban Ki-moon at G20 as 'defender of the defenceless'| work=Toronto Star| date=26 June 2010| publisher=thestar.com| accessdate=2012-03-26| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021153922/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/829237--ban-ki-moon-at-g20-as-defender-of-the-defenceless| archivedate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n| [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General]]\n|-\n!\n| [[World Bank Group]]\n| [[Robert Zoellick]]<ref name=\"simon\"/>\n| President\n|-\n!\n| [[World Trade Organization]]\n| [[Pascal Lamy]]<ref name=\"gubert\"/>\n| Director-General\n|}\n\n== Protests ==\n{{Main|2010 G20 Toronto summit protests}}\n[[File:G-20 Toronto June 2010 (20).jpg|thumb|right|Demonstrators holding signs with slogans against the G20]]\nMajor protests occurred in [[downtown Toronto]] during the week of the summit, which abruptly escalated during the days of the summit. Early opposition to the G20 included an incident in [[Ottawa]] where a bank was firebombed by [[anarchism|anarchists]], who claimed they would be present during the G20 summit in Toronto.<ref name=\"rbc\">{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/rbc-firebombed-as-protest-group-claims-1.915706 | title=RBC firebombed as protest, group claims | publisher=CBC.ca | work=CBC News | date=8 May 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-23 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522013917/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/rbc-firebombed-as-protest-group-claims-1.915706 | archivedate=22 May 2010 }}</ref> The perceived security threat caused the [[Integrated Security Unit]] to increase security measures.<ref name=\"swainson\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/812976--ottawa-firebombing-proves-security-need-clement-says |title=Ottawa firebombing proves security need, Clement says |work=Toronto Star |date=21 May 2010 |publisher=thestar.com |accessdate=2010-09-28 |author=Gail Swainson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607101152/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/812976--ottawa-firebombing-proves-security-need-clement-says |archivedate=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nProtests began one week ahead of the summit, organized by groups including [[Oxfam Canada]] and the [[Ontario Coalition Against Poverty]].  Issues such as [[poverty]],<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news| url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE65E4RB20100617?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Toronto G20 protest hints at more to come |publisher=Reuters (Canada) |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23 |author=Cameron French and Pav Jordan| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100622091653/http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE65E4RB20100617?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0| archivedate= 22 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Canada|gay rights]],<ref name=\"yang\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827058--gays-lesbians-hold-g20-kiss-in?bn=1 |title=G20 turning downtown Toronto into a ghost town |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-22|accessdate=2010-06-24 | first1=Jennifer | last1=Yang | first2=Liam | last2=Casey| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100626093646/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827058--gays-lesbians-hold-g20-kiss-in?bn=1| archivedate= 26 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[capitalism]] and [[globalization]],<ref name=\"poisson\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826478--g20-protesters-try-to-take-over-downtown-property?bn=1 |title=G20 protesters try to take over downtown property |publisher=thestar.com | date=21 June 2010| accessdate=2010-06-22 | work=Toronto Star | first=Jayme | last=Poisson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625043412/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826478--g20-protesters-try-to-take-over-downtown-property?bn=1| archivedate= 25 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[indigenous rights]],<ref name=\"edwards\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827924--first-nations-demonstrators-take-over-downtown-streets?bn=1 |title=First nations demonstrators take over downtown streets |publisher=thestar.com |date=24 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-24| work=Toronto Star| first=Peter | last=Edwards| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100627143516/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827924--first-nations-demonstrators-take-over-downtown-streets?bn=1| archivedate= 27 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and controversial issues with the summit itself were the object of protests.<ref name=\"largest\">{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100625/g20-summit-protest-poverty-100625/20100625/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Riot police turn back largest G20 protest yet| work=CTV News| publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=25 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-24| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628035045/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100625/g20-summit-protest-poverty-100625/20100625/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Despite a few arrests, protests over the week were mainly determined to be peaceful.<ref name=\"continue\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/protests-continue-in-toronto-as-g20-nears-1.914177 |title=Protests continue in Toronto as G20 nears |publisher=CBC.ca |work=CBC News |date=22 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-24| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625060457/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/protests-continue-in-toronto-as-g20-nears-1.914177| archivedate= 25 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs the first day of the summit approached, protesters grew in numbers. Several streets were closed to demonstrations on the debut of the summit. Peaceful protests were followed by [[black bloc]] tactics as individuals dressed in black dispersed from the crowd and began damaging the windows of particular businesses across downtown Toronto, mostly [[List of fast food restaurant chains|fast food chains]], retail stores and banks, as well as local businesses.<ref name=\"tactics\">{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829168--violent-black-bloc-tactics-on-display-at-g20-protest?bn=1 |title=Violent Black Bloc tactics on display at G20 protest |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-26 |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=2010-06-27 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630071652/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829168--violent-black-bloc-tactics-on-display-at-g20-protest?bn=1| archivedate= 30 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Police car|Police cruisers]] were set on fire and vehicles of media corporations were damaged.<ref name=\"clear\">{{cite web| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/summit-protests-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Police attempt to clear crowds amid G20 unrest |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628062552/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/summit-protests-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Nearby hospitals, shopping centres, and hotels were put in [[lockdown]] mode while public transit services were diverted from downtown to other locations.<ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite web| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/toronto-chaos-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=TTC lines, Eaton Centre locked down as protests heat up |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100630151222/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/toronto-chaos-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 30 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs security was further tightened and forces increased in presence the following day, protests against police brutality occurred in front of the [[Eastern Avenue (Toronto)|Eastern Avenue]] temporary detention centre, where nearly 500 arrested individuals were kept from the previous day's riots.<ref name=\"CTV.ca\">{{cite news |author=Jesse Ship |date=2010-06-28 |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/toronto-g20-anti-police-rally-100628/20100628/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Another large demonstration follows the G20 |publisher=[[CFTO-DT]] |accessdate=13 November 2010  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902065917/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/toronto-g20-anti-police-rally-100628/20100628?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=2 September 2010 }}</ref> A group of protesters was also \"[[kettling|kettled]]\" for several hours through the night after black bloc protesters were believed to be in the crowd.<ref name=\"mclean2\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829642--police-defend-crowd-trap-at-queen-and-spadina |title=Police defend crowd trap at Queen and Spadina  |publisher=thestar.com |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23 | work=Toronto Star | author=Jesse McLean| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100701151357/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829642--police-defend-crowd-trap-at-queen-and-spadina| archivedate= 1 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Over 1100 people were confirmed to be arrested over the week.<ref name=\"mahoney\">{{cite news | title=G20-related mass arrests unique in Canadian history | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/g20-related-mass-arrests-unique-in-canadian-history/article1621198/ | date=29 June 2010 | work=The Globe and Mail | accessdate=2012-04-05 | author=Jill Mahoney and Ann Hui | publisher=theglobeandmail.com | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728172459/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/g20-related-mass-arrests-unique-in-canadian-history/article1621198/ | archivedate=28 July 2010 }}</ref> The ISU performed sweeping arrests within a specific boundary from the summit venue.<ref name=\"sweeping\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/828367--g20-law-gives-police-sweeping-powers-to-arrest-people |title=G20 law gives police sweeping powers to arrest people |work=Toronto Star |publisher=thestar.com |date=25 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-24 |author=Jennifer Yang| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628022808/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/828367--g20-law-gives-police-sweeping-powers-to-arrest-people| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Individuals arrested during the protests condemned the treatment they received from police.<ref name=\"ship\">{{cite news |author=Jesse Ship |date=28 June 2010 |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829921--i-will-not-forget-what-they-have-done-to-me?bn=1 |title=I will not forget what they have done to me |work=Toronto Star |publisher=thestar.com |accessdate=2012-03-23  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702011919/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829921--i-will-not-forget-what-they-have-done-to-me?bn=1 |archivedate=2 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Outcome ==\n[[File:Leaders at the 2010 G-20 Toronto summit.jpg|thumb|right|Leaders confer at the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] on June 27]]\nPrior to the Toronto summit, it was speculated that it would not see the same outcome as previous summits. This was partially due to most countries' entering recovery mode from the [[Great Recession|global economic recession]] after the past G20 summits; thus, the likelihood of new issues being raised was minimal.<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite news| title=G20 lacks governing instruments| url=https://rt.com/politics/roar-russia-g20-g8/| publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT News]]| date=28 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-23| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725214901/https://rt.com/politics/roar-russia-g20-g8/| archivedate=25 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the working dinner for G20 leaders on the evening of June 26, South African president [Jacob Zuma] promoted more partnership between the international community and Africa for the development in the continent. \"As Africa we bring to the G20 Summit the key message that we must, together as the developing and developed worlds, promote stronger and more effective and equal international partnerships for growth and development,\" he remarked.<ref name=\"zuma\">{{cite news| url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=nw20100627065853768C239086| title=Zuma urges more partnerships at G20 dinner| work=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-23| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628142927/http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=nw20100627065853768C239086| archivedate=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the summit, the US president [[Barack Obama]] warned that global recovery was still \"fragile.\" In hopes of boosting American exports, he proposed a [[free trade agreement]] between the [[United States]] and [[South Korea]].<ref name=\"schneider\">{{cite news| author=Howard Schneider| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/26/AR2010062604314.html?sid=ST2010062604320| title=President Obama urges G-20 nations to spend; they pledge to halve deficits| work=[[The Washington Post]]| date=28 June 2010| publisher=washingtonpost.com| accessdate=2012-03-28| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112133834/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/26/AR2010062604314.html?sid=ST2010062604320| archivedate=12 November 2012}}</ref> A key agreement the leaders of [[Developed country|developed nations]] made was to cut annual budget deficits in half by 2013.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/100628_harper_g20/20100628/?hub=CP24Home |title=Harper applauds summit outcome but says G20 still has a lot more to do |publisher=[[CP24]] |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305161607/http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/100628_harper_g20/20100628/?hub=CP24Home |archivedate=5 March 2012 }}</ref> The leaders also agreed on reducing [[debt-to-GDP ratio]] in each economy by 2016.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> The debate on imposing a [[bank tax|tax on financial institutions]] was settled as the group agreed that [[financial institution]]s would be required to make fair contributions to recover costs from the financial sector reform,<ref name=\"fmm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesfinanzministerium.de/EN/Topics/International-affairs/Articles/20100816-Outcome-of-the-Toronto-G20-summit.html |title=Outcome of the Toronto G20 summit |publisher=[[Federal Ministry of Finance (Germany)]] |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229212604/http://www.bundesfinanzministerium.de/EN/Topics/International-affairs/Articles/20100816-Outcome-of-the-Toronto-G20-summit.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref> but the manner of collecting the contributions would be left to each government.<ref name=\"whittingon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829266--g20-adopts-canadian-compromise-on-deficits-bank-tax |title=G20 adopts Canadian compromise on deficits, bank tax |publisher=thestar.com |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |work=Toronto Star |first1=Les |last1=Whittingon |author2=Bruce Campion-Smith and Richard J. Brennan |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419012709/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829266--g20-adopts-canadian-compromise-on-deficits-bank-tax |archivedate=19 April 2012 }}</ref> Participants also decided that the institutions would be required to keep a higher amount of [[financial capital]] in case of future [[Shock (economics)|financial shocks]].<ref name=\"gascoigne\">{{cite press release |author=Clark Gascoigne |url=http://www.financialtaskforce.org/2010/04/23/g20-finance-ministers-communique-is-released/ |title=G20 Finance Ministers Communiqu\u00e9 is Released |publisher=[[Task Force on Financial Integrity and Economic Development]] |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427041640/http://www.financialtaskforce.org/2010/04/23/g20-finance-ministers-communique-is-released/ |archivedate=27 April 2010 }}</ref> [[Climate change]] and [[food security]] were also discussed; the leaders reiterated their commitment to a \"[[environmentally friendly|greener]] growth\".<ref name=\"iisd\">{{cite web|url=http://climate-l.org/news/g-20-toronto-summit-addresses-energy-subsidies-climate-change-and-food-security/ |title=G-20 Toronto Summit Addresses Energy Subsidies, Climate Change and Food Security |publisher=International Institute for Sustainable Development |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813174308/http://climate-l.org/news/g-20-toronto-summit-addresses-energy-subsidies-climate-change-and-food-security/ |archivedate=13 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''The G20 Toronto Summit Declaration'', which was released shortly after the summit concluded, stated that \"serious challenges remain.\" According to the document, the challenges include high unemployment rates in various economies and the concurrent existence of the impact of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|financial crisis]]. The [[International Monetary Fund]], in its post-summit document, indicated that a speedy cut in deficits may substantially slow growth. In a publication entitled ''Top Ten Commandments for Fiscal Adjustment in Advanced Economies'', the organization insisted that balanced public spending could stabilize [[bond market]]s, reduce interest rates from less government spending, and encourage private investment. It also recommended that emerging economies such as [[China]], which has largely benefited from trade surpluses, rely less on developed nations and increase their own spending in order to promote domestic demand.<ref name=\"declaration\">{{cite web |title=The G20 Toronto summit declaration |url=http://canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-declaration-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |publisher=Government of Canada |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=2012-03-27  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503090441/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-declaration-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |archivedate=3 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Financial costs ===\n[[File:DirectEnergyCentreLivingWall.jpg|thumb|$246,000 was spent on a Green wall for G20.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/living-wall-mass-casualty-kits-all-part-of-1-billion-tab-for-g8g20-summits/article1213892/ Living wall, 'mass casualty kits' all part of $1-billion tab for G8/G20 summits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305004209/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/living-wall-mass-casualty-kits-all-part-of-1-billion-tab-for-g8g20-summits/article1213892/ |date=2016-03-05 }}</ref>]]\nThe financial costs of hosting the [[36th G8 summit|G8]] and G20 summits was the topic of several political debates and the target of criticism by local groups.<ref name=\"rider\">{{cite news| author=David Rider| title=Toronto warns Ottawa on G20 costs| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/769614--toronto-warns-ottawa-on-g20-costs| work=Toronto Star| date=22 February 2010| publisher=thestar.com| accessdate=2012-03-30| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021153957/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/769614--toronto-warns-ottawa-on-g20-costs| archivedate=21 October 2012}}</ref> The reasons for the large price for both summits were questioned by some politicians and local groups. Members of Parliament [[Olivia Chow]] and [[Mark Holland]] labelled the initially claimed budget of $1.1-billion for hosting the summits as \"obscene\" and \"insane\" while others argued that the money could have been used for long-pending municipal projects in Canada,<ref name=\"security\">{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/?s_name=&no_ads=| title=Security chief defends high cost of G8-G20 summits| publisher=CTV.ca| date=28 May 2010| accessdate=2012-03-30| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609185308/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/?s_name=&no_ads=| archivedate=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"sufrin\">{{cite news|author=Jon Sufrin |url=http://www.torontolife.com/daily/informer/summit-survivor/2010/05/26/833-million-security-bill-for-g20-and-g8-called-insane/ |title=$833-million security bill for G20 and G8 called 'insane' |work=[[Toronto Life]] |date=26 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-04-01 |publisher=torontolife.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227045544/http://www.torontolife.com/daily/informer/summit-survivor/2010/05/26/833-million-security-bill-for-g20-and-g8-called-insane/ |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref> such as [[Transit City]].<ref name=\"pate\">{{cite news| author=Stephen Pate| url=http://www.oyetimes.com/views/columns/3186-1-billion-price-tag-for-g20-security-and-climbing| title=$1 billion price tag for G20 security and climbing| work=Oye! Times| publisher=oyetimes.com| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-01| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226215954/http://www.oyetimes.com/views/columns/3186-1-billion-price-tag-for-g20-security-and-climbing| archivedate=26 February 2012}}</ref> The security cost for the two summits was believed to be more expensive than the combined security costs of the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] and [[2010 Winter Paralympics|Paralympics]] in [[Vancouver]] and [[Whistler, British Columbia]], which were {{Nowrap|$878 million}}.<ref name=\"sufrin\"/>  However, according to final calculations from the [[House of Commons of Canada]] as of October 2010, the exact cost for holding both summits was $857,901,850.31, making it less expensive than the security costs for the 2010 Winter Olympics.<ref name=\"final\"/>\n\nIt was initially claimed that the summits stand as the most expensive ever held, with security costs for the [[2009 G20 London summit|London]] and [[2009 G20 Pittsburgh summit|Pittsburgh]] reported as having been only {{Nowrap|$30 million}} and {{Nowrap|$18 million}}, respectively.<ref name=\"security\"/>  However, the Canadian [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]], [[Kevin Page]], stated in his official report on the costs of the Huntsville and Toronto gatherings that other countries had not been as open about the full price for the similar meetings held there and that the {{Nowrap|$18 million}} figure for the Pittsburgh summit was merely for overtime pay for local police and the cost of law enforcement brought from other regions.<ref name=\"tibbetts\">{{cite news| author=Janice Tibbetts| title=Tories 'transparent' on security costs: Watchdog| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Federal+government+transparent+summit+security+costs+Watchdog/3192674/story.html| publisher=canada.com| work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]| agency=[[Canwest]] News Service| date=23 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-05| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517034458/http://www.canada.com/news/Federal+government+transparent+summit+security+costs+Watchdog/3192674/story.html| archivedate=17 May 2012}}</ref>  [[Ward Elcock]], former [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service]] director and the chief of the [[Integrated Security Unit]]s for the Winter Olympics and the G8/G20 summits, claimed that the security costs were in fact \"comparable\" with those of previous summits.<ref name=\"security\"/> Finance minister [[Jim Flaherty]] defended the security cost, claiming \"it's necessary to spend substantially to have security. It's Canada's turn, and it's necessary that we either don't take our turn or pay the appropriate price to have the security that is necessary so that everyone is safe here in Toronto.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100607/flaherty_cost_100607/20100607/?hub=WinnipegHome |title=Financial reform taking too long: Flaherty |work=CTV News |publisher=CTV.ca |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224080622/http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100607/flaherty_cost_100607/20100607/?hub=WinnipegHome |archivedate=24 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe creation of the $23-million international media centre, which included the {{Nowrap|$1.9 million}} ''Experience Canada'' pavilion and $57,000 artificial lake, at the [[Exhibition Place]] was widely opposed and criticized by politicians as \"a waste of taxpayers' money.\"<ref name=\"loon\">{{cite web |url=http://looncanada.wordpress.com/2010/06/08/g20-summit-fake-lake-has-canadian-taxpayers-in-stitches/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611084935/http://looncanada.wordpress.com/2010/06/08/g20-summit-fake-lake-has-canadian-taxpayers-in-stitches/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2010 |title=G20 summit's $2 million \"fake lake\" has Canadian taxpayers in stitches |work=Loon |location=Canada |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 }}</ref> Criticism mainly targeted Stephen Harper and Canada's [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative government]]. Some protesting groups gave names to the artificial lake, such as \"Harper's Folly\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20100607/g20-security-cost-100607/ | title=Tories say artificial lake will help 'showcase Canada' | publisher=CTV.ca | work=CTV News | date=7 June 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-28 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119025822/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20100607/g20-security-cost-100607/ | archivedate=19 January 2012 }}</ref> In a debate in the House of Commons, member Mark Holland said, \"Instead of hosting world leaders, maybe the government should consider party planning for [[Lady Gaga]].\"<ref name=\"weese\">{{cite news| url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/canada/2010/06/07/14291091.html| title='Fake lake' flak dogs PM| publisher=Torontosun.com| work=Toronto Sun| date=7 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-28| author=Bryn Weese| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125223638/http://www.torontosun.com/news/canada/2010/06/07/14291091.html| archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref> According to some critics, the spending misled the objective of the summits into showing off Canada's attributes instead of promoting the summits' agendas.<ref name=\"taber\">{{cite news| title=Tories pilloried for fake lake at G8/G20 media centre |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-pilloried-for-fake-lake-at-g8g20-media-centre/article1595348/ |publisher=theglobeandmail.com| work=The Globe and Mail| author=Jane Taber |date=7 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-28 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100915141804/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-pilloried-for-fake-lake-at-g8g20-media-centre/article1595348/| archivedate= 15 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] leader [[Jack Layton]] condemned the Harper government, saying, \"we've got a government here that has to create an artificial lake when Canada has more lakes than just about any other country in the world. It is the taxpayers who are going to end up at the bottom of the fake lake.\" Transport minister [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]] defended the artificial lake, saying that the summits gave a \"chance to showcase the very best that [Canada] has to offer.\" Foreign affairs minister [[Lawrence Cannon]] said it was \"normal practice\" for a country to showcase its attributes while hosting world events.<ref name=\"taber\"/> Harper also defended by saying, \"This is a classic attempt for us to be able to market the country.\"<ref name=\"akin\">{{cite news | title=Ottawa defends $1.9-million taste of Muskoka at G20 media centre | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-defends-19-million-taste-of-muskoka-at-g20-media-centre/article1595709/ | publisher=theglobeandmail.com | work=The Globe and Mail | date=7 June 2010 | author=Siri Agrell | accessdate=2012-03-28 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126044809/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-defends-19-million-taste-of-muskoka-at-g20-media-centre/article1595709/ | archivedate=26 January 2011 }}</ref> Upon its opening, the artificial lake received mostly negative reviews from Canadian reporters.<ref name=\"fakelake\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827453--g20-fake-lake-makes-its-debut |title=G20 'Fake Lake' makes its debut |publisher=thestar.com |work=Toronto Star |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |author=David Rider |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021154016/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827453--g20-fake-lake-makes-its-debut |archivedate=21 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Economic impact ===\nThe summit's economic impact was a major concern of a few local politicians and citizens. The [[City of Toronto government]], as well as some public representatives, previously argued that the G20 summit should be held at an isolated venue, such as the [[Exhibition Place]], rather than the Metro Toronto Convention Centre, which is located in the city's [[central business district]].<ref name=\"mclean3\">{{cite news| title=Lessons for G20 security from Vancouver Olympics| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/torontog20summit/article/820332--lessons-for-g20-security-from-vancouver-olympics|publisher=theStar.com| work=Toronto Star |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 | author=Jesse McLean}}</ref> As a result, during the aftermath of the protests during the summit, when several business and properties in Downtown Toronto were damaged, mayor [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] urged the federal government to compensate for all the damages. It was initially outlined by the government that only damages to businesses within the security zone would be compensated. However, all damages occurred outside of the security zone. Some businesses in the downtown core suffered financially as a result.<ref name=\"compensation\">{{cite news |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100629/toronto-riot-compensation-businesses-100629/20100629/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Advocates want compensation for T.O. businesses |publisher=CTV.ca |work=CTV News Toronto |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310051412/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100629/toronto-riot-compensation-businesses-100629/20100629/?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> According to Member of Parliament [[John McCallum]], \"Stephen Harper made a huge mistake in holding this summit in downtown Toronto.\" According to the ''Toronto Star'', at least 40 stores in the [[Downtown Yonge|Downtown Yonge Business Improvement Area]] suffered damages and one repair firm performed up to {{nowrap|$750,000}} in repairs.<ref name=\"ridder\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829912--pressure-builds-on-ottawa-for-compensation?bn=1 |title=Pressure builds on Ottawa for compensation |publisher=thestar.com |work=Toronto Star |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |author=David Rider and Susan Delacourt |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702011815/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829912--pressure-builds-on-ottawa-for-compensation?bn=1 |archivedate=2 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nOn June 17, the [[United States Department of State]] issued a travel alert for Toronto, warning tourists of the expected traffic disruptions and potentially violent protests during the G20 summit. The alert, which was expected to expire on the last day of the summit, stated that \"Even demonstrations that are meant to be peaceful can become violent and unpredictable.\"  Toronto Mayor [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] described the warning as an \"over-reaction.\"<ref name=\"usalert\">{{cite news| author=Jesse McLean| title=U.S. issues G20 travel alert for Toronto| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/824844--u-s-issues-g20-travel-alert-for-toronto?bn=1| work=Toronto Star| publisher=thestar.com| date=18 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418205124/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/824844--u-s-issues-g20-travel-alert-for-toronto?bn=1| archivedate=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summit, a few overseas reporters commented on Canada and the summits. A reporter of the [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC) made positive remarks about Canada's economy, saying \"The Canadians, it seems, have answers for even the toughest puzzles and they are keen to share their strategies with the rest of the world. Why in this economy, we all want to be Canadian.\" A writer in ''[[The New York Times]]'' made positive comments about the summits' preparations and natural beauty of the [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka]] region. ''[[The Times of India]]'' and ''[[The Hindu]]'' commented on impacts on city life in Toronto due to the G20 summit and the \"unprecedented\" security measures taken in Canada. A [[Reuters]] reporter, on the other hand, condemned the international media centre's artificial lake.<ref name=\"buzzing\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/100626_cost_g20/20100626/?hub=CP24Home| title=World media buzzing about cost of G20 security and fake lake| agency=The Canadian Press| date=26 June 2010| publisher=CP24| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305161433/http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/100626_cost_g20/20100626/?hub=CP24Home| archivedate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nLooking forward, French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] announced that the costs for hosting the proposed [[2011 G20 Cannes summit]] and [[37th G8 summit]] in France would be one-tenth of Canada's.<ref name=\"curry\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/sarkozy-says-his-g8g20-will-cost-one-tenth-of-canadas/article1619637/| title=Sarkozy says his G8/G20 will cost one-tenth of Canada's| work=The Globe and Mail| publisher=theglobeandmail.com| author=Bill Curry| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104113136/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/sarkozy-says-his-g8g20-will-cost-one-tenth-of-canadas/article1619637/| archivedate=4 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Economics|Canada}}\n* [[14th G7 summit]]\n* [[G20 Research Group]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|2010 G-20 Toronto summit}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=3}}\n\n{{G-20 leaders' summits}}\n{{2008 economic crisis}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:G-20 summit 2010 Toronto}}\n[[Category:G20 summits|2010 06 Toronto]]\n[[Category:2010 conferences]]\n[[Category:2010 in economics]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:History of Toronto]]\n[[Category:2010 in Toronto]]\n[[Category:June 2010 events in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{broader|G20}}\n{{Infobox summit\n| summit_name  = 2010 G20 Toronto summit\n| other_titles = \n| logo         = 2010 G-20 Toronto summit logo.svg\n| image        = Official photo session - 4763025214.jpg\n| caption      = \n| country      = Canada\n| venues       = [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]]\n| cities       = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| date         = June 26\u201327, 2010\n| precedes     = [[2010 G20 Seoul summit]]\n| follows      = [[2009 G20 Pittsburgh summit]]\n| website      = [http://canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=3&menu=L Official website]\n}}\nThe '''2010 G20 Toronto summit''' was the [[List of G20 summits|fourth meeting]] of the [[G20]] heads of state/government, to  discuss the [[global financial system]] and the [[world economy]], which took place at the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, during June 26\u201327, 2010. The summit's priorities included evaluating the progress of financial reform, developing sustainable stimulus measures,<ref>{{cite news| title=G-20 countries set deficit and debt-reducing goals| url=http://articles.marketwatch.com/2010-06-27/economy/30783027_1_g-20-deficit-debt-to-gdp-ratio| archive-url=https://archive.is/20130128111239/http://articles.marketwatch.com/2010-06-27/economy/30783027_1_g-20-deficit-debt-to-gdp-ratio| url-status=dead| archive-date=28 January 2013| author=Ronald D. Orol| date=27 June 2010| work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]| location=[[New York City]]| publisher=marketwatch.com| accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref> debating [[bank tax|global bank tax]],<ref name=\"background\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/background-summit-issues/article1547024/ |title=Background: Summit Issues |work=The Globe and Mail |publisher=theglobeandmail.com |date=April 28, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-20 |location=Toronto |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100711124423/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/background-summit-issues/article1547024/| archivedate= 11 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and promoting [[open market]]s.<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=3209 |title=Statement by the Prime Minister of Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |date=18 March 2010 |accessdate=2010-05-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420021101/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=3209 |archivedate=20 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Alongside the twenty-one representatives of the G20 major economies, leaders of six invited nations, and eight additional [[intergovernmental organization]]s also took part in the summit.\n\nPrior to the summit, [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] announced that the theme would be \"recovery and new beginnings,\" referring to an anticipated [[Stimulus (economics)|economic stimulus]] from the impact of the [[Great Recession|ongoing world recession]].<ref name=\"theme\">{{cite press release|title=PM announces participation of key leaders at the Toronto G-20 Summit this June |url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=3342 |date=8 May 2010 |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306065834/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=3342 |archivedate=6 March 2012 }}</ref> Harper initially proposed to hold the summit in [[Huntsville, Ontario]], where the [[36th G8 summit]] was scheduled immediately prior. Organizers later deemed the town insufficient to provide hospitality for the large number of G20 delegates and journalists, favouring Toronto as the host location.<ref name=washingtonexaminer1>{{cite news |author=Rob Gillies |title=Opposition miffed by $1 billion summit security |url=https://www.boston.com/news/world/canada/articles/2010/05/26/opposition_miffed_by_1_billion_summit_security/ |publisher=boston.com |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=26 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-04-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213121433/http://www.boston.com/news/world/canada/articles/2010/05/26/opposition_miffed_by_1_billion_summit_security/ |archivedate=13 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOrganizers formed an [[Integrated Security Unit]], consisting of police officers from several regional departments, to provide security during the summit in [[Downtown Toronto]].<ref name=\"tps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.torontopolice.on.ca/g20/ |title=G20 Toronto |publisher=Toronto Police Service |accessdate=2010-05-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701105703/http://www.torontopolice.on.ca/g20/ |archivedate=1 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The event was part of the largest and most expensive security operation in [[History of Canada|Canadian history]].<ref name=\"alcoba\">{{cite news|author=Alcoba, Natalie |url=http://mostlywater.org/g8g20_be_biggest_security_operation_canadian_history |work=[[National Post]] |title=G8/G20: Gearing up for the biggest security event in Canadian history |publisher=Mostly Water |date=25 February 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308000206/http://mostlywater.org/g8g20_be_biggest_security_operation_canadian_history |archivedate=8 March 2010 }}</ref> The total combined cost between the [[36th G8 summit]] in [[Huntsville, Ontario|Huntsville]] and the G20 summit in Toronto  including security, infrastructure, and hospitality, was determined to be approximately [[Canadian dollar|C$]]858 million.<ref name=\"final\">{{cite news| title=G8/G20 costs top $857M| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/g8-g20-costs-top-857m-1.915254| publisher=CBC.ca| work=CBC News| date=5 November 2010| accessdate=2012-04-01| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107005715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/g8-g20-costs-top-857m-1.915254| archivedate=7 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Agenda ==\nMany leaders of the G20 disagreed about which issues should be discussed at the summit.<ref name=\"wolverson\">{{cite web| author=Roya Wolverson| url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/22542/g20s_twenty_agendas.html?breadcrumb=%2Fpublication%2Fby_type%2Fbackgrounder| title=The G20's Twenty Agendas| publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]| date=24 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816181826/http://www.cfr.org/publication/22542/g20s_twenty_agendas.html?breadcrumb=%2Fpublication%2Fby_type%2Fbackgrounder| archivedate=16 August 2010}}</ref> The prime focus of the summit discussions was the recovery from the ongoing [[Great Recession|global recession]] and the [[European sovereign-debt crisis|European debt crisis]]. Summit leaders were divided over which strategies would be best for tackling these problems. The [[European Union]] emphasized the need to cut their deficits by focusing on [[austerity]] measures.  In contrast, the [[United States]] emphasized the importance of maintaining [[Stimulus (economics)|economic stimulus]] spending in order to encourage growth.<ref name=\"tops\">{{cite news| url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/2010/06/2010627114252622620.html| title=Recession recovery tops G20 agenda| publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]| place=[[Qatar]]| date=28 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-06| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205064133/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/2010/06/2010627114252622620.html| archivedate=5 February 2011}}</ref> In summit discussions, the countries of the European Union explained projected reductions in spending and balanced budgets.  Alternatively, [[People's Republic of China|China]], India, and the United States argued in favor of increased stimulus funding to mitigate the effects of recession. Among the specifics proposed by the European Union were a global [[bank tax]] and a [[Robin Hood tax]], but the United States and [[Canada]] opposed these plans.<ref name=\"davies\">{{cite news| author=Rhodri Davies| url=http://english.aljazeera.net/focus/2010/06/201062571713780493.html| title=G20:Battles within and outside| publisher=Al Jazeera| place=Qatar| date=26 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-06| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205064503/http://english.aljazeera.net/focus/2010/06/201062571713780493.html| archivedate=5 February 2011}}</ref> Other topics of concern were [[international development]] and continuing [[international aid]] to [[Africa]] and other developing nations.<ref>{{cite news| title=Forgotten Goals| url=http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/insidestory/2010/06/2010624125511683950.html| publisher=Al Jazeera| location=Qatar| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-06| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223232112/http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/insidestory/2010/06/2010624125511683950.html| archivedate=23 December 2010}}</ref>  Some invitees expressed criticism of [[Israel]]'s [[Blockade of the Gaza Strip|Gaza strip blockade]] and of the nuclear programs of [[North Korea]] and the United States raised issues of corruption and security in [[Afghanistan]].\n\n== Preparations ==\n{{Main|2010 G20 Toronto summit preparations}}\n\n=== Security ===\n[[File:Fences Are Up Toronto 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Security fencing erected along the middle of Wellington Street]]\nSecurity officials began preparing for summit security in Toronto in February 2010.<ref name=\"prepare\">{{cite news| title=G20 police didn't have time to prepare: chief| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2011/06/24/g20-police-union-report652.html| date=24 June 2010| work=CBC News| publisher=CBC.ca| accessdate=2012-04-07| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323090701/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2011/06/24/g20-police-union-report652.html| archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref> General policing and patrolling was provided by the [[Toronto Police Service]], the [[Ontario Provincial Police]], the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], and the [[Canadian Forces]], while the [[Peel Regional Police]] aided in policing at [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] in [[Mississauga]] during the arrivals of delegates. The five departments formed an [[Integrated Security Unit]] (ISU), similar to the one created for the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]]. Additional officers were deployed from [[York Regional Police]], [[Halton Regional Police Service]],<ref name=\"home\">{{cite news | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/22/peter-kuitenbrouwer-downtown-doesnt-feel-like-home-during-g20/ | author=Peter Kuitenbrouwer | title=Downtown doesn't feel like home during G20 | work=National Post | publisher=nationalpost.com | date=22 June 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-27 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120703180037/http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/22/peter-kuitenbrouwer-downtown-doesnt-feel-like-home-during-g20/ | archivedate=3 July 2012 }}</ref> [[Barrie Police Service]], [[Waterloo Regional Police Service]], [[Niagara Regional Police Service]], [[Hamilton Police Service]], [[Ottawa Police Service]],<ref name=\"skinner\">{{cite news|url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/article/839309--protesters-gather-at-allan-gardens-to-oppose-g20-summit |author=Justin Skinner |work=[[Toronto Star]] |title=Protesters gather at Allan Gardens to oppose G20 Summit |publisher=InsideToronto |date=25 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229170723/http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/article/839309--protesters-gather-at-allan-gardens-to-oppose-g20-summit |archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref> and [[Service de police de la Ville de Montr\u00e9al]]. [[Calgary Police Service]] supplied 150 volunteer police officers a week before the summit.<ref name=\"calgary\">{{cite news| author=Nadia Moharib| work=[[Calgary Sun]]| date=28 June 2010| url=http://www.calgarysun.com/news/alberta/2010/06/28/14548506.html| title=Calgary cops return home from G8/G20 duty| publisher=Calgarysun.com| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514075447/http://www.calgarysun.com/news/alberta/2010/06/28/14548506.html| archivedate=14 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an early estimate by ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 25,000 uniformed police officers, 1,000 security guards from [[Commissionaire]]s Great Lakes, and several Canadian military forces were to be deployed during the summit.<ref name=mondaq1>{{cite web| author=Mary Beth Currie| url=http://www.mondaq.com/canada/article.asp?articleid=99928 |title=Canada: Toronto G8 and G20 Summits \u2013 Employer Planning Issues |publisher=Mondaq.com |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100529210007/http://www.mondaq.com/canada/article.asp?articleid=99928| archivedate= 29 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[North American Aerospace Defense Command]] (NORAD) conducted [[Amalgam Virgo]] exercises on May 6 and 7 across the [[Greater Toronto Area]] using [[McDonnell Douglas CF-18 Hornet|CF-18 Hornet]] jets, [[CH-124 Sea King]]s, and [[CH-146 Griffon]] helicopters at low altitudes.<ref name=\"agrell1\">{{cite news| author=Siri Agrell |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/its-a-bird-its-a-plane-its-a-terrifying-display-of-military-might/article1558886/ |title=It's a bird, it's a plane, it's a terrifying display of military might |publisher=theglobeandmail.com| work=The Globe and Mail |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100511031943/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/its-a-bird-its-a-plane-its-a-terrifying-display-of-military-might/article1558886/| archivedate= 11 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The total cost for security at both the G8 and the G20 summits was determined to be {{Nowrap|$1.8 billion<!--THIS IS ONLY THE ESTIMATE THAT WAS GIVEN BEFORE THE SUMMIT. DO NOT CHANGE TO THE ACTUAL VALUE THAT WAS CALCULATED AFTER THE SUMMIT. SEE THE REFERENCE.-->}},<ref name=\"delacourt\">{{cite news| author=Susan Delacourt |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/816123--what-can-1-billion-buy?bn=1 |title=G20 security tab: What else could $1B buy? |publisher=thestar.com |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-20 | work=Toronto Star| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100601080201/http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/816123--what-can-1-billion-buy?bn=1| archivedate= 1 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> paid entirely by the [[Government of Canada|federal Crown]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]], excluding the costs of any possible damage to local business.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/20100528/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Security chief defends high cost of G8-G20 summits| publisher=CTV News| date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-04| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100530062200/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/20100528/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 30 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe ISU created a security perimeter, beginning with the outer boundary, specifically bordered by [[King Street (Toronto)|King Street]] to the north, [[Lake Shore Boulevard]] to the south, [[Yonge Street]] to the east, and [[Spadina Avenue]] to the west, where vehicles would be restricted during the summit dates.<ref name=\"mondaq1\"/> Residents who lived within the security zone were issued registration cards prior to the summit and other pedestrians who wished to enter the security zone were only able to do so at one of 38 checkpoints, where they were required to present two pieces of [[photo identification]] and provide justification for entry.<ref name=thestar2>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/825713--g20-survival-guide |title=G20 survival guide |publisher=thestar.com |date=18 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-20 |work=Toronto Star |author=Noor Javed |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100621072034/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/825713--g20-survival-guide |archivedate= 21 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The area surrounding the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] itself was fenced and off-limits to civilians and protesters.<ref name=\"fence1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/local/article/823021--g20-traffic-and-perimeter-plans-unveiled |title=G20 traffic and perimeter plans unveiled |work=Inside Toronto |publisher=insidetoronto.com |author=Joanna Lavoie |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610233601/http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/local/article/823021--g20-traffic-and-perimeter-plans-unveiled |archivedate=10 June 2010 }}</ref> The {{convert|3|m|ft|0|adj=on}} high fence, contracted to [[SNC-Lavalin]] by [[Public Works and Government Services Canada]] and installed by two [[Gormley, Ontario]]-based companies,<ref name=\"ormsby\">{{cite news|author=Mary Ormsby |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/825908--fortress-toronto-secrets-of-the-fence |title=Fortress Toronto: Secrets of the fence |publisher=thestar.com |date=19 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623014659/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/825908--fortress-toronto-secrets-of-the-fence |archivedate=23 June 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> was built at a cost of {{Nowrap|$5.5-million}} and installation began on June 7.<ref name=\"wallace\">{{cite news| author=Kenyon Wallace| url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/10/g20-torontos-controversial-security-fence-cost-5-5-million/ |title=G20: Toronto's controversial security fence cost $5.5-million |work=National Post |publisher=nationalpost.com |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://archive.is/20100613000602/http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/10/g20-torontos-controversial-security-fence-cost-5-5-million/| archivedate= 13 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The Toronto Police Service installed 77 additional [[closed-circuit television]] security cameras in the area and purchased four [[Long Range Acoustic Device]]s which were to be in use exclusively during the summit.<ref name=\"global\">{{cite web |url=http://www.globalnational.com/Toronto+Police+sound+security+tools/3108050/story.html |title=Police sound off on G20 security tools |publisher=Globalnational.com |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727114848/http://www.globalnational.com/Toronto+Police+sound+security+tools/3108050/story.html |archivedate=27 July 2011 }}</ref> The ISU decided on also using [[water cannon]]s for [[riot control]].<ref name=\"mclean1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826245--police-add-water-cannon-to-g20-arsenal?bn=1 |title=Police add water cannon to G20 arsenal |publisher=thestar.com |date= 21 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-24 | work=Toronto Star | author=Jesse McLean| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625002916/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826245--police-add-water-cannon-to-g20-arsenal?bn=1| archivedate= 25 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThe security perimeter even extended into the waters of Lake Ontario and included a Maritime Security Operation with numerous Police vessels and the [[Canadian Coast Guard]] Ship Griffon patrolling to discourage international demonstrators from unlawful entry into Canada.\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nA former film studio located on [[Eastern Avenue (Toronto)|Eastern Avenue]] was designated as a temporary detention centre for individuals arrested during the summit.<ref name=\"protesters prepare\">{{cite web |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/G20-Protest-100511/20100511/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Protesters prepare for G20 demonstrations |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |work=CTV Toronto |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310050941/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/G20-Protest-100511/20100511/?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> Toronto Police Service announced that [[Trinity Bellwoods Park]] would be the designated protest area, but following opposition from local residents, police relocated the designated protest zone to the northern part of [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]].<ref name=\"queenspark\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/100511_protest/20100511/?hub=CP24Home |title=Police chief reconfirms that Queen's Park will be designated protest area during G20 |publisher=CP24 |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305161148/http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/100511_protest/20100511/?hub=CP24Home |archivedate=5 March 2012 }}</ref> [[Canada Post]] declared that it would remove post boxes in the security zone.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news |author=Siri Agrell |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/keep-those-cards-and-letters-coming/article1555282/ |title=Keep those cards and letters coming&nbsp;... |work=The Globe and Mail |publisher=theglobeandmail.com |date=4 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |location=Toronto |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022075721/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/keep-those-cards-and-letters-coming/article1555282/ |archivedate=22 October 2012 }}</ref> [[Toronto Parking Authority]] removed some parking meters as well. Small trees along sidewalks around the convention centre were removed to prevent them from being used as weapons by protesters.<ref name=\"trees\">{{cite news|url=http://www.680news.com/news/local/article/67011--trees-could-be-removed-around-metro-convention-centre-for-summit |title=Trees could be removed around Metro Toronto Convention Centre for summit |work=[[CFTR (AM)]] |publisher=680News |author=Collin D'Mello |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307155812/http://www.680news.com/news/local/article/67011--trees-could-be-removed-around-metro-convention-centre-for-summit |archivedate=7 March 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"toofar\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/06/g20-is-security-going-too-far.html | title=G20: Is security going too far? | publisher=Cbc.ca | date=17 June 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-27 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811053053/http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/06/g20-is-security-going-too-far.html | archivedate=11 August 2010 }}</ref> Other removed municipal properties include 745 newspaper boxes, 200 public trash cans, 70 mailboxes, 29 bus shelters, and 5 public information boards.<ref name=\"fortress\">{{cite news| url=http://nationalpostnews.files.wordpress.com/2010/06/g20-fortress-new.jpg| title=Fortress Toronto| work=National Post| date=18 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307122445/http://nationalpostnews.files.wordpress.com/2010/06/g20-fortress-new.jpg| archivedate=7 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:G-20 Toronto June 2010 (1).jpg|thumb|left|Shops near [[King (TTC)|King]] [[Toronto subway|subway station]] boarded up windows to prevent vandalism from protests]]\n[[Big Five (banks)|Canada's largest banks]], which are headquartered in Downtown Toronto, made plans to have employees work at alternate sites outside their downtown facilities, such as at home or in other branches.<ref name=\"blackwell\">{{cite news| author=Richard Blackwell |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/banks-make-plans-for-employees-to-work-off-site-during-g20/article1562639/ |title=Banks make plans for employees to work off-site during G20 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=9 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100513191326/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/banks-make-plans-for-employees-to-work-off-site-during-g20/article1562639/| archivedate= 13 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Liquor Control Board of Ontario]] (LCBO) announced the closure of seven [[liquor store]]s in the downtown core during the summit as a precaution to looting.<ref name=toronto1>{{cite web| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100621/lcbo_shut_down_100621/20100621/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Police ride herd as G20 protesters march the streets |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=29 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100624024104/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100621/lcbo_shut_down_100621/20100621/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 24 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]],<ref name=thestar2 /> [[CN Tower]],<ref name=\"CNtower\">{{cite web | url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100519/G20-shuts-CNTower-100519/20100519/?hub=TorontoNewHome | title=Amid G20 security concerns, CN Tower to be shut | work=CTV News | publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca | date=16 May 2010 | accessdate=2010-05-20 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521173059/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100519/G20-shuts-CNTower-100519/20100519/?hub=TorontoNewHome | archivedate=21 May 2010 }}</ref> [[University of Toronto]],<ref name=\"UofT\">{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100524/G20-Shuts-UofT-100524/20100524/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=U of T to shut down during G20 Summit| work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=24 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100530051700/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100524/G20-Shuts-UofT-100524/20100524/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 30 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Art Gallery of Ontario]],<ref name=\"ago\">{{cite news| title=AGO  to close for G20 weekend| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2010/06/07/g20-ago-closing.html| publisher=CBC.ca| work=CBC News| date=7 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512112828/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2010/06/07/g20-ago-closing.html| archivedate=12 May 2012}}</ref> and the [[Ontario Legislative Building]]<ref name=\"legislature\">{{cite news| author=Rob Ferguson |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/818484 |title=Legislature closing for G20 summit |publisher=thestar.com |work=Toronto Star |date=3 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605071109/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/818484| archivedate=5 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> were also closed to public during the summit dates.\n\nA three-game [[Major League Baseball]] series between the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] and the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], scheduled June 25 to 27 at the [[Rogers Centre]], was relocated to [[Citizens Bank Park]] in [[Philadelphia]], after much discussion by league officials and amidst discontentment from fans, who highly anticipated the return of former Blue Jays pitcher [[Roy Halladay]] to Toronto after being traded to the Phillies;<ref name=thestar1>{{cite news| author=Mark Zwolinski| url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/article/807716--g20-summit-scuppers-halladay-s-first-trip-to-toronto-as-a-phillie |title=G20 summit scuppers Halladay's first trip to Toronto as a Philly| work=Toronto Star| publisher=thestar.com| date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100514101920/http://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/article/807716--g20-summit-scuppers-halladay-s-first-trip-to-toronto-as-a-phillie| archivedate= 14 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/12/sports/baseball/12bats.html?scp=1&sq=toronto&st=cse |title=Halladay's Return To Toronto Is Rerouted to Philadelphia |publisher=NYTimes.com |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-05-11 |accessdate=2010-05-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406110030/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/12/sports/baseball/12bats.html?scp=1&sq=toronto&st=cse |archivedate=2012-04-06 }}</ref><ref name=theglobeandmail2>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/baseball/jays---phillies-series-moving-to-philadelphia/article1564925/ |title=Jays-Phillies series moving to Philadelphia |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=2010-05-11 |accessdate=2010-05-20 |location=Toronto |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514124128/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/baseball/jays---phillies-series-moving-to-philadelphia/article1564925/ |archivedate=14 May 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> because the [[American League]] Blue Jays was still officially the \"home\" team, the series marked the first time in Major League history that the [[designated hitter]] was used in a [[National League]] ballpark during the regular season.  [[Mirvish Productions]] cancelled performances of two musicals at its theatres, ''[[Rock of Ages (musical)#2010 Toronto|Rock of Ages]]'' and ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'', during the week of the summit.<ref name=\"mirvish\">{{cite news|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/140550-G20-Summit-Forces-Cancellation-of-Toronto-Mamma-Mia-and-Rock-of-Ages-Performances |title=G20 Summit Forces Cancellation of Toronto Mamma Mia! and Rock of Ages Performances |author=Adam Hetrick |work=[[Playbill]] |date=18 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825032320/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/140550-G20-Summit-Forces-Cancellation-of-Toronto-Mamma-Mia-and-Rock-of-Ages-Performances |archivedate=25 August 2010 }}</ref> Similarly, the [[Factory Theatre]] cancelled shows during the summit week.<ref name=\"jam\">{{cite web |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Theatre/2010/06/05/14274891.html |author=John Coulbourne |title=G20 summit dims Toronto musicals |publisher=Jam.canoe.ca |date=4 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120630124732/http://jam.canoe.ca/Theatre/2010/06/05/14274891.html |archivedate=30 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Ontario Highway 427|Highway 427]] and the [[Gardiner Expressway]], the route from [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] in [[Mississauga]] to the Convention Centre in downtown, periodically closed down for motorcades, and police [[wireless signal jammer|jammed]] wireless reception along the two highways.<ref name=\"cell\">{{cite news|agency=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.680news.com/g20/article/64725--g8-g20-wireless-signal-blockers-unlikely-to-leave-cell-phone-users-in-a-jam |title=G8-G20 wireless signal blockers unlikely to leave cell phone users in a jam |work=CFTR (AM) |publisher=680News |date=2010-06-09 |accessdate=2010-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716052140/http://www.680news.com/g20/article/64725--g8-g20-wireless-signal-blockers-unlikely-to-leave-cell-phone-users-in-a-jam |archivedate=2011-07-16 }}</ref> Exits to [[Yonge Street]] and [[Bay Street]] from the Gardiner Expressway were closed during the summit dates.<ref name=thestar2 /> [[Toronto Transit Commission]] announced that [[List of Toronto subway stations|subway stations]] near the convention centre would remain open and operational, despite some detoured [[Toronto Transit Commission buses|bus]] routes and the closure of [[Queens Quay (TTC)|Queens Quay Station]].<ref name=\"TTC\">{{cite news| author=Don Peat| url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/05/28/14179256.html| title=G20 should cause only token disruption of TTC| date=28 May 2010| work=[[Toronto Sun]]| publisher=torontosun.com| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126173045/http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/05/28/14179256.html| archivedate=26 January 2012}}</ref> [[Via Rail]] announced that it would not operate at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] during the summit dates,<ref name=\"via\">{{cite news |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100603/via-rail-g20-100603/20100603/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Via Rail to close at Union Station during G20 |agency=Canadian Press |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=26 July 2009 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310051213/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100603/via-rail-g20-100603/20100603/?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> instead providing [[shuttle bus service]] from the [[Yorkdale Bus Terminal|Yorkdale]] and [[Scarborough Centre Bus Terminal|Scarborough Centre]] bus terminals to the [[Brampton GO Station|Brampton]] and [[Oshawa GO Station|Oshawa]] stations respectively.<ref name=thestar2/> [[Nav Canada]] announced that it would place restrictions on the airspace in Toronto, making it limited to commercial flights only while all others would be restricted within a {{convert|30|nmi|km|0|adj=on}} radius.<ref name=\"airspace\">{{cite news |url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/06/09/14326041.html |title=Fighter jets on alert during G20 |author=Tom Godfrey |work=Toronto Sun |publisher=torontosun.com |date=9 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604140328/http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/06/09/14326041.html |archivedate=4 June 2012 }}</ref> [[Porter Airlines]] received permission to continue flights to and from [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport]].<ref name=\"porter\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/business-as-usual-for-porter/article1557544/ |title=Business as usual for Porter? |work=The Globe and Mail |publisher=theglobeandmail |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100511055654/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/business-as-usual-for-porter/article1557544/| archivedate= 11 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Toronto District School Board]] and [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]] cancelled school bus services to six Downtown schools on June 25, affecting 45,000 students, 10,000 of whom were physically disabled.<ref name=\"schools\">{{cite news |agency=The Canadian Press |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/g20-forces-toronto-school-bus-cancellations-1.940659 |title=G20 forces Toronto school bus cancellations |work=CBC News |publisher=cbc.ca |date=18 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512113319/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/g20-forces-toronto-school-bus-cancellations-1.940659 |archivedate=12 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSummit organizers established a media centre for international media personnel, journalists, and press reporters at the Direct Energy Centre at the [[Exhibition Place]].<ref name=\"media\">{{cite web |url=http://g20.gc.ca/for-media/media-centre/ |title=Media Centre |publisher=G20.gc.ca |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-04-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531073457/http://g20.gc.ca/for-media/media-centre/ |archivedate=31 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The Federal and Ontario governments constructed a {{convert|20000|sqft|m2|0|adj=on}} pavilion, called ''Experience Canada'' or ''Canadian Corridor'' in the media centre to promote Canadian tourism internationally.<ref name=\"worth\">{{cite news| url=http://ottawa.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100613/g8-g20-costs-100613/20100613/?hub=OttawaHome |title=G8/G20 organizer says marketing Canada worth cost |work=CTV News |publisher=Ottawa.ctv.ca |date=13 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616014146/http://ottawa.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100613/g8-g20-costs-100613/20100613/?hub=OttawaHome| archivedate=16 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The pavilion included three life-sized government-funded displays: ''Cityscape'', which showcased successful Canadian businesses and innovation; ''The Bridge'', which included information kiosks for media personnel as well as large high-definition screens that televised the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] games; and ''Northern Ontario Oasis'', an artificial lakefront based on [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka region's]] [[cottage country]].<ref name=\"muskoka\">{{cite news| title=G20 media centre with fake lake to cost $1.9 million| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/torontog20summit/article/819841--g20-media-centre-with-fake-lake-to-cost-1-9m| work=Toronto Star| agency=The Canadian Press| publisher=thestar.com| date=10 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"corporate\">{{cite news|author=Siri Agrell |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-steered-clear-of-corporate-sponsorships-for-g8-g20/article1608401/ |title=Ottawa steered clear of corporate sponsorships for G8-G20 |publisher=theglobeandmail.com |work=The Globe and Mail |date=17 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27 |location=Toronto| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100620000221/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-steered-clear-of-corporate-sponsorships-for-g8-g20/article1608401/| archivedate=20 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The ''Northern Ontario Oasis'' included donated canoes, a shoreline with deck chairs for journalists to cool off, and a [[mobile phone]] recharging station.  The background was a large screen that portrayed various images of the Muskoka region.<ref name=\"thestar3\">{{cite news |author=Heather Scoffield |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/g8/article/820057--fake-lake-part-of-1-9m-g20-g8-toronto-media-centre?bn=1 |title=Fake lake part of $1.9M G20/G8 Toronto media centre |work=Toronto Star |publisher=thestar.com |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419021253/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/g8/article/820057--fake-lake-part-of-1-9m-g20-g8-toronto-media-centre?bn=1 |archivedate=19 April 2012 }}</ref> The cost of the international media centre, the ''Experience Canada'' pavilion, and artificial lake, which were {{Nowrap|$23 million}}, {{Nowrap|$1.9 million}}, and $57,000 respectively, was the target of [[#Controversies|controversies]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/06/08/g20-fakelake-costs.html |work=CBC News |title=PM defends G8 fake lake pavilion |publisher=cbc.ca |date=8 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100611053655/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/06/08/g20-fakelake-costs.html| archivedate=11 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Attendance ==\n[[File:Group photo of the 2010 G-20 Toronto summit family photo.jpg|thumb|right|Leaders pose for a group photo at the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]]]]\nParticipants of the Toronto summit were announced by [[Stephen Harper]] on May 8, 2010. Harper extended invitations to the leaders of [[Ethiopia]] and [[Malawi]] to further represent the continent of Africa along with [[South Africa]], a G20 member.<ref name=\"malawi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsudanvision.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2127:canadian-prime-minister-invites-malawi-ethiopia-for-g20-summit-in-toronto&catid=3:international&Itemid=10 |title=Canadian Prime Minister invites Malawi, Ethiopia, for G20 summit in Toronto |publisher=New Sudan Vision |date=10 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929205300/http://newsudanvision.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2127%3Acanadian-prime-minister-invites-malawi-ethiopia-for-g20-summit-in-toronto&catid=3%3Ainternational&Itemid=10 |archivedate=29 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He also invited leaders of the [[Netherlands]], [[Spain]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Nigeria]].<ref name=punchng1>{{cite web| url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/africa/offor-decapua-nigeria-g8-23jun10-96975959.html| title=G8 Invites 7 African Countries to Muskoka| publisher=[[Voice of America]]| date=23 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223204828/http://www.voanews.com/english/news/africa/offor-decapua-nigeria-g8-23jun10-96975959.html| archivedate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] was the [[port of entry]] for delegates attending both the G8 and G20 summits. French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] and Chinese president [[Hu Jintao]] were the first of the G20 leaders to arrive. The arrival of Hu coincided with his [[state visit]] to Canada, hosted by Governor General of Canada [[Micha\u00eblle Jean]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"hu\">{{cite  news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/823204--chinese-president-to-make-extended-visit-to-canada |title=Chinese president to make extended visit to Canada| author=Tonda MacCharles| work=Toronto Star| publisher=thestar.com |date=14 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27}}</ref> Presidents [[Jacob Zuma]] of South Africa and [[Goodluck Jonathan]] of Nigeria arrived on June 24.<ref name=\"leaders_begin\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827910--leaders-begin-arriving-for-g8-g20?bn=1| title=Leaders begin arriving for G8, G20| work=Toronto Star| publisher=thestar.com| date=24 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024105429/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827910--leaders-begin-arriving-for-g8-g20?bn=1| archivedate=24 October 2012}}</ref> British prime minister [[David Cameron]] arrived on June 25, following a short visit in [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] to celebrate the centennial of the [[Canadian Forces Maritime Command]]. Remaining leaders with the G8 also arrived on the same day.<ref name=toronto2/>\n\nThe [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and the [[International Labour Organization]], as well as Ethiopia, Malawi, Nigeria, and Vietnam made their first G20 summit appearances in Toronto.<ref name=\"theme\"/>  Recently designated heads of government, namely Cameron and Japanese prime minister [[Naoto Kan]], made the [[36th G8 summit|G8]] and G20 summits their first international [[diplomatic conference|conferences]]. Australia's deputy prime minister, [[Wayne Swan]], attended the summit on behalf of [[Julia Gillard]], whose appointment as prime minister occurred on June 24.<ref name=\"toronto2\">{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100624/g8-g20-leaders-arrive-100624/20100624/?hub=TorontoNewHome|title=Leaders arrive in Canada ahead of G8/G20 summits|work=CTV News|publisher=CTV.ca|date=24 June 2010|accessdate=2012-03-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310051224/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100624/g8-g20-leaders-arrive-100624/20100624/?hub=TorontoNewHome|archivedate=10 March 2012}}</ref> Brazilian president [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] cancelled his trip to remain in his country due to [[2010 northeastern Brazil floods|the then-recent flooding in northeastern Brazil]]; in his place, [[Guido Mantega]], Brazil's finance minister, headed the nation's delegation.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news| author=Iuri Dantas| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-25/lula-will-skip-g-20-summit-to-oversee-brazil-flood-relief-official-says.html| title=Lula Will Skip G-20 Summit to Oversee Brazil Flood Relief, Official Says| publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]| date=25 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-27| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410065844/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-25/lula-will-skip-g-20-summit-to-oversee-brazil-flood-relief-official-says.html| archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> After the G8 summit in [[Huntsville, Ontario]] ended, Cameron, whose aircraft was grounded due to weather conditions, shared transportation to Toronto in [[Marine One]] with US President, [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"wardell\">{{cite news| url=https://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2010/06/28/britains_cameron_bolsters_reputation_at_summits/| title=Britain's Cameron bolsters reputation at summits| work=The Boston Globe| publisher=boston.com| date=28 June 2010| accessdate=2010-09-28| author=Jane Wardell| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217124711/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2010/06/28/britains_cameron_bolsters_reputation_at_summits/| archivedate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Obama and Cameron in Toronto 2010.jpg|thumb|[[Barack Obama]] (right) and [[David Cameron]] (centre) arrive after travelling together on [[Marine One]] from [[Huntsville, Ontario|Huntsville]]]]\n[[File:Medvedev Merkel Sarkozy at Toronto G20.jpg|thumb|[[Dmitry Medvedev]] shaking hands with [[Angela Merkel]] and [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|{{unbulleted list|'''G20 members'''|{{small|Host nation and leader are indicated in bold text}}}}\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=2 | Member\n! Represented by\n! Title\n|-\n\n! {{flagicon|ARG}}\n| [[Argentina]]\n| [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]]<ref name=\"campanario\">{{cite news| author=Sebasti\u00e1n Campanario| language=Spanish| url=http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2010/6/26/politica-498796.asp| title=Cristina dir\u00e1 ante las potencias que no hay una sola salida para la crisis| work=[[Los Andes (Argentine newspaper)|Los Andes]]| date=26 June 2010| publisher=losandes.com.ar| accessdate=2011-04-06| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609073549/http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2010/6/26/politica-498796.asp| archivedate=9 June 2011}}</ref>\n| [[President of Argentina|President]]\n|-\n! {{flagicon|AUS}}\n| [[Australia]]\n| [[Wayne Swan]]<ref name=\"sydney\">{{cite news| author=Sandra O'Malley| url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/swan-to-take-international-stage-at-g20-20100626-zahn.html| title=Swa