12}}</ref>\n| Director-General\n|-\n!\n| [[International Monetary Fund]]\n| [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]]<ref name=\"gubert\"/>\n| Managing Director\n|-\n!\n| [[New Partnership for Africa's Development|NEPAD]]\n| [[Meles Zenawi]]<ref name=\"macleans_arrive\"/>\n| Chairman\n|-\n!\n| [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]]\n| [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Gurr\u00eda]]<ref name=\"simon\">{{cite journal| title=Angel Gurr\u00eda, OECD Secretary-General (CV)| publisher=OCED}}</ref>\n| Secretary General\n|-\n! {{flagicon|United Nations}}\n| [[United Nations]]\n| [[Ban Ki-moon]]<ref name=\"ward\">{{cite news| author=Olivia Ward| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/829237--ban-ki-moon-at-g20-as-defender-of-the-defenceless| title=Ban Ki-moon at G20 as 'defender of the defenceless'| work=Toronto Star| date=26 June 2010| publisher=thestar.com| accessdate=2012-03-26| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021153922/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/829237--ban-ki-moon-at-g20-as-defender-of-the-defenceless| archivedate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n| [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General]]\n|-\n!\n| [[World Bank Group]]\n| [[Robert Zoellick]]<ref name=\"simon\"/>\n| President\n|-\n!\n| [[World Trade Organization]]\n| [[Pascal Lamy]]<ref name=\"gubert\"/>\n| Director-General\n|}\n\n== Protests ==\n{{Main|2010 G20 Toronto summit protests}}\n[[File:G-20 Toronto June 2010 (20).jpg|thumb|right|Demonstrators holding signs with slogans against the G20]]\nMajor protests occurred in [[downtown Toronto]] during the week of the summit, which abruptly escalated during the days of the summit. Early opposition to the G20 included an incident in [[Ottawa]] where a bank was firebombed by [[anarchism|anarchists]], who claimed they would be present during the G20 summit in Toronto.<ref name=\"rbc\">{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/rbc-firebombed-as-protest-group-claims-1.915706 | title=RBC firebombed as protest, group claims | publisher=CBC.ca | work=CBC News | date=8 May 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-23 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522013917/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/rbc-firebombed-as-protest-group-claims-1.915706 | archivedate=22 May 2010 }}</ref> The perceived security threat caused the [[Integrated Security Unit]] to increase security measures.<ref name=\"swainson\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/812976--ottawa-firebombing-proves-security-need-clement-says |title=Ottawa firebombing proves security need, Clement says |work=Toronto Star |date=21 May 2010 |publisher=thestar.com |accessdate=2010-09-28 |author=Gail Swainson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607101152/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/812976--ottawa-firebombing-proves-security-need-clement-says |archivedate=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nProtests began one week ahead of the summit, organized by groups including [[Oxfam Canada]] and the [[Ontario Coalition Against Poverty]].  Issues such as [[poverty]],<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news| url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE65E4RB20100617?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Toronto G20 protest hints at more to come |publisher=Reuters (Canada) |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23 |author=Cameron French and Pav Jordan| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100622091653/http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE65E4RB20100617?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0| archivedate= 22 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Canada|gay rights]],<ref name=\"yang\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827058--gays-lesbians-hold-g20-kiss-in?bn=1 |title=G20 turning downtown Toronto into a ghost town |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-22|accessdate=2010-06-24 | first1=Jennifer | last1=Yang | first2=Liam | last2=Casey| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100626093646/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827058--gays-lesbians-hold-g20-kiss-in?bn=1| archivedate= 26 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[capitalism]] and [[globalization]],<ref name=\"poisson\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826478--g20-protesters-try-to-take-over-downtown-property?bn=1 |title=G20 protesters try to take over downtown property |publisher=thestar.com | date=21 June 2010| accessdate=2010-06-22 | work=Toronto Star | first=Jayme | last=Poisson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625043412/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826478--g20-protesters-try-to-take-over-downtown-property?bn=1| archivedate= 25 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[indigenous rights]],<ref name=\"edwards\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827924--first-nations-demonstrators-take-over-downtown-streets?bn=1 |title=First nations demonstrators take over downtown streets |publisher=thestar.com |date=24 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-24| work=Toronto Star| first=Peter | last=Edwards| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100627143516/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/827924--first-nations-demonstrators-take-over-downtown-streets?bn=1| archivedate= 27 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and controversial issues with the summit itself were the object of protests.<ref name=\"largest\">{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100625/g20-summit-protest-poverty-100625/20100625/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Riot police turn back largest G20 protest yet| work=CTV News| publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=25 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-24| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628035045/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100625/g20-summit-protest-poverty-100625/20100625/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Despite a few arrests, protests over the week were mainly determined to be peaceful.<ref name=\"continue\">{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/protests-continue-in-toronto-as-g20-nears-1.914177 |title=Protests continue in Toronto as G20 nears |publisher=CBC.ca |work=CBC News |date=22 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-24| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100625060457/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/protests-continue-in-toronto-as-g20-nears-1.914177| archivedate= 25 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs the first day of the summit approached, protesters grew in numbers. Several streets were closed to demonstrations on the debut of the summit. Peaceful protests were followed by [[black bloc]] tactics as individuals dressed in black dispersed from the crowd and began damaging the windows of particular businesses across downtown Toronto, mostly [[List of fast food restaurant chains|fast food chains]], retail stores and banks, as well as local businesses.<ref name=\"tactics\">{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829168--violent-black-bloc-tactics-on-display-at-g20-protest?bn=1 |title=Violent Black Bloc tactics on display at G20 protest |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-26 |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=2010-06-27 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630071652/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829168--violent-black-bloc-tactics-on-display-at-g20-protest?bn=1| archivedate= 30 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Police car|Police cruisers]] were set on fire and vehicles of media corporations were damaged.<ref name=\"clear\">{{cite web| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/summit-protests-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Police attempt to clear crowds amid G20 unrest |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628062552/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/summit-protests-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Nearby hospitals, shopping centres, and hotels were put in [[lockdown]] mode while public transit services were diverted from downtown to other locations.<ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite web| url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/toronto-chaos-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=TTC lines, Eaton Centre locked down as protests heat up |work=CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100630151222/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/toronto-chaos-100626/20100626/?hub=TorontoNewHome| archivedate= 30 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs security was further tightened and forces increased in presence the following day, protests against police brutality occurred in front of the [[Eastern Avenue (Toronto)|Eastern Avenue]] temporary detention centre, where nearly 500 arrested individuals were kept from the previous day's riots.<ref name=\"CTV.ca\">{{cite news |author=Jesse Ship |date=2010-06-28 |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/toronto-g20-anti-police-rally-100628/20100628/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Another large demonstration follows the G20 |publisher=[[CFTO-DT]] |accessdate=13 November 2010  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902065917/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/toronto-g20-anti-police-rally-100628/20100628?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=2 September 2010 }}</ref> A group of protesters was also \"[[kettling|kettled]]\" for several hours through the night after black bloc protesters were believed to be in the crowd.<ref name=\"mclean2\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829642--police-defend-crowd-trap-at-queen-and-spadina |title=Police defend crowd trap at Queen and Spadina  |publisher=thestar.com |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-23 | work=Toronto Star | author=Jesse McLean| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100701151357/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829642--police-defend-crowd-trap-at-queen-and-spadina| archivedate= 1 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Over 1100 people were confirmed to be arrested over the week.<ref name=\"mahoney\">{{cite news | title=G20-related mass arrests unique in Canadian history | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/g20-related-mass-arrests-unique-in-canadian-history/article1621198/ | date=29 June 2010 | work=The Globe and Mail | accessdate=2012-04-05 | author=Jill Mahoney and Ann Hui | publisher=theglobeandmail.com | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728172459/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/g20-related-mass-arrests-unique-in-canadian-history/article1621198/ | archivedate=28 July 2010 }}</ref> The ISU performed sweeping arrests within a specific boundary from the summit venue.<ref name=\"sweeping\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/828367--g20-law-gives-police-sweeping-powers-to-arrest-people |title=G20 law gives police sweeping powers to arrest people |work=Toronto Star |publisher=thestar.com |date=25 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-24 |author=Jennifer Yang| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100628022808/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/828367--g20-law-gives-police-sweeping-powers-to-arrest-people| archivedate= 28 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Individuals arrested during the protests condemned the treatment they received from police.<ref name=\"ship\">{{cite news |author=Jesse Ship |date=28 June 2010 |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829921--i-will-not-forget-what-they-have-done-to-me?bn=1 |title=I will not forget what they have done to me |work=Toronto Star |publisher=thestar.com |accessdate=2012-03-23  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702011919/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829921--i-will-not-forget-what-they-have-done-to-me?bn=1 |archivedate=2 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Outcome ==\n[[File:Leaders at the 2010 G-20 Toronto summit.jpg|thumb|right|Leaders confer at the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] on June 27]]\nPrior to the Toronto summit, it was speculated that it would not see the same outcome as previous summits. This was partially due to most countries' entering recovery mode from the [[Great Recession|global economic recession]] after the past G20 summits; thus, the likelihood of new issues being raised was minimal.<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite news| title=G20 lacks governing instruments| url=https://rt.com/politics/roar-russia-g20-g8/| publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT News]]| date=28 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-23| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725214901/https://rt.com/politics/roar-russia-g20-g8/| archivedate=25 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the working dinner for G20 leaders on the evening of June 26, South African president [Jacob Zuma] promoted more partnership between the international community and Africa for the development in the continent. \"As Africa we bring to the G20 Summit the key message that we must, together as the developing and developed worlds, promote stronger and more effective and equal international partnerships for growth and development,\" he remarked.<ref name=\"zuma\">{{cite news| url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=nw20100627065853768C239086| title=Zuma urges more partnerships at G20 dinner| work=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-23| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628142927/http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=nw20100627065853768C239086| archivedate=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the summit, the US president [[Barack Obama]] warned that global recovery was still \"fragile.\" In hopes of boosting American exports, he proposed a [[free trade agreement]] between the [[United States]] and [[South Korea]].<ref name=\"schneider\">{{cite news| author=Howard Schneider| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/26/AR2010062604314.html?sid=ST2010062604320| title=President Obama urges G-20 nations to spend; they pledge to halve deficits| work=[[The Washington Post]]| date=28 June 2010| publisher=washingtonpost.com| accessdate=2012-03-28| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112133834/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/26/AR2010062604314.html?sid=ST2010062604320| archivedate=12 November 2012}}</ref> A key agreement the leaders of [[Developed country|developed nations]] made was to cut annual budget deficits in half by 2013.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/100628_harper_g20/20100628/?hub=CP24Home |title=Harper applauds summit outcome but says G20 still has a lot more to do |publisher=[[CP24]] |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305161607/http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100628/100628_harper_g20/20100628/?hub=CP24Home |archivedate=5 March 2012 }}</ref> The leaders also agreed on reducing [[debt-to-GDP ratio]] in each economy by 2016.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> The debate on imposing a [[bank tax|tax on financial institutions]] was settled as the group agreed that [[financial institution]]s would be required to make fair contributions to recover costs from the financial sector reform,<ref name=\"fmm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesfinanzministerium.de/EN/Topics/International-affairs/Articles/20100816-Outcome-of-the-Toronto-G20-summit.html |title=Outcome of the Toronto G20 summit |publisher=[[Federal Ministry of Finance (Germany)]] |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229212604/http://www.bundesfinanzministerium.de/EN/Topics/International-affairs/Articles/20100816-Outcome-of-the-Toronto-G20-summit.html |archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref> but the manner of collecting the contributions would be left to each government.<ref name=\"whittingon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829266--g20-adopts-canadian-compromise-on-deficits-bank-tax |title=G20 adopts Canadian compromise on deficits, bank tax |publisher=thestar.com |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |work=Toronto Star |first1=Les |last1=Whittingon |author2=Bruce Campion-Smith and Richard J. Brennan |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419012709/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/829266--g20-adopts-canadian-compromise-on-deficits-bank-tax |archivedate=19 April 2012 }}</ref> Participants also decided that the institutions would be required to keep a higher amount of [[financial capital]] in case of future [[Shock (economics)|financial shocks]].<ref name=\"gascoigne\">{{cite press release |author=Clark Gascoigne |url=http://www.financialtaskforce.org/2010/04/23/g20-finance-ministers-communique-is-released/ |title=G20 Finance Ministers Communiqu\u00e9 is Released |publisher=[[Task Force on Financial Integrity and Economic Development]] |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427041640/http://www.financialtaskforce.org/2010/04/23/g20-finance-ministers-communique-is-released/ |archivedate=27 April 2010 }}</ref> [[Climate change]] and [[food security]] were also discussed; the leaders reiterated their commitment to a \"[[environmentally friendly|greener]] growth\".<ref name=\"iisd\">{{cite web|url=http://climate-l.org/news/g-20-toronto-summit-addresses-energy-subsidies-climate-change-and-food-security/ |title=G-20 Toronto Summit Addresses Energy Subsidies, Climate Change and Food Security |publisher=International Institute for Sustainable Development |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813174308/http://climate-l.org/news/g-20-toronto-summit-addresses-energy-subsidies-climate-change-and-food-security/ |archivedate=13 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''The G20 Toronto Summit Declaration'', which was released shortly after the summit concluded, stated that \"serious challenges remain.\" According to the document, the challenges include high unemployment rates in various economies and the concurrent existence of the impact of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|financial crisis]]. The [[International Monetary Fund]], in its post-summit document, indicated that a speedy cut in deficits may substantially slow growth. In a publication entitled ''Top Ten Commandments for Fiscal Adjustment in Advanced Economies'', the organization insisted that balanced public spending could stabilize [[bond market]]s, reduce interest rates from less government spending, and encourage private investment. It also recommended that emerging economies such as [[China]], which has largely benefited from trade surpluses, rely less on developed nations and increase their own spending in order to promote domestic demand.<ref name=\"declaration\">{{cite web |title=The G20 Toronto summit declaration |url=http://canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-declaration-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |publisher=Government of Canada |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=2012-03-27  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503090441/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-declaration-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |archivedate=3 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Financial costs ===\n[[File:DirectEnergyCentreLivingWall.jpg|thumb|$246,000 was spent on a Green wall for G20.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/living-wall-mass-casualty-kits-all-part-of-1-billion-tab-for-g8g20-summits/article1213892/ Living wall, 'mass casualty kits' all part of $1-billion tab for G8/G20 summits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305004209/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/living-wall-mass-casualty-kits-all-part-of-1-billion-tab-for-g8g20-summits/article1213892/ |date=2016-03-05 }}</ref>]]\nThe financial costs of hosting the [[36th G8 summit|G8]] and G20 summits was the topic of several political debates and the target of criticism by local groups.<ref name=\"rider\">{{cite news| author=David Rider| title=Toronto warns Ottawa on G20 costs| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/769614--toronto-warns-ottawa-on-g20-costs| work=Toronto Star| date=22 February 2010| publisher=thestar.com| accessdate=2012-03-30| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021153957/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/769614--toronto-warns-ottawa-on-g20-costs| archivedate=21 October 2012}}</ref> The reasons for the large price for both summits were questioned by some politicians and local groups. Members of Parliament [[Olivia Chow]] and [[Mark Holland]] labelled the initially claimed budget of $1.1-billion for hosting the summits as \"obscene\" and \"insane\" while others argued that the money could have been used for long-pending municipal projects in Canada,<ref name=\"security\">{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/?s_name=&no_ads=| title=Security chief defends high cost of G8-G20 summits| publisher=CTV.ca| date=28 May 2010| accessdate=2012-03-30| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609185308/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/?s_name=&no_ads=| archivedate=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"sufrin\">{{cite news|author=Jon Sufrin |url=http://www.torontolife.com/daily/informer/summit-survivor/2010/05/26/833-million-security-bill-for-g20-and-g8-called-insane/ |title=$833-million security bill for G20 and G8 called 'insane' |work=[[Toronto Life]] |date=26 May 2010 |accessdate=2012-04-01 |publisher=torontolife.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227045544/http://www.torontolife.com/daily/informer/summit-survivor/2010/05/26/833-million-security-bill-for-g20-and-g8-called-insane/ |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref> such as [[Transit City]].<ref name=\"pate\">{{cite news| author=Stephen Pate| url=http://www.oyetimes.com/views/columns/3186-1-billion-price-tag-for-g20-security-and-climbing| title=$1 billion price tag for G20 security and climbing| work=Oye! Times| publisher=oyetimes.com| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-01| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226215954/http://www.oyetimes.com/views/columns/3186-1-billion-price-tag-for-g20-security-and-climbing| archivedate=26 February 2012}}</ref> The security cost for the two summits was believed to be more expensive than the combined security costs of the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] and [[2010 Winter Paralympics|Paralympics]] in [[Vancouver]] and [[Whistler, British Columbia]], which were {{Nowrap|$878 million}}.<ref name=\"sufrin\"/>  However, according to final calculations from the [[House of Commons of Canada]] as of October 2010, the exact cost for holding both summits was $857,901,850.31, making it less expensive than the security costs for the 2010 Winter Olympics.<ref name=\"final\"/>\n\nIt was initially claimed that the summits stand as the most expensive ever held, with security costs for the [[2009 G20 London summit|London]] and [[2009 G20 Pittsburgh summit|Pittsburgh]] reported as having been only {{Nowrap|$30 million}} and {{Nowrap|$18 million}}, respectively.<ref name=\"security\"/>  However, the Canadian [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]], [[Kevin Page]], stated in his official report on the costs of the Huntsville and Toronto gatherings that other countries had not been as open about the full price for the similar meetings held there and that the {{Nowrap|$18 million}} figure for the Pittsburgh summit was merely for overtime pay for local police and the cost of law enforcement brought from other regions.<ref name=\"tibbetts\">{{cite news| author=Janice Tibbetts| title=Tories 'transparent' on security costs: Watchdog| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Federal+government+transparent+summit+security+costs+Watchdog/3192674/story.html| publisher=canada.com| work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]| agency=[[Canwest]] News Service| date=23 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-05| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517034458/http://www.canada.com/news/Federal+government+transparent+summit+security+costs+Watchdog/3192674/story.html| archivedate=17 May 2012}}</ref>  [[Ward Elcock]], former [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service]] director and the chief of the [[Integrated Security Unit]]s for the Winter Olympics and the G8/G20 summits, claimed that the security costs were in fact \"comparable\" with those of previous summits.<ref name=\"security\"/> Finance minister [[Jim Flaherty]] defended the security cost, claiming \"it's necessary to spend substantially to have security. It's Canada's turn, and it's necessary that we either don't take our turn or pay the appropriate price to have the security that is necessary so that everyone is safe here in Toronto.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100607/flaherty_cost_100607/20100607/?hub=WinnipegHome |title=Financial reform taking too long: Flaherty |work=CTV News |publisher=CTV.ca |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224080622/http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100607/flaherty_cost_100607/20100607/?hub=WinnipegHome |archivedate=24 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe creation of the $23-million international media centre, which included the {{Nowrap|$1.9 million}} ''Experience Canada'' pavilion and $57,000 artificial lake, at the [[Exhibition Place]] was widely opposed and criticized by politicians as \"a waste of taxpayers' money.\"<ref name=\"loon\">{{cite web |url=http://looncanada.wordpress.com/2010/06/08/g20-summit-fake-lake-has-canadian-taxpayers-in-stitches/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611084935/http://looncanada.wordpress.com/2010/06/08/g20-summit-fake-lake-has-canadian-taxpayers-in-stitches/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2010 |title=G20 summit's $2 million \"fake lake\" has Canadian taxpayers in stitches |work=Loon |location=Canada |date=28 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 }}</ref> Criticism mainly targeted Stephen Harper and Canada's [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative government]]. Some protesting groups gave names to the artificial lake, such as \"Harper's Folly\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20100607/g20-security-cost-100607/ | title=Tories say artificial lake will help 'showcase Canada' | publisher=CTV.ca | work=CTV News | date=7 June 2010 | accessdate=2012-03-28 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119025822/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20100607/g20-security-cost-100607/ | archivedate=19 January 2012 }}</ref> In a debate in the House of Commons, member Mark Holland said, \"Instead of hosting world leaders, maybe the government should consider party planning for [[Lady Gaga]].\"<ref name=\"weese\">{{cite news| url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/canada/2010/06/07/14291091.html| title='Fake lake' flak dogs PM| publisher=Torontosun.com| work=Toronto Sun| date=7 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-28| author=Bryn Weese| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125223638/http://www.torontosun.com/news/canada/2010/06/07/14291091.html| archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref> According to some critics, the spending misled the objective of the summits into showing off Canada's attributes instead of promoting the summits' agendas.<ref name=\"taber\">{{cite news| title=Tories pilloried for fake lake at G8/G20 media centre |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-pilloried-for-fake-lake-at-g8g20-media-centre/article1595348/ |publisher=theglobeandmail.com| work=The Globe and Mail| author=Jane Taber |date=7 June 2010| accessdate=2012-03-28 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100915141804/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-pilloried-for-fake-lake-at-g8g20-media-centre/article1595348/| archivedate= 15 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] leader [[Jack Layton]] condemned the Harper government, saying, \"we've got a government here that has to create an artificial lake when Canada has more lakes than just about any other country in the world. It is the taxpayers who are going to end up at the bottom of the fake lake.\" Transport minister [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]] defended the artificial lake, saying that the summits gave a \"chance to showcase the very best that [Canada] has to offer.\" Foreign affairs minister [[Lawrence Cannon]] said it was \"normal practice\" for a country to showcase its attributes while hosting world events.<ref name=\"taber\"/> Harper also defended by saying, \"This is a classic attempt for us to be able to market the country.\"<ref name=\"akin\">{{cite news | title=Ottawa defends $1.9-million taste of Muskoka at G20 media centre | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-defends-19-million-taste-of-muskoka-at-g20-media-centre/article1595709/ | publisher=theglobeandmail.com | work=The Globe and Mail | date=7 June 2010 | author=Siri Agrell | accessdate=2012-03-28 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126044809/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-defends-19-million-taste-of-muskoka-at-g20-media-centre/article1595709/ | archivedate=26 January 2011 }}</ref> Upon its opening, the artificial lake received mostly negative reviews from Canadian reporters.<ref name=\"fakelake\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827453--g20-fake-lake-makes-its-debut |title=G20 'Fake Lake' makes its debut |publisher=thestar.com |work=Toronto Star |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |author=David Rider |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021154016/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827453--g20-fake-lake-makes-its-debut |archivedate=21 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Economic impact ===\nThe summit's economic impact was a major concern of a few local politicians and citizens. The [[City of Toronto government]], as well as some public representatives, previously argued that the G20 summit should be held at an isolated venue, such as the [[Exhibition Place]], rather than the Metro Toronto Convention Centre, which is located in the city's [[central business district]].<ref name=\"mclean3\">{{cite news| title=Lessons for G20 security from Vancouver Olympics| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/torontog20summit/article/820332--lessons-for-g20-security-from-vancouver-olympics|publisher=theStar.com| work=Toronto Star |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 | author=Jesse McLean}}</ref> As a result, during the aftermath of the protests during the summit, when several business and properties in Downtown Toronto were damaged, mayor [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] urged the federal government to compensate for all the damages. It was initially outlined by the government that only damages to businesses within the security zone would be compensated. However, all damages occurred outside of the security zone. Some businesses in the downtown core suffered financially as a result.<ref name=\"compensation\">{{cite news |url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100629/toronto-riot-compensation-businesses-100629/20100629/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Advocates want compensation for T.O. businesses |publisher=CTV.ca |work=CTV News Toronto |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310051412/http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100629/toronto-riot-compensation-businesses-100629/20100629/?hub=TorontoNewHome |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> According to Member of Parliament [[John McCallum]], \"Stephen Harper made a huge mistake in holding this summit in downtown Toronto.\" According to the ''Toronto Star'', at least 40 stores in the [[Downtown Yonge|Downtown Yonge Business Improvement Area]] suffered damages and one repair firm performed up to {{nowrap|$750,000}} in repairs.<ref name=\"ridder\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829912--pressure-builds-on-ottawa-for-compensation?bn=1 |title=Pressure builds on Ottawa for compensation |publisher=thestar.com |work=Toronto Star |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |author=David Rider and Susan Delacourt |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702011815/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/829912--pressure-builds-on-ottawa-for-compensation?bn=1 |archivedate=2 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nOn June 17, the [[United States Department of State]] issued a travel alert for Toronto, warning tourists of the expected traffic disruptions and potentially violent protests during the G20 summit. The alert, which was expected to expire on the last day of the summit, stated that \"Even demonstrations that are meant to be peaceful can become violent and unpredictable.\"  Toronto Mayor [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] described the warning as an \"over-reaction.\"<ref name=\"usalert\">{{cite news| author=Jesse McLean| title=U.S. issues G20 travel alert for Toronto| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/824844--u-s-issues-g20-travel-alert-for-toronto?bn=1| work=Toronto Star| publisher=thestar.com| date=18 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418205124/http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/824844--u-s-issues-g20-travel-alert-for-toronto?bn=1| archivedate=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summit, a few overseas reporters commented on Canada and the summits. A reporter of the [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC) made positive remarks about Canada's economy, saying \"The Canadians, it seems, have answers for even the toughest puzzles and they are keen to share their strategies with the rest of the world. Why in this economy, we all want to be Canadian.\" A writer in ''[[The New York Times]]'' made positive comments about the summits' preparations and natural beauty of the [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka]] region. ''[[The Times of India]]'' and ''[[The Hindu]]'' commented on impacts on city life in Toronto due to the G20 summit and the \"unprecedented\" security measures taken in Canada. A [[Reuters]] reporter, on the other hand, condemned the international media centre's artificial lake.<ref name=\"buzzing\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/100626_cost_g20/20100626/?hub=CP24Home| title=World media buzzing about cost of G20 security and fake lake| agency=The Canadian Press| date=26 June 2010| publisher=CP24| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305161433/http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100626/100626_cost_g20/20100626/?hub=CP24Home| archivedate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nLooking forward, French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] announced that the costs for hosting the proposed [[2011 G20 Cannes summit]] and [[37th G8 summit]] in France would be one-tenth of Canada's.<ref name=\"curry\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/sarkozy-says-his-g8g20-will-cost-one-tenth-of-canadas/article1619637/| title=Sarkozy says his G8/G20 will cost one-tenth of Canada's| work=The Globe and Mail| publisher=theglobeandmail.com| author=Bill Curry| date=27 June 2010| accessdate=2012-04-03| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104113136/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/sarkozy-says-his-g8g20-will-cost-one-tenth-of-canadas/article1619637/| archivedate=4 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Economics|Canada}}\n* [[14th G7 summit]]\n* [[G20 Research Group]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|2010 G-20 Toronto summit}}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g20/summit-sommet/2010/toronto-toronto.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=3}}\n\n{{G-20 leaders' summits}}\n{{2008 economic crisis}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:G-20 summit 2010 Toronto}}\n[[Category:G20 summits|2010 06 Toronto]]\n[[Category:2010 conferences]]\n[[Category:2010 in economics]]\n[[Category:2010 in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:History of Toronto]]\n[[Category:2010 in Toronto]]\n[[Category:June 2010 events in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_G20_Toronto_summit"}
{"title_page": "Indian Railways", "text_new": "{{About|the organisation|general information on railways in India|Rail transport in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox company|\n| logo = Indian railways.webp\n| logo_size = 125px\n| logo_alt = Red-and-white Indian Railways logo\n| logo_caption = \n| image = Indian Railways Headquarters.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = [[Rail Bhavan]], [[New Delhi]]\n| type = Government\n| industry = [[Rail transport]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|p=y|1845|5|08}}<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: IR History: Early Days \u2013 1|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=3 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307181407/http://irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|archive-date=7 March 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> <!-- Indian railways traces its history back to Madras Railway which was incorporated on 8 May 1845 by . See the ref, http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html. The first passenger line albeit was by GIPR in 1853. This article is about the company and not about rail transport. Hence the foundation year is 1845 and not 1853. -->\n| hq_location_city = [[New Delhi]]\n| hq_location_country = India\n| area_served = [[India]]\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list| [[Piyush Goyal]] ([[Minister of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]])| [[Suresh Angadi]] (Minister of State for Railways)| [[Vinod Kumar Yadav]] ([[Chairman]], [[Railway Board]])}}\n| services = [[Passenger railway]]s<br />[[Freight]] services<br />[[Parcel carrier]]<br />Catering and tourism services<br />[[Parking lot]] operations<br />Other related services\n| revenue = {{Increase}} {{INRConvert|1.97214|t}}<ref name=\"financial-summary\">{{cite web|url=http://indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/Budget_2019-20_Final/Statement%20of%20Railway%20Receipts%20and%20Expenditure_Regular%20Budget%202019-20.pdf|title=Indian Railways Budget Documents 2019\u201320|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue_year = 2018\u201319\n| profit = {{Increase}} {{INRConvert|60.14|b}}<ref name=\"financial-summary\" />\n| profit_year = 2018\u201319\n| owner = [[Government of India]] (100%)\n| num_employees = 1.30  million<ref name=\"stats-summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/Statistical_Summary.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Statistical summary \u2013 Indian Railways|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=22 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222170734/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/Statistical_Summary.pdf|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]\n| divisions = [[Zones and divisions of Indian Railways|18 zones]]\n| subsid = [[Centre for Railway Information Systems|CRIS]], [[Container Corporation of India|CONCOR]], [[RITES]], [[Ircon International|IRCON]], [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]], [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|DFCCI]], [[RailTel Corporation of India|RailTel]], [[Mumbai Railway Vikas Corporation|MRVC]], \n[[Rail Vikas Nigam|RVNL]], [[High-speed rail in India|NHSRCL]], [[Indian Railway Finance Corporation|IRFC]]\n| module = \n| footnotes = \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.indianrail.gov.in/}}<br />{{URL|http://indianrailways.gov.in/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox rail\n|railroad_name     =\n|logo_filename     =\n|logo_size         =\n|system_map        = India railway schematic map.svg\n|map_caption       = Railway network map of India - schematic\n|map_size          =\n|marks             = IR\n|image             = \n|image_size        =\n|image_caption     = Railway network map of India - schematic\n|locale            = India\n|start_year        = {{Start date|1845|5|8|df=y}}<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\"/> <!-- Indian railways traces its history back to Madras Railway which was incorporated on 8 May 1845. See the ref, http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html. The first [[passenger]] line albeit was by GIPR in 1853. This article is about the company and not about rail transport. Hence the foundation year is 1845 and not 1853. -->\n|end_year          = present\n|predecessor_line  =\n|successor_line    =\n|gauge             = {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|1000mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}}\n|length            = {{convert|67368|km}} (route)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> <br />{{convert|93902|km}} (running track)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> <br /> {{convert|121407|km}} (total track)<ref name=\":4\"/>\n|electrification   = {{convert|37359|km}}(as of March 2020 approx.)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Indian Railways plans to end the pain of waitlist tickets |url=https://zeenews.india.com/economy/indian-railways-plans-to-end-the-pain-of-waitlist-tickets-2230519.html |website=Zee News |accessdate=29 August 2019 |language=en |date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Indian Railways''' ('''IR''') is [[India]]'s national railway system operated by the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]. It is one of the public facilities given by the government and manages the [[List of countries by rail transport network size|fourth largest railway network in the world]] by size, with a route length of {{convert|67368|km||adj=on|abbr=}} as of March 2017. About 57.91% of the routes are electrified with [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25 kV 50 Hz AC]] electric traction while 33% of them are double or multi-tracked.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/10.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Statistics for Track and Bridges \u2013 Indian Railways|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=22 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222225514/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/10.pdf|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the fiscal year ending March 2018, IR carried 8.26&nbsp;billion passengers and transported 1.16&nbsp;billion tonnes of freight.<ref name=\"financial-summary\" /> In the fiscal year 2017\u201318, IR is projected to have revenue of {{INRConvert|1.874|t|lk=}}, consisting of {{INRConvert|1.175|t|lk=}} in freight revenue and {{INRConvert|501.25|b|lk=}} in passenger revenue, with an [[operating ratio]] of 96.0 percent.<ref name=\"financial-summary\" />\n\n[https://thefactsone.com/interesting-facts-about-indian-railways/ Indian Railway] (IR) runs more than 20,000 passenger trains daily, on both [[Rail transport in India|long-distance]] and [[Suburban rail in India|suburban routes]], from 7,349 stations across India.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> The trains have five-digit and four-digit numbering system. [[Express trains in India|Mail or Express trains]], the most common types, run at an average speed of {{convert|50.6|km/h|}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/5.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Passenger Business|work=Ministry of Railway|page=23|format=PDF|accessdate=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050611/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/5.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Most premium passenger trains like [[Rajdhani Express]] and [[Shatabdi Express]] run at a peak speed of {{convert|140-150|km/h|abbr=on|}} with [[Gatimaan Express|Gatiman Express]] between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] and [[Jhansi Junction railway station|Jhansi]] touching a peak speed of {{convert|160|km/h|abbr=on}}. Indian railways also runs indigenously built semi-high speed train called [[Vande Bharat Express|Vande Bharat]] (also known as [[Vande Bharat Express|Train-18]])\" between [[Delhi Junction railway station|Delhi]] and [[Varanasi Junction railway station|Varanasi]] or [[Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra railway station|Katra]] which clocks a maximum track speed of {{convert|180|km/h|abbr=on}}. In the freight segment, IR runs more than 9,200 trains daily. The average speed of freight trains is around {{convert|24|km/h||abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/2.pdf|title=extrastats-summary|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223174343/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/2.pdf|archive-date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Maximum speed of freight trains varies from {{convert|60 to 75|km/h|abbr=on}} depending on their axle load with \"container special\" trains running at a peak speed of {{convert|100|km/h|abbr=on}}.\n\nAs of March 2017, Indian Railways' [[rolling stock]] consisted of 277,987 [[Freight rail transport|freight wagons]], 70,937 [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger coaches]] and 11,452 [[locomotive]]s.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> IR owns [[locomotive]] and [[coach (rail)|coach-production]] facilities at several locations in India. Being the world's [[List of companies by employees|eighth-largest employer]], it had 1.30&nbsp;million employees as of March 2016.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" />\n\nThe government has committed to [[Central Organisation for Railway Electrification|electrify its entire rail network]] by 2023, and become a \"net-zero railway\" by 2030.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/thumbs-up-indian-railways-to-go-eco-friendly-by-becoming-worlds-1st-100-electrified-and-net-zero-railway/1737339/|title=Thumbs up! Indian Railways to go eco-friendly by becoming world\u2019s 1st 100% electrified and \u2018Net-Zero\u2019 railway|date=2019-10-16|website=TheFinancial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of rail transport in India}}\n\nThe first railway proposals for India were made in [[Madras]] in 1832.<ref name=\"irfca.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/docs/history/india-first-railways.html|title=[IRFCA] India's First Railways|website=www.irfca.org}}</ref> The country's first train, ''Red Hill Railway'' (built by [[Arthur Cotton]] to transport granite for road-building), ran from [[Red Hills, Chennai|Red Hills]] to the [[Chintadripet]] bridge in Madras in 1837.<ref name=\"irfca.org\"/> In 1845, the ''Godavari Dam Construction Railway'' was built by Cotton at [[Dowleswaram]] in [[Rajahmundry]], to supply stone for the construction of a dam over the [[Godavari River]]. In 1851, the ''Solani Aqueduct Railway'' was built by [[Proby Cautley]] in [[Roorkee]] to transport construction materials for an [[aqueduct (bridge)|aqueduct]] over the Solani River.<ref name=\"irfca.org\" />\n\nIndia's first passenger train, operated by the [[Great Indian Peninsula Railway]] and hauled by three steam locomotives (''Sahib'', ''Sindh'' and ''Sultan''), ran for {{convert|34|km}} with 400 people in 14 carriages on {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}} [[broad gauge]] track between [[Bori Bunder railway station|Bori Bunder]] ([[Mumbai]]) and [[Thane]] on 16 April 1853.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/164-years-ago-on-this-day-india-s-first-train-ran-from-mumbai-to-thane-275748.html|title=164 Years Ago On This Day, India's First Train Ran From Mumbai To Thane|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729114445/http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/164-years-ago-on-this-day-india-s-first-train-ran-from-mumbai-to-thane-275748.html|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Indias-1st-train-When-Sahib-Sindh-Sultan-blew-steam/articleshow/19717248.cms|title=India\u2019s 1st train: When Sahib, Sindh & Sultan blew steam \u2013 Times of India|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808221221/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Indias-1st-train-When-Sahib-Sindh-Sultan-blew-steam/articleshow/19717248.cms|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Thane viaducts, India's first [[railway bridge]]s, were built over the [[Thane creek]] when the Mumbai-Thane line was extended to [[Kalyan]] in May 1854.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/docs/history/railway-times.html|title=Extracts from the Railway Times|date=1854|publisher=Railway Times|access-date=1 Jan 2019}}</ref> Eastern India's first passenger train ran {{convert|24|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Howrah]], near [[Kolkata]], to [[Hugli-Chinsura|Hoogly]] on 15 August 1854.<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\"/> The first passenger train in [[South India]] ran {{convert|60|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Royapuram]]- Veyasarapady ([[Madras]]) to Wallajah Road ([[Arcot]]) on 1 July 1856.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railnews.in/royapuram-railway-station-legacy-through-the-ages/|title=Legacy of First Railway Station of South India|website=RailNews Media India Ltd|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729092115/http://www.railnews.in/royapuram-railway-station-legacy-through-the-ages/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 1873, a [[Horsecar|horse-drawn]] {{convert|3.8|km||abbr=on}} [[tram]] opened in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] between [[Sealdah]] and Armenian Ghat Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturebowl.com/kolkatas-trams-a-ride-through-history/|title=Kolkata\u2019s trams \u2013 A ride through history|date=2 March 2016|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729094331/http://www.culturebowl.com/kolkatas-trams-a-ride-through-history/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 May 1874, a horse-drawn tramway began operation in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] between [[Colaba]] and [[Parel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dighist.fas.harvard.edu/courses/2015/HUM54/exhibits/show/mumbai_development/trams|title=The Evolution of Trams in Mumbai|website=The Urban Imagination \u2013 Faculty of Arts and Sciences|publisher=[[Harvard University]]|access-date=18 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011232644/http://dighist.fas.harvard.edu/courses/2015/HUM54/exhibits/show/mumbai_development/trams|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1897, lighting in passenger coaches was introduced by many railway companies. On 3 February 1925, the first electric passenger train in India ran between [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus railway station|Victoria Terminus]] and [[Kurla]].<ref name=\"core.indianrailways.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,530|title=Welcome to Official Website of CORE|website=www.core.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=26 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807073445/http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,530|archive-date=7 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe organization of Indian railways into regional zones began in 1951,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in/index.php/history-of-railways|title=History of Railways|website=www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721211938/http://www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in/index.php/history-of-railways|archive-date=21 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> when the [[Southern Railway zone|Southern]] (14 April 1951), [[Central Railway zone|Central]] (5 November 1951), and [[Western Railway zone|Western]] (5 November 1951) zones were created.<ref name=\"indianrail.gov.in\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319003737/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |archive-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fans and lights were mandated for all compartments in all passenger classes in 1951, and sleeping accommodations were introduced in coaches. In 1956, the first fully air-conditioned train was introduced between [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]] and Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/NAT-TOP-160-years-of-indian-railways-watch-how-ac-trains-were-kept-cool-4224130-PHO.html|title=160 years of Indian Railways: Here's how AC trains were kept cool|date=2 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Ten years later, the first containerized freight service began between Mumbai and [[Ahmedabad]].\n\nIn 1974, Indian Railways endured a [[1974 railway strike in India|20 day strike]], which damaged the nation's economy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/08/archives/strike-of-indian-rail-workers-begins-tension-high-with-food.html|title=Strike of Indian Rail Workers Begins|date=1974-05-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2019/jan/30/better-jail-than-rail-george-fernandes-slogan-that-led-to-asias-biggest-railway-strike-in-1974-1931637.html|title=Better jail than rail: George Fernandes' slogan that led to Asia's biggest railway strike in 1974|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, computerized ticketing and reservations were introduced in New Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://icisa.cag.gov.in/audit_report/2/15db5cf8539e7f66e05214564e6b5d01.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712231120/http://icisa.cag.gov.in/audit_report/2/15db5cf8539e7f66e05214564e6b5d01.pdf |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 1988, the first [[Shatabdi Express]] was introduced between New Delhi and Jhansi; it was later extended to [[Bhopal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-railways/trains/shatabdi-express.html|title=Shatabdi Express \u2013 Shatabdi Express Train, Shatabadi Express Timetable, Shatabadi Express Schedule Booking India|website=www.iloveindia.com|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715191922/http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-railways/trains/shatabdi-express.html|archive-date=15 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years later, the first self-printing ticket machine (SPTM) was introduced in New Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/happy-birthday-indian-railways-first-passenger-train-started-165-years-ago-unknown-facts-about-the-network/1134650/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528051814/https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/happy-birthday-indian-railways-first-passenger-train-started-165-years-ago-unknown-facts-about-the-network/1134650/ |archive-date=28 May 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 1993, air-conditioned three-tier coaches and a sleeper class (separate from second class) were introduced on IR. The CONCERT system of computerized reservations was deployed in New Delhi, Mumbai and [[Chennai Central railway station|Chennai]] in September 1996. In 1998, coupon validating machines (CVMs) were introduced at [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus|Mumbai Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus]]. The nationwide concierge system began operation on 18 April 1999. In February 2000, the Indian Railways website went online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/index_new.html|title=Indian Railway|website=www.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724071557/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/index_new.html|archive-date=24 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 August 2002, IR began online train reservations and ticketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irctc.co.in/eticketing/loginHome.jsf|title=IRCTC Next Generation eTicketing System|website=www.irctc.co.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724151246/https://www.irctc.co.in/eticketing/loginHome.jsf|archive-date=24 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Railway Budget was presented every year, a few days before the Union budget, till 2016. Modi government on 21 September 2016 approved [[Railway budget of India|merger of the Rail and General budgets]] from next year, ending a 92-year-old practice of a separate budget for the nation's largest transporter. Railways Minister Suresh Prabhu said that his merger proposal was in the long term interest of railways as well as the country's economy\n\nOn 31 March 2017, Indian Railways announced that the country's entire rail network would be electrified by 2022 or 2023, and become a net-zero railway by 2030.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/48-per-cent-rail-tracks-electrified-aim-to-double-it-in-5-years-govt-4594389/|title=48 per cent rail tracks electrified, aim to double it in 5 years: Govt|date=31 March 2017|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718224354/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/48-per-cent-rail-tracks-electrified-aim-to-double-it-in-5-years-govt-4594389/|archive-date=18 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Tanna Village and Smaller Viaduct (12671597053).jpg|alt=A stone bridge|The smaller railway viaduct near Thane in 1855\nFile:Tanna Railway Viaduct (9142699593).jpg|alt=Train on a stone bridge with girder|The longer railway viaduct near Thane in 1855\nFile:India railways1909a.jpg|alt=Railway map|Railway map of India in 1909\n</gallery>On 22 March 2020, Indian Railways announced a nationwide shutdown of passenger rail service to combat the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]. This became part of a [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] to slow the spread of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/03/23/coronavirus-indian-railways-cancels-passenger-train-services/|title=Indian Railways cancels passenger train services|website=Business Traveller|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The railway shutdown was initially scheduled to last from 23 to 31 March,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrosaga.com/indian-railways-suspends-all-passenger-trains-but-theres-some-good-news/|title=Indian Railways Suspends All Passenger Trains But There\u2019s Some Good News|last=HP|first=Akarsh|date=2020-03-22|website=MetroSaga|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> but the nationwide lockdown, as announced by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 24 March, was to last 21 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/coronavirus-puts-over-1-billion-people-in-india-on-21-day-lockdown-to-combat-spread.html|title=Coronavirus puts over 1 billion people in India on 21-day lockdown to combat spread|last=Miller|first=Adam Jeffery,Hannah|date=2020-03-26|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The national rail network is maintaining its freight operations during the lockdown, to transport essential goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/indian-railways-continuing-its-freight-operations-post-22-march-lockdown-11585314775866.html|title=How Indian Railways continuing its freight operations post lockdown|last=Nandi|first=Tamal|date=2020-03-27|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> On 29 March, Indian Railways announced that it would start service for special parcel trains to transport essential goods, in addition to regular freight service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-railways-resumes-parcel-trains-to-transport-essential-goods-11585504148683.html|title=Covid-19: Railways resumes parcel trains to transport essential goods|last=Nandi|first=Shreya|date=2020-03-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail operator has also announced plans to convert coaches into isolation wards for patients of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-indian-railways-converts-non-ac-train-coach-into-isolation-ward-on-trial-basis-8201221.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Indian Railways converts non-AC train coach into isolation ward on trial basis|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n=== {{anchor|Organisational structure}}Structure ===\n{{Main|Indian Railways organisational structure|Zones and divisions of Indian Railways}}\n\nIndian Railways is headed by a seven-member [[Railway Board]] whose chairman reports to the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]. Railway Board also acts as the Ministry of Railways. The officers manning the office of Railway Board are mostly from organised Group A Railway Services and [[Railway Board Secretariat Service]]. IR is divided into 18 zones, headed by general managers who report to the Railway Board.<ref name=\"IRStruct\">{{cite web|title=Organization Structure|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Organisation_Structure_Eng_pdf.pdf|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=2 March 2017|format=PDF|date=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517005226/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Organisation_Structure_Eng_pdf.pdf|archive-date=17 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Railways Report|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=2 March 2017|format=PDF|date=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517103428/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|archive-date=17 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The zones are further subdivided into 68 operating [[Zones and divisions of Indian Railways|divisions]], headed by divisional railway managers (DRM).<ref>{{cite news | first = Vijay Pratap | last = Singh | title = SMS complaint system: A Northern Railway brainwave spreads | date = 27 February 2010 | url = http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sms-complaint-system-a-northern-railway-brainwave-spreads/585107/0 | work = [[Indian Express]] | accessdate = 19 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Stats_2012\">{{cite book| title = Indian Railways Facts and Figures (2011\u20132012)| url = http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,554,1275| publisher = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]], [[Government of India]]| year = 2012| page = personnel| accessdate = 21 July 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014175900/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,554,1275| archive-date = 14 October 2013| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Zones and their Divisions in Indian Railways |url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |publisher=Indian Railways |accessdate=26 August 2011 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319003737/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |archivedate=19 March 2015  }}</ref> The divisional officers of the engineering, mechanical, electrical, signal and telecommunication, stores, accounts, personnel, operating, commercial, security and safety branches report to their respective DRMs and are tasked with the operation and maintenance of assets. Station masters control individual stations and train movements through their stations' territory. In addition, there are a number of production units, training establishments, public sector enterprises and other offices working under the control of the Railway Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|title=stats-network|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619112957/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Subsidiaries and undertakings ===\nIR is a major shareholder in 16 [[State-owned enterprise|public sector undertakings (PSU)]] and other organizations that are related to rail transport in India. Notable among this list include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/25.pdf|title=Indian Railways Annual Publication 2016\u201317 \u2013 Undertakings|date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301171434/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/25.pdf|archive-date=1 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFinancing, construction and project implementation: [[Indian Railway Finance Corporation|IRFC]], [[RITES]], [[Ircon International|IRCON]], [[Mumbai Railway Vikas Corporation|MRVC]], [[Rail Vikas Nigam Limited|RVNL]]\n\nLand and station development: [[Rail Land Development Authority|RLDA]], [[Indian Railway Stations Development Corporation|IRSDC]]\n\nRail infrastructure: [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|DFCCIL]], PRCL<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pipavavrailway.com/ |title=PRCL |access-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024204707/http://www.pipavavrailway.com/ |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nPassenger and freight train operations: [[Konkan Railway Corporation|KRCL]], [[Container Corporation of India|CONCOR]]\n\nIT and communications: [[Centre for Railway Information Systems|CRIS]], [[RailTel Corporation of India|RCIL]]\n\nCatering and tourism: [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]]\n\n=== Human resources ===\n{{Main|Centralised Training Institutes of the Indian Railways}}\n\nStaff are classified into [[Gazetted Officer (India)|gazetted]] (Groups A and B) and non-gazetted (Groups C and D) employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,388|title=Railway Board Directorates|work=INDIAN RAILWAY ESTABLISHMENT CODE|publisher=Indian Railways|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530064841/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,388|archive-date=30 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Gazetted employees carry out executive / managerial / officer level tasks. As of March 2017, the number of personnel (Groups A & B) constitutes 1.2% of the total strength, while Group C & D account for 92.6%  and 6.2% respectively.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/16.pdf|title=stats-personnel|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 \u2013 Personnel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223051733/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/16.pdf|archive-date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere is no direct recruitment of Group B employees in Indian Railways and they are recruited by departmental promotional exams of Group C employees. Recruitment of Group A employees is carried out by the [[Union Public Service Commission]] Civil Service exam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irts.org.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,409|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802173355/http://www.irts.org.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,409|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 August 2012|title=Indian Railways level which constitutes the Governing Council of Association|publisher=irts.org.in}}</ref> Recruitment of Group C junior engineers and depot material superintendents is conducted by the Railway Recruitment Board. Group C employees are recruited by 21 Railway Recruitment Board or RRB, which are controlled by the [[Railway Recruitment Control Board]] (RRB).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rrcb.gov.in/rrbs.html|title=Indian Railways Establishment Manual|publisher=rrcb.gov.in|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525103317/http://rrcb.gov.in/RRBS.HTML|archive-date=25 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/education/rrb-ntpc-exam-2016-postponed-new-dates-to-release-soon/|title=RRB NTPC exam 2016|publisher=indianexpress.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720032851/http://indianexpress.com/article/education/rrb-ntpc-exam-2016-postponed-new-dates-to-release-soon/|archive-date=20 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Group D staffs are recruited by 16 Railway Recruitment Cells or RRCs.\n\nThe training of all groups is shared among seven centralized zonal training institutes and 295 training centers all over India.\n\nIR offers housing and runs its own hospitals, schools and sports facilities for the welfare of its staff.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Rolling stock ==\n\n=== Locomotives ===\n{{Main|Locomotives of India}}\n[[File:11308 WAP7 030418.jpg|alt=Light-coloured electric locomotive|thumb|Ajni Loco Shed [[WAP-7]]-class [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] [[Alternating current|AC]] electric locomotive]]\n[[File:WDM-3D class Locomotive of Indian Railway.jpg|thumb|alt=Blue diesel locomotive hauling a passenger train|[[ALCO DL560C|WDM-3D]] broad-gauge diesel locomotive]]\n[[File:Steam Locomotive, Nilgiri Mountain Railway, May 2010.JPG|alt=Black steam locomotive at a station|thumb|The [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]], which uses one of India's few running steam locomotives]]\n\nIndia uses [[Electric locomotive|electric]] and [[diesel locomotive]]s, along with a few [[Compressed natural gas|CNG]] (compressed natural gas) locomotives.<ref>{{cite news |title=India's first CNG train flagged off |url=http://www.rediff.com/business/report/pix-indias-first-cng-train-flagged-off/20150115.htm |access-date=26 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226164505/http://www.rediff.com/business/report/pix-indias-first-cng-train-flagged-off/20150115.htm |archive-date=26 February 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Steam locomotive]]s are no longer in use, except in [[restored train|heritage trains]]. [[Locomotive]]s in India are classified by gauge, motive power, the work they are suited for, and their power or model number. Their four- or five-letter class name includes this information. The first letter denotes the track gauge, the second their motive power (diesel or electric), and the third their suitable traffic (goods, passenger, multi or shunting). The fourth letter denoted the locomotive's chronological model number, but in 2002, a new classification was adopted in which the fourth letter in newer diesel locomotives indicate [[horsepower]] range.\n\nA locomotive may have a fifth letter in its name, denoting a technical variant, subclass, or sub-type (a variation in the basic model (or series) or a different motor or manufacturer). In the new diesel-locomotive classification, the fifth letter refines the horsepower in 100-hp increments: A for 100&nbsp;hp, B for 200&nbsp;hp, C for 300&nbsp;hp and so on. In this classification, a WDM-3A is a 3100&nbsp;hp, a WDM-3D a 3400&nbsp;hp and a WDM-3F a 3600&nbsp;hp locomotive.{{efn|This classification system does not apply to steam locomotives, which retained their original class names (such as M class or [[Indian locomotive class WP|WP class]]).}} Diesel locomotives are fitted with auxiliary power units, which save almost 88 percent of fuel during idle time when a train is not running.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology allows Railways to save Rs 20 Lakhs Diesel per Engine|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/new-technology-allows-railways-to-save-rs-20-lakhs-diesel-per-engine/|accessdate=6 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908145226/http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/new-technology-allows-railways-to-save-rs-20-lakhs-diesel-per-engine/|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Goods wagons ===\n{{see also|Wagon numbering system in India|label 2=Wagon numbering system}}\nAs of March 2017, IR fleet consisted of 277,987 [[goods wagon]]s. They carried 1,110&nbsp;million tonnes of freight in Fiscal Year 2016\u201317.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> [[Wagon numbering system in India|Wagon types used by IR]] include BCACBM, BCCN, BCNA, BCNHL, BOBRN, BOBYN, BOXN (BOXN-HL, BOXN-HS, BOXN-HL, BOXN-CR, BOXN-LW, BOXN-AL, BOXN-EL), BRH, BTPGLN, BTPN and VVN.\n\nIR's bulk requirement of wagons is met by wagon manufacturing units both in public and private sectors as well as other Public Sector Units under the administrative control of Ministry of Railways.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/12.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 : Rolling Stock Summary|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032243/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/12.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Passenger coaches ===\nOn long-distance routes and also on some shorter routes, IR uses 2 primary types of coach design types. [[ICF coaches]], in production from 1955 until Jan 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/railminindia/status/956485140451962881?lang=en|title=End of an Era - The historic last ICF Coach was flagged off by Senior Techcnician Shri Bhaskar P in the presence of Railway Board Chairman Shri @AshwaniLohani. The 1st ICF coach had been flagged by Prime Minister Shri Lal Bahadur Shastri on 2 October, 1955.pic.twitter.com/qCfl8tVrQy|last=Railways|first=Ministry of|date=25 January 2018|website=@railminindia|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://twitter.com/railminindia/status/956485140451962881?lang=en|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> constitute the bulk of the current stock. These coaches, considered to be having inadequate safety features, are slowly being phased out. As of September 2017, around 40,000 coaches are still in operation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/after-spate-of-accidents-indian-railways-speeds-up-safety-plan-check-out-the-massive-task-and-big-numbers-involved/844454/|title=After spate of accidents, Indian Railways speeds up safety plan; check out the massive task and big numbers involved|date=7 September 2017|work=The Financial Express|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041740/http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/after-spate-of-accidents-indian-railways-speeds-up-safety-plan-check-out-the-massive-task-and-big-numbers-involved/844454/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The older coaches are being replaced with [[LHB coaches]]. Introduced in mid '90s, these coaches are lighter, safer and are capable of speeds up to {{convert|160|km/h||abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=April 2017|title=Indian Railways Passenger Coaches: Safety Features and Technologies Adopted|url=http://www.ijetsr.com/images/short_pdf/1492945632_nitttr232_Ijetsr_skype.pdf|journal=International Journal of Engineering Technology Science and Research|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041703/http://www.ijetsr.com/images/short_pdf/1492945632_nitttr232_Ijetsr_skype.pdf|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIR has announced that two new self-propelled train set designs will be introduced starting from mid 2018. These two train types, termed as [[Vande Bharat Express|Train-18]] and [[Train 20|Train-20]], are expected to replace locomotive-hauled trains on long-distance routes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/128617/train-18-train-20-indian-railways/|title=At 176 Kmph, These Two Upcoming Trains May Be India's Fastest Ever!|date=22 January 2018|work=The Better India|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100703/https://www.thebetterindia.com/128617/train-18-train-20-indian-railways/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn regional short-distance routes, IR runs [[MEMU|Mainline Electrical Multiple Unit (MEMU)]] or [[DEMU|Diesel Electrical Multiple Unit (DEMU)]] trains, depending on the traction available. These train sets are self-propelled with capability for faster acceleration or deceleration and are expected to reduce congestion on dense routes. Passenger locomotive-hauled trains, having frequent stops, are slowly being replaced with train sets across India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Loco-hauled-commuter-trains-to-be-replaced-with-DEMU/MEMU/articleshow/54680592.cms|title=Loco hauled commuter trains to be replaced with DEMU/MEMU \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226042551/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Loco-hauled-commuter-trains-to-be-replaced-with-DEMU/MEMU/articleshow/54680592.cms|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn suburban commuter routes around the large urban centers, IR runs trains with [[Electric multiple unit|Electric Multiple Unit (EMU)]] coaches. As of March 2017, about 9100 coaches are in operation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/13.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 \u2013 Rolling Stock|date=25 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041530/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/13.pdf|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Manufacturing ==\n\nIndian Railways is a [[Vertical integration|vertically-integrated]] organization that produces majority of its locomotives & rolling stock at in-house production units, with a few recent exceptions.\n\n'''Locomotives:'''\n* [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]] in [[Chittaranjan]], [[West Bengal]] manufactures electric locomotives.\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] in [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] manufactures diesel & electric locomotives. \n* [[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra|Diesel Locomotive Factory]] in [[Marhowra]], [[Bihar]], a [[Joint Venture]] of [[Indian Railway]]s & [[General Electric]] manufactures high capacity diesel locomotives, used especially for freight transportation.\n* [[Electric Locomotive Factory, Madhepura|Electric Locomotive Factory]] in [[Madhepura]], [[Bihar]], a [[Joint Venture]] of [[Indian Railway]]s and [[Alstom|Alstom SA]] manufactures electric locomotives.\n*[[Diesel-Loco Modernisation Works]] in [[Patiala]], [[Punjab]] upgrades and overhauls locomotives. They also manufacture electric locomotives\n\n'''Rolling Stock:'''\n* [[Integral Coach Factory]] in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Rail Coach Factory]] in [[Kapurthala]], [[Punjab]] \n* [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]] in [[Raebareli]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n*[[Integral Coach Factory|Coach Manufacturing Unit]] in [[Haldia]], [[West Bengal]]\n\n'''Wheel & Axle:'''\n\n* [[Rail Wheel Factory]] in [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Plant, Bela]] in [[Chhapra]], [[Bihar]]\n\nThe repair and maintenance of this vast fleet of rolling stock is carried out at 44 loco sheds, 212 carriage & wagon repair units and 45 periodic overhaul workshops across various zones of IR.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Network ==\n\n=== Tracks ===\n[[File:Project Unigauge (India).svg|thumb|Comparison of gauges in India with the standard gauge]]\n{{see also|Project Unigauge}}\n\nAs of March 2017, IR network spans {{convert|121,407|km||abbr=on}} of track length, while the route length is {{convert|67,368|km||abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Indian Railways, as of 1 April 2019, had a broad-gauge network of {{cvt|64,298|km}}. Of this, {{cvt|35,488|km}} was electrified. Track sections are rated for speeds ranging from {{convert|80|to|200|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, though the maximum speed attained by passenger trains is 180&nbsp;km/h (110&nbsp;mph) during trial runs. As of March 2017, most of the broad-gauge network is equipped with [[Track (rail transport)#Continuous welded rail|long-welded]], high-tensile strength [[Rail profile#Rail weights and sizes|52kg/60kg 90 UTS]] rails and [[prestressed concrete|pre-stressed concrete (PSC)]] sleepers with elastic fastenings.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n{{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}} [[broad gauge]] is the predominant [[track gauge|gauge]] used by IR and spans {{convert|61,680|km|abbr=on}} of route (92% of total route network). It is among the broadest gauge in use across the world for passenger movement.<ref name=\":4\" /> Broad gauge generated 100% of the freight output (Net tonne-Kilometres) and more than 99% of the passenger output (Passenger Kilometres) in the fiscal year 2016\u201317.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}} tracks and {{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}} and {{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}} [[narrow gauge]] tracks are present on fewer routes. All of these routes, except the heritage routes, are being converted to broad gauge. The metre gauge tracks were {{convert|3479|km|}} (5% of total route network) and narrow gauges tracks were {{convert|2208|km||abbr=on}} (3% of total route network) {{as of|2017|March|31|lc=y|post=.}}<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Electrification ===\n{{Main|Central Organisation for Railway Electrification}}\n\nAs of 31 March 2019, IR has electrified 50% or {{convert|35,442|km||abbr=on}} of the route kilometers and 46% or {{convert|55,240|km||abbr=on}} of the total running track. India uses [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25 kV 50 Hz AC]] traction on all its electrified tracks.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" />\n\n[[File:State Wise Position of Electric Traction of Rail Network in India.png|thumb|right|Total Route Kilometers Covered in the State as on 2018 (In Percentage).]]\n\nRailway electrification in India began with the first electric train, between [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus]] and [[Kurla]] on the Harbour Line, on 3 February 1925 on the [[Great Indian Peninsula Railway]] (GIPR) at 1500 V DC. Heavy gradients in the [[Western Ghats]] necessitated the introduction of electric traction on the GIPR to [[Igatpuri]] on the North East line and [[Pune]] on the South East line. On 5 January 1928 1500 V DC traction was introduced on the suburban section of the [[Bombay, Baroda and Central India Railway]] between [[Colaba]] and [[Borivili]], and between [[Madras]] Beach and [[Tambaram]] of the [[Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway]] on 11 May 1931, to meet growing traffic needs.<ref name=\"ELECT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,532 |title=Brief on Railway Electrification |access-date=1 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926072829/http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,532 |archive-date=26 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The 3000 V DC electrification of the [[Howrah]]-[[Burdwan]] section of the [[Eastern Railway Zone (India)|Eastern Railway]] was completed in 1958. The first 3000 V DC [[electric multiple unit|EMU]] service began on the [[Howrah]]-[[Sheoraphuli]] section on 14 December 1957.<ref name=\"ELECT\"/>\n\nResearch and trials in [[Europe]], particularly on French Railways ([[SNCF]]), indicated that 25 kV AC was an economical electrification system. Indian Railways decided in 1957 to adopt 25 kV AC as its standard, with SNCF their consultant in the early stages. The first 25 kV AC section was Raj Kharswan\u2013Dongoaposi on the [[South Eastern Railway Zone, India|South Eastern Railway]] in 1960. The first 25 kV AC [[electric multiple unit|EMUs]], for [[Kolkata]] suburban service, began service in September 1962. For continuity, the Howrah\u2013Burdwan section of the Eastern Railway and the Madras Beach\u2013Tambaram section of the Southern Railway were converted to 25 kV AC by 1968. Because of limitations in the DC traction system, a decision was made to convert the electric traction system of the Mumbai suburban rail network of WR and CR from 1.5kV DC to 25 kV AC in 1996\u201397. The conversion from DC to AC traction was completed in 2012 by Western Railway, and in 2016 by Central Railway. Since then, the entire electrified mainline rail network in India uses 25 kV AC, and DC traction is used only for metros and trams.<ref name=\"ELECT\"/>\n\n[[File:Railway Electrification Rate for Leading & Laggard State\u2019s of India 2018.png|thumb|left|Railway electrification rate for leading and laggard states of India]]\n[[File:Railway-Electrification-Trend-&-Roadmap-for-India-till-FY-2022.png|thumb|right|Railway electrification trend and road map for India until FY 2022]]\n\nIndian Railways announced on 31 March 2017 that the country's entire rail network would be electrified by 2022.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\"/><ref name=\"enincon1\">{{cite web|url=https://enincon.com/report/railway-electrification-market-opportunities-in-india-2018/|title=Railway Electrification Market in India 2018|date=20 February 2018|publisher=Enincon|access-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230336/https://enincon.com/report/railway-electrification-market-opportunities-in-india-2018/|archive-date=20 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThough not a nascent concept, the electrification in India now has been committed with a fresh investment of {{INRConvert|35000|c}} to electrify the entire network and eliminate the cost of fuel under transportation which will amount to a massive savings of {{INRConvert|10500|c}} overall. This will be a boon for savings for the Government to channelize the investments in modernization of the railway infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enincon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Railway-Electrification-Market-in-India-2018_Flyer.pdf|title=Railway Electrification Market in India 2018|date=20 February 2018|publisher=Enincon|access-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320170538/https://enincon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Railway-Electrification-Market-in-India-2018_Flyer.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClose to 30&nbsp;billion units of electricity will be required for railway electrification on an annual basis by 2022, leading to excellent opportunities for IPPs of conventional power.<ref name=\"enincon1\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n=== Signaling and telecommunication ===\n{{See also|Railway signal|Railway signalling}}\nIR uses a range of signalling technologies and methods to manage its train operations based on traffic density and safety requirements.\n\nAs of March 2017, around {{convert|2850|km|abbr=on}} of the route uses [[Automatic block signaling|automatic block signalling]] for train operations \u2013 concentrated in high density routes, large cities and junctions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/10.pdf|title=Indian Railways \u2013 Statistical Publication 2016\u201317 \u2013 Signalling and Telecom|date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044403/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/10.pdf|archive-date=1 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Remaining routes are based on [[absolute block signalling]] with trains manually controlled by signal men from the signal boxes typically located at stations. Few low density routes still use [[North American railway signaling#Absolute or manual block|manual block signalling]] methods with communication on track clearance based on physical exchange of tokens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://railscapestravel.com/2017/07/25/art-of-the-token-exchange/|title=Art of the token exchange|date=25 July 2017|work=Railscapes|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228233429/http://railscapestravel.com/2017/07/25/art-of-the-token-exchange/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a few sections, intermediate block signalling is provided to further enhance line capacity with minimal investment. As of March 2017, 501 block sections have intermediate block signals on IR.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIR primarily uses [[railway signal#Color light signals|coloured signal lights]], which replaced [[railway signal#Mechanical signals|semaphores and disc-based signalling]] (dependent on position or colour).<ref name=\"irfcasignal\">{{cite web |title=Signalling System |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-signal.html |accessdate =4 June 2007 |work=IRFCA.org |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> IR uses two-aspect, three-aspect and four (or multiple) aspect color signalling across its network.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-signal2.html |title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Signal Aspects and Indications \u2013  Principal Running Signals |website=www.irfca.org|access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSignals at most stations are interlocked using [[Interlocking#Electro-mechanical interlocking|panel interlocking]], [[Interlocking#Relay interlocking|route-relay interlocking]] or [[Interlocking#Electronic interlocking|electronic interlocking]] methods that eliminate scope for human signalling errors. IR uses [[track circuit]]ing, and block proving [[axle counter]]s for train detection.\n\nAs of March 2017, 5584 stations across IR (about 90% of stations on broad gauge) have interlocked stations and multi-aspect signalling. Around 99% of key routes (A, B, C and D) have track circuitry or block proving axle counters for automated train detection. Also, IR has about 51,000 route kilometers of [[optical fiber cable]] network across India, that is used for train control, voice and data communication. Around {{convert|2500|km|abbr=on}} of the route is covered by [[GSM-R]] based Mobile Train Radio Communication.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2017, IR announced that it will implement [[European Train Control System|ETCS Level 2]] system for signalling and control on key routes with an investment of {{INRConvert|12000|c|lk=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/tech/news-analysis/indian-railways-clears-proposal-to-equip-electric-locomotives-with-european-train-protection-systems-4263417.html|title=Indian Railways clears proposal to equip electric locomotives with European train protection systems- Technology News, Firstpost|website=Tech2|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203235730/http://www.firstpost.com/tech/news-analysis/indian-railways-clears-proposal-to-equip-electric-locomotives-with-european-train-protection-systems-4263417.html|archive-date=3 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently IR uses [[Centralized traffic control|Centralised Traffic Control (CTC)]] on the busy Ghaziabad \u2013 Kanpur route and real-time train monitoring systems on [[Mumbai]] and [[Kolkata]] suburban routes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== {{anchor|Rail links with adjacent countries}}Links with adjacent countries ===\nRail links between India and neighboring countries are not well developed.\n\nTwo trains operate to [[Transport in Pakistan|Pakistan]]: the ''[[Samjhauta Express]]'' between [[Delhi]] and [[Lahore]] and the ''[[Thar Express]]'' between [[Jodhpur]] and [[Karachi]]. However, as of August 2019, they have been cancelled due to the [[Kashmir conflict|tension over Kashmir]]. [[Transport in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]] is connected by the four times a week ''[[Maitree Express]]'' that runs from [[Kolkata]] to [[Dhaka]] and weekly ''[[Bandhan Express]]'' which began running commercial trips between [[Kolkata]] and [[Khulna]] in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kolkata-khulna-bandhan-express-new-passenger-train-between-west-bengal-and-bangladesh-launched-5-poi-1773162 |title=Bandhan Express, New Train Between Bengal And Bangladesh: 10 Facts |work=NDTV.com |access-date=16 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116133418/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kolkata-khulna-bandhan-express-new-passenger-train-between-west-bengal-and-bangladesh-launched-5-poi-1773162 |archive-date=16 November 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/bandhan-express-makes-its-first-run-between-kolkata-khulna-india-bangladesh-on-thursday-4939545/|title=Bandhan Express makes its first commercial run between Kolkata and Khulna today|date=24 November 2019|work=The Indian Express|access-date=16 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116063408/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/bandhan-express-makes-its-first-run-between-kolkata-khulna-india-bangladesh-on-thursday-4939545/|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTwo rail links to [[Transport in Nepal|Nepal]] exist: passenger service between [[Jainagar, Bihar|Jainagar]] and [[Bijalpura]] and freight services between [[Raxaul]] and [[Birganj]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[India]]n and [[Bangladeshi]] governments has started work on a new rail link to ease surface transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inserbia.info/today/2014/06/construction-work-of-new-india-bangladesh-railway-link-to-begin-in-2015/|title=Construction Work Of New India-Bangladesh Railway Link To Begin In 2015|author=Das, Koushik |work=InSerbia News|access-date=26 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909150606/http://inserbia.info/today/2014/06/construction-work-of-new-india-bangladesh-railway-link-to-begin-in-2015/|archive-date=9 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> India will build a {{convert|13|km||adj=on|abbr=on}} railway linking [[Tripura]]'s capital [[Agartala]] with Bangladesh's southeastern city of [[Akhaura]], an important railway junction connected to [[Chittagong port]], resource-rich [[Sylhet]] and [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/work-on-new-indiabangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/480099-61.html |title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015-INews \u2013 IBNLive Mobile |date=18 June 2014 |work=IBNlive |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081939/http://m.ibnlive.com/news/work-on-new-indiabangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/480099-61.html |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> An agreement to implement the railway project was signed between the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] and Bangladesh Premier [[Sheikh Hasina]] during the latter's visit to India in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/indian-railway-to-build-a-15-km-track-linking-agartala-with-bangladesh/1/235817.html |title=Indian Railway to build a 15-km track linking Agartala with Bangladesh |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131837/http://m.indiatoday.in/story/indian-railway-to-build-a-15-km-track-linking-agartala-with-bangladesh/1/235817.html |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Total cost of the proposed project is estimated at {{INRConvert|252|c}}. The Indian Railway Construction Company (IRCON) is constructing the new railway tracks on both sides of the border. Of the {{convert|13|km|abbr=on}} rail line, {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} of tracks fall in Indian territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/guwahati/Work-on-Agartala-Akhaura-rail-link-to-commence-soon/articleshow/36756922.cms|title=Work on Agartala-Akhaura rail link to commence soon|work=The Times of India|access-date=26 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006122942/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/guwahati/Work-on-Agartala-Akhaura-rail-link-to-commence-soon/articleshow/36756922.cms|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms |title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718085020/http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms |archive-date=18 July 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Northeast Frontier Railways]] (NFR) is laying the connecting tracks for the new rail link on the Indian side, up to Tripura's southern-most border town, [[Sabroom railway station|Sabroom]] \u2013 {{convert|135|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Agartala]]. From [[Sabroom]], the [[Chittagong]] international sea port is {{convert|72|km|abbr=on}} away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meghalayatimes.info/index.php/region/13394-india-bangladesh-align-rail-link-in-tripura |title=India, Bangladesh align rail link in Tripura |work=Meghalaya Times |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006100230/http://www.meghalayatimes.info/index.php/region/13394-india-bangladesh-align-rail-link-in-tripura |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNo rail link currently exist with [[Transport in Myanmar|Myanmar]], but a railway line is to be built from [[Jiribam]] (in Manipur) to [[Tamu, Myanmar|Tamu]] through [[Imphal]] and [[Moreh, India|Moreh]].<ref name=\"imphalmorehline\">{{cite news |url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/IA03Df01.html |title=India's rail-building challenge |date=3 January 2007 |work=By Sudha Ramachandran|publisher=[[Asia Times]] |page=2 |accessdate=16 April 2009}}</ref> The construction of this missing link, as per the feasibility study conducted by the Ministry of External Affairs through [[RITES]] Ltd, is estimated to cost {{INRConvert|29.41|b}}.<ref name=\"tamujiribamrail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.siliconindia.com/shownews/India_signs_transAsian_railways_pact-nid-36316.html |title=India signs trans-Asian railways pact |date=2 July 2007 <!-- , 12:30 hrs -->|publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]|page=1|accessdate=16 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn {{convert|18|km|adj=on|abbr=on}} railway link with [[Transport in Bhutan|Bhutan]] is being constructed from [[Hashimara]] in West Bengal to Toribari in Bhutan.\n\nNo rail link currently exist with either [[China]] or [[Transport in Sri Lanka|Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-inter.html |title=IRFCA:Indian Railways FAQ:Geography:International |publisher=IRFCA, website of the Indian Railway Fan Club |accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n=== {{anchor|Passenger services}}Passenger service ===\n\n==== {{anchor|Categories of stations| Station categories |Types of stations| Station types}} Station categories ====\nFrom December 2017, stations are categorised into the Non-Suburban Groups NSG1 to NSG6, the Suburban Groups SG1 to SG3, and the Halt Groups HG1 to HG3 based on the earnings, passenger footfall, and strategic importance.<ref name=stac1/>\n\nBefore December 2017, stations were classified into A1, A, B, C, D, E, and F categories, based only on the passenger earnings from the sales of platform tickets, thus limiting the ability of IR to better focus its investments in passenger amenities.<ref name=stac1>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/railways-revise-station-categories-to-improve-services/articleshow/62280609.cms Railways revise station categories to improve services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317035551/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/railways-revise-station-categories-to-improve-services/articleshow/62280609.cms |date=17 March 2018 }}, [[The Economic Times|Economic Times]], 28 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==== {{anchor|Classes of service | Travel class| Travel type category}} Travel classes ====\n{{Main|Indian Railways coaching stock}}\n[[File:Rajdhani First AC1.jpg|thumb|alt=See caption|Interior of a first-class compartment on the [[Rajdhani Express]]]]\n[[File:Inside a 3-tier AC Compartment Dakshin Express.jpg|thumb|alt=Train compartment with two seats and a bed|Interior of a three-tier compartment on the Dakshin Express]]\n[[File:Habibganj-JabalpurJS.jpg|thumb|alt=Train car with many passenger seats|Interior of an air-conditioned chair-car coach on the [[Jan Shatabdi Express]]]]\n[[File:Inside an Indian Railways Train - Sleeper Coach.jpg|thumb|Interior of a sleeper coach]]\n\nIR has several classes of travel, with or without air-conditioning. A train may have one or several classes. Slow passenger trains have only unreserved seating, and the [[Rajdhani Express]], [[Shatabdi Express]], [[Garib Rath Express]], [[Double Decker Express]], [[Tejas Express]], [[Humsafar Express]] , [[Duronto Express]] , [[Yuva Express]], and [[Vande Bharat Express]] have only air-conditioned classes. Fares for all classes differ, and unreserved seating is the least expensive. Fares for the Rajdhani, Duronto Shatabdi and Vande Bharat Express trains include food. In September 2016, IR introduced dynamic fares for the Rajdhani, Duronto and Shatabdi trains (except 1AC and EC classes) to increase revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/indian-railways-ticket-price-hike-50-percent-rajdhani-shatabdi-3019567/|title=Premium railway fares hiked up to 50 per cent in new dynamic pricing model|date=8 September 2016|access-date=8 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909054512/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/indian-railways-ticket-price-hike-50-percent-rajdhani-shatabdi-3019567/|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Long-distance trains usually include a [[pantry car]], and food is served at the passengers' berth or seat. Luxury trains (such as [[Palace on Wheels]]) have separate dining cars, but these trains cost as much as\u2014or more than\u2014a five-star hotel room.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eman |first1=Borhan |title=Indian railway ready for 'privatization to run trains'! Meramaal Wiki |url=https://www.wiki.meramaal.com/2019/06/20/indian-railway-knockout-of-privatization/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=Meramaal News |date=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nA standard passenger rake has four unreserved (general) compartments, two at the front and two at the rear (one of which may be for women). The number of other coaches varies by demand and route. A luggage compartment may be at the front or the rear. On some mail trains, a separate mail coach is attached. Lavatories are communal, and [[Squat toilet|Indian-]] and Western-style. The classes in operation are (although a train may not have all these classes):\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\"\n! Class<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/class_Code.html|title=Accommodation Classes in Indian Railways|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=15 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426000003/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/class_Code.html|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! Description<ref name=irfcatravel>{{cite web| title = General Information on travelling by IR|work=IRFCA.org| url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-travel.html| accessdate =3 June 2007|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref><ref name=indrailuk>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiarail.co.uk/indrail.htm |title=Class of Travel |accessdate=3 June 2007 |work=indiarail.co.uk |publisher=S.D. Enterprises Ltd |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513200442/http://www.indiarail.co.uk/indrail.htm |archive-date=13 May 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Saloon''' \n|IR has started to operate saloon coaches to give hotel ambience on trains. These coaches operate on charter basis i.e. booking is required. These have a master bedroom, one normal bedroom, one kitchen and window trailing. Four to six extra beds are given to accommodate more people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianluxurytrains.com/home-on-wheels/|title=Home on Wheels - Luxury Train Travel in an Exclusive Railway Saloon|website=www.indianluxurytrains.com}}</ref> First of these coach was attached to [[Jammu Mail]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ready-to-shell-out-more-now-you-can-travel-in-railways-luxury-saloons/jammu-mail/slideshow/63554248.cms|title=Ready to shell out more! Now you can travel in Railways' luxury saloons - Jammu Mail|website=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''1A'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''AC first class''': The most luxurious and expensive class of Indian Railways, with fares almost at par with airfares. There are eight cabins (including two coupes) in a full AC first class coach and three cabins (including one coupe) in a half AC first class coach. The coach has a dedicated attendant and bedding is included in the fare. This air-conditioned coach, present only on popular routes, can carry 18 (full coach) or 10 passengers (half coach).\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''2A'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC two tier''': These air-conditioned coaches have sleeping berths across eight bays (full coach). Berths are usually arranged in two tiers in bays of six: four across the width of the coach and two lengthwise across the corridor, with curtains along the corridor. Bedding is included in the fare. A coach can carry 48 (full coach) or 20 passengers (half coach).\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''3A'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC three tier''': Air-conditioned coaches with 64 sleeping berths. Berths are similar to 2A, but with three tiers across the width and two lengthwise for eight bays of eight. They are slightly less well-appointed, usually with no reading lights or curtains. Bedding is included in the fare.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''3E'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC three tier (economy)''': Air-conditioned coaches with 81 sleeping berths on the [[Garib Rath Express]]. Berths are usually arranged as in 3A, but with three tiers across the width and three lengthwise. Appointments are similar to 3A, but bedding is not included. These coaches are also present in some [[Duronto Express]] trains as well.\n|-\n|'''Vistadome'''\n|IR operates Vistadome glass roof coaches on some tourist routes. These include Araku Valley, [[Konkan Railway]], [[Kalka\u2013Shimla railway|Kalka-Shimla Railway]], Kashmir Valley, Kangra Valley and Neral-Matheran Route. These coaches' fares are equivalent to AC Executive Chair Car. IR also has plans to start Vistadome on [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyoooz.com/news/chennai/858438/icf-to-design-airconditioned-coach-for-nilgiri-mountain-railway/|title=ICF to design air-conditioned coach for Nilgiri Mountain Railway &#124; Chennai NYOOOZ|website=NYOOOZ}}</ref>\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''EA'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Anubhuti''': Air-conditioned top-end class of [[Shatabdi Express]]. These coaches were introduced in January 2018. The first train to get these coaches was the [[Chennai Central\u2013Mysuru Shatabdi Express]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''EC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Executive chair car''': An air-conditioned coach with spacious seats and legroom. With four seats in a row, it is used for intercity day travel and is available on the [[Tejas Express|Tejas]] , [[Shatabdi Express]] and [[Vande Bharat Express]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''CC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''AC chair car''': An air-conditioned coach with five seats in a row, used for intercity day travel. Air-conditioned double-deck coaches are used on the [[Double Decker Express]], Shatabdi Express, Vande Bharat Express, and Intercity services.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''SL'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Sleeper class''': The sleeper class is the most common coach on IR, with ten or more SL coaches attached to a train rake. They are sleeping coaches with three berths across the width and two lengthwise, without air-conditioning. They carry 72 passengers per coach.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2S'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Second seater''': similar to CC, but without air-conditioning. Double-deck second seaters are used on the [[Flying Ranee]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''UR/GEN'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Unreserved/General''': The least-expensive accommodation, with a seat not guaranteed. Tickets are valid on any train on a route if used within 24 hours of purchase.\n|}\n\nAt the rear of the train is the [[Brake van#India|guard's cabin]]. It contains a [[transceiver]], and is where the guard usually gives the all-clear signal before the train departs.\n\n==== {{anchor|Types of passenger trains}}Train types ====\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2018}}<!--most of the table is not cited-->\n{{main|Train numbering in India| List of named passenger trains in India| Longest train services of Indian Railways | Longest non-stop run in Indian Railways | label 1 =  Train numbering | label 2 = Named passenger trains | label 3 = Longest train services  | label 4 = Longest non-stop run}}\n[[File:NewDeli Mumbai Rajdhani AC 2 tier new livery.jpg|thumb|alt=Red-and-silver passenger train|The [[Mumbai Rajdhani Express]]. The long-distance, high-speed [[Rajdhani Express]]es connect state capitals and large cities with [[New Delhi]].]]\n[[File:Garib Rath.JPG|thumb|alt=Green-and-yellow passenger train|[[Secunderabad]]-[[Yeswanthpur|Yeshwanthpur]] [[Garib Rath Express]], an economy air-conditioned train]]\n\nTrains are sorted into categories which dictate the number of stops on a route, their priority on the network, and their fare structure. Each express train is identified by a five-digit number. If the first digit in the train number is 1 or 2, they are long-distance express trains. If the first digit is 0, the train is a special train which will operate for a limited period of time with a different fare structure. A first digit of 5 denotes a passenger train.\n\nThe second digit indicates the zone operating the train. However, for high-speed trains, the second digit is either 0 or 2 (the first remains 1 or 2).<ref name=irfcanumber/> The third digit denotes the division within the zone which is responsible for maintenance and cleanliness, and the last two digits are the train's serial number.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\">{{cite web | title = The system of train numbers |work=IRFCA.org\n | url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-number.html | accessdate = 3 June 2007 |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> The train numbering system was changed from four digits from December 2010,<ref name=\"fiveDigitNumer\">{{cite web |title        = New Train Number Enquiry\n |work         = Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Inquiry |url          = http://www.indianrail.gov.in/inet_trnno_enq.html\n |accessdate   = 5 February 2011 |publisher    = Centre For Railway Information Systems |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101124132548/http://indianrail.gov.in/inet_trnno_enq.html |archive-date = 24 November 2010\n |url-status     = live |df           = dmy-all}}</ref> to accommodate the increasing number of trains.\n\nTrains traveling in opposite directions along the same route are usually labelled with consecutive numbers.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\" /> However, there is considerable variation in train numbers; some zones, such as [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]], have a less-systematic method of numbering trains.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\" />\n\nTrains are classified by average speed.<ref name=\"irfcarailops\">{{cite web | title = railway operations&nbsp;\u2014 I | url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-ops.html | accessdate =11 June 2007 |work=IRFCA.org |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> A faster train has fewer stops (halts) than a slower one, and is usually used for long-distance travel. Most express trains have special names to identify them easily. The names of the trains usually denote the regions they connect, the routes they traverse, or a famous person or tourist spot connected with the train.<ref name=\"irfcaname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-name.html|title=Train names|work=IRFCA.org|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|accessdate=3 June 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"namehindu\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blonnet.com/life/2005/06/24/stories/2005062400010100.htm|title=What's in a Train Name?|last=Sekhsaria|first=Pankaj|date=24 June 2005|accessdate=4 June 2007|publisher=The Hindu Business Line|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608015032/http://www.blonnet.com/life/2005/06/24/stories/2005062400010100.htm|archivedate=8 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable toccolours\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n! '''Train types'''\n! '''Description'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Vande Bharat Express]]'''\n|A semi-high-speed, air-conditioned day time journey train with facilities such as [[Wi-Fi]], snack tables, CCTV cameras, hydraulic-pressure doors, and a fire and smoke detection and extinguishing system. It can run at a speed of 200&nbsp;km/h. It is the first hi-tech locomotive-less (EMU) train set made in India. It was flagged off on 15 February 2019 by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]. The model number for this particular train set is [[Train 18]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Tejas Express]]\n|A semi-high-speed, air-conditioned train which had its [[Mumbai CST - Karmali Tejas Express|inaugural run]] on 24 May 2017, covering {{convert|551.7|km|0|abbr=on}} in 8 hours 30 minutes. Coaches have bio-vacuum toilets, water-level indicators, tap sensors, hand dryers, integrated Braille displays, an LED TV for each passenger with a phone jack, local cuisine, [[Wi-Fi]], tea and [[coffee vending machine]]s, magazines, snack tables, CCTV cameras, and a fire and smoke detection and extinguishing system. It can run at a speed of 200&nbsp;km/h but it is restricted to 130&nbsp;km/h due to some technical reasons.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Gatimaan Express]]'''\n|The first [[Higher-speed rail|semi-high-speed]], air-conditioned train running between [[Delhi]] and [[Jhansi]] with a top speed of {{convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Shatabdi Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, intercity trains for daytime travel. Unlike the Rajdhani or Duronto Expresses, the Shatabdi expresses make a round trip on the same day. The Bhopal Shatabdi Express (train number 12001/12002) is India's second-fastest train between New Delhi and Agra, with an average speed of {{convert|90|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and a top speed of {{convert|150|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. The limited-stop trains have Wi-Fi.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rajdhani Express]]'''\n|Limited-stop, air-conditioned trains linking state capitals to the national capital, New Delhi, with a top speed of {{convert|130|-|140|km/h|abbr=on|mph}}. The 2014 railway budget proposed increasing the numbers of Rajdhani and Shatabdi Expresses to {{convert|180|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Duronto Express]]'''\n|Non-stop (except for technical halts) service introduced in 2009. In January 2016, it became possible to book tickets from those technical stops. They connect India's metros and major state capitals, and were introduced to equal (or exceed) the speed of the Rajdhani Express. With air-conditioned one-, two-, or three-tier seating, some have non-air-conditioned sleeper-class accommodations.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Humsafar Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, three-tier coach trains with [[LED screen]]s displaying information about stations and train speed, a PA system, [[vending machines]] for tea and coffee, charging ports for electronic devices, bio-toilets, smoke alarms, CCTV cameras, curtains, and heating and refrigeration facilities for food. Its inaugural run was between [[Gorakhpur Junction railway station|Gorakhpur]] to [[Anand Vihar Terminal railway station|Anand Vihar Terminal]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[AC Express (Indian Railways)|AC Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, limited-stop trains linking major cities, with a speed of about {{convert|130|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Double Decker Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, limited-stop, two-tier express trains for daytime travel\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Uday Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned double decker train for overnight travel.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Garib Rath Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, economy, three-tier trains with a top speed of {{convert|130|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Yuva Express]]'''\n|Introduced with the Duronto Express to provide air-conditioned travel to young Indians, 60 percent of its seats were reserved for passengers between 18 and 45 years of age. The trains were unsuccessful, and operate only on the Delhi-Howrah and Delhi-Mumbai routes.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Jan Shatabdi Express]]'''\n|A more-economical version of the Shatabdi Express, with air-conditioned and non-air-conditioned classes and a top speed of {{convert|110|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Sampark Kranti Express]]'''\n|Express service to New Delhi.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Kavi Guru Express]]'''\n|Introduced in honor of [[Rabindranath Tagore]], four pairs of the trains operate on the network.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Vivek Express]]'''\n|Introduced to commemorate the 150th birth Anniversary of [[Swami Vivekananda]] in 2013, four pairs of Vivek Expresses run in the country.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rajya Rani Express]]'''\n|Introduced to connect state capitals to major cities in that state.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mahamana Express]]'''\n| Superfast train with Indian Railways' model rake coaches.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Intercity Express (Indian Railways)|Intercity Express]]'''\n|Introduced to connect major cities on short routes with high and semi-high speeds. Trains include the [[Deccan Queen]], [[Flying Ranee]] and [[Bilaspur \u2013 Nagpur Intercity Express|Bilaspur Nagpur Intercity Express]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Antyodaya Express]]'''\n|Non-reserved, high-speed [[LHB coaches]] on peak routes to ease congestion.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Jan Sadharan Express]]'''\n|Non-reserved express trains on peak routes to ease congestion.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Suvidha Express]]'''\n|High priority trains with dynamic pricing on high demand routes.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Express trains in India#Superfast Express|Superfast Express]]'''\n|Trains with a max speed greater than {{convert|100|-|110|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and an average speed greater than {{convert|55|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. With stops at very few stations, the tickets for these trains have a superfast surcharge.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Express trains in India|Express]]'''\n|Trains with a max speed greater than {{convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and an average speed greater than {{convert|36|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, with stops at few stations.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mail trains in India|Mail]]'''\n|These trains earlier had separate [[mail]] coaches. Nowadays, mail is carried in the [[Baggage car|luggage coach]] like all other trains.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Slow and fast passenger trains in India|Passenger]]''' \n|Slow, economical trains which stop at every (or almost every) station on a route. With generally-unreserved seating, these trains travel at about {{convert|40|-|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Suburban rail in India|Suburban]]'''\n|These trains operate in [[Mumbai]], [[Delhi]], [[Kolkata]], [[Chennai]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Vadodara]], [[Surat]], [[Bengaluru]], [[Pune]] and between [[Kanpur]] and [[Lucknow]], usually stop at every station, and have unreserved seating.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rapid transit in India|Metro]]'''\n|Designed for urban transport, the first metro was the [[Kolkata Metro]] in 1984.<ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/indias-first-underwater-metro-nears-completion-after-costs-double/articleshow/73686059.cms</ref> 13 metro systems currently exist, in a total of 21 cities. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways]]'''\n|Three of the lines were declared a [[World Heritage Site]] as \"[[Mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways of India]]\" by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web |title        = Toy Trains of India |url          = http://www.triptoindia.com/toy-trains-of-india-royal-train-tours-of-india-calling-tours-trip-to-india.html |accessdate   = 12 May 2007 |work         = Our Trips&nbsp;\u2013 Royal Train Tours |publisher    = India Calling Tours (P) Limited\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070808012804/http://www.triptoindia.com/toy-trains-of-india-royal-train-tours-of-india-calling-tours-trip-to-india.html |archive-date = 8 August 2007 |url-status     = live |df           = dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==== {{anchor|Luxury trains}}Tourism ====\n\nIndian Railway operates tourist train or coach services on popular tourist circuits in different regions of the country. The service offers tour packages inclusive of rail travel, local transportation, accommodation, food and guided tours. IR offers various tourist services in this segment including Luxury tourist trains, Semi luxury trains, Buddhist special trains, Bharat Darshan trains, Aastha Circuit trains, and Steam trains.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe ''[[Palace on Wheels]]'' is a luxury-train service, frequently hauled by a steam locomotive, to promote tourism in [[Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/travel/Palace+wheels/7386580/story.html|title=NPalace on wheels \u2013 Exclusive Indian train was originally used by royalty|publisher=Times of India|date=13 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017234123/http://www.vancouversun.com/travel/Palace+wheels/7386580/story.html|archivedate=17 October 2012}}</ref> The train has a seven-night, eight-day itinerary on a round trip from [[New Delhi]] via [[Jaipur]], [[Sawai Madhopur]] and [[Chittaurgarh]], [[Udaipur]], [[Jaisalmer]], [[Jodhpur]], [[Bharatpur, India|Bharatpur]] and [[Agra]].\n\n''[[Royal Rajasthan on Wheels]]'' covers a number of tourist destinations in Rajasthan. The seven-day, eight-night tour is a round trip from New [[Delhi]]'s [[Safdarjung railway station|Safdarjung station]] via [[Jodhpur]], [[Udaipur]] and [[Chittaurgarh]], [[Ranthambore National Park]] and [[Jaipur]], [[Khajuraho]], [[Varanasi]] and [[Sarnath]], and Agra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalsrajasthanonwheels.com/itinerary.html |title=Royal Rajasthan on Wheels Itinerary &#124; Tour Program for 2014\u201315 |publisher=Royalsrajasthanonwheels.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331033949/http://www.royalsrajasthanonwheels.com/itinerary.html |archive-date=31 March 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n''[[Maharajas' Express]]'', a luxury train operated by the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation]] (IRCTC), runs on five routes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themaharajasexpressindia.com/booking.php |title=The Maharajas' Express Train Journeys Season 2014\u20132015 |publisher=The-maharajas.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228004518/http://www.themaharajasexpressindia.com/booking.php |archive-date=28 February 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> to about 12 destinations across northwest and central India (centered around Rajasthan) from October to April.\n\nThe ''[[Deccan Odyssey]]'' covers tourist destinations in [[Maharashtra]] and [[Goa]]. Its seven-night, eight-day tour begins in [[Mumbai]] and stops at [[Jaigad Fort]], [[Ganapatipule]] and [[Ratnagiri]], [[Sindhudurg]], [[Tarkarli]] and [[Sawantwadi]], Goa, [[Kolhapur]] and [[Pune]] (Day 5), [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] and [[Ellora Caves]], and [[Ajanta Caves]] and [[Nashik]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1063 |title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board) |access-date=26 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105054339/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1063 |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Golden Chariot]]'' is a luxury train service running on two tours: Pride of the South<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/tour-itinerary.html |title=Tour Itinerary \u2013 Tour Itinerary of Golden Chariot Train, Itinerary of Golden Chariot Train |publisher=Goldenchariottrain.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414112147/http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/tour-itinerary.html |archive-date=14 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and Splendor of the South.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/southern-splendour-tour-itinerary.html |title=Southern Splendour Tour \u2013 South India Tour and South India Tour Package |publisher=Goldenchariottrain.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414125105/http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/southern-splendour-tour-itinerary.html |archive-date=14 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Mahaparinirvan Express]]'', an air-conditioned service also known as the Buddhist Circuit Train, is run by the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]] for [[Buddhist]] pilgrims. Its seven-night, eight-day tour begins in New Delhi and visits [[Bodh Gaya]], [[Rajgir]] and [[Nalanda]], [[Varanasi]] and [[Sarnath]], [[Kushinagar]] and [[Lumbini]], [[Sravasti]], and the [[Taj Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1066 |title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board) |publisher=Indianrailways.gov.in |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410173012/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1066 |archive-date=10 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Fairy Queen (locomotive)|Fairy Queen]]'', a tourist attraction also known as the world's oldest operating steam engine, hauls a luxury train from Delhi to [[Alwar]].\n\n==== Ticketing ====\n{{see also| Tatkal scheme}}\n[[File:Railway ticket from Bangalore City junction to Pune junction.jpg|right|thumb|An Indian Railway ticket from [[Bangalore]] to [[Pune]] on Lokmanya Tilak Terminus - Coimbatore Express]]\nUntil the late 1980s, Indian Railways ticket reservations were made manually. In late 1987, IR began using a computerized ticketing system. The system went online in 1995 to provide current information on status and availability. The ticketing network at stations is computerized with the exception of remote areas. As of March 2017, close to 6000 stations are networked with reserved or unreserved ticketing systems across India.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/6.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications \u2013 Passenger Business|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302173243/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/6.pdf|archive-date=2 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  IR now provides multiple channels for passengers to book tickets between any two train stations in the country.\n\nReserved tickets may be booked up to 120 days in advance on the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation]] website, smartphone apps, [[SMS]], rail reservation counters at train stations, or through private ticket booking counters. A [[Tatkal scheme|Tatkal train ticket]] can be booked by passengers who want to travel at short notice with a reserved seat or berth, but such tickets are sold at higher fares than regular advance reservation tickets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/tatkal-ticket-booking-charges-timings-cancellation-and-more/articleshow/63095041.cms|title=Tatkal Ticket Booking: Charges, timings, cancellation and more \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612105406/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/tatkal-ticket-booking-charges-timings-cancellation-and-more/articleshow/63095041.cms|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConfirmed reservation tickets will show the passenger and fare details along with berth or seat number(s) allocated to them on the ticket. If the reservation is not available on a particular train, the ticket has a wait-list number. A person with a wait-listed ticket must wait for enough cancellations to obtain a confirmed ticket. If their ticket is not confirmed on the day of departure, they cannot board the train. [[Reservation against Cancellation|Reservation against cancellation tickets]], between the waiting and confirmed lists, allow a ticket holder to board the train and obtain a seat chosen by a ticket collector after the collector has found a vacant seat.<ref name=\"reserve rules\" /><ref name=\"irfcatravel\" />\n\nUnreserved tickets for short distance or unplanned travels may be purchased at stations at any time before departure. Holders of such tickets may only board the general compartments. Suburban networks issue unreserved tickets valid for a limited time or season passes with unlimited travel between two stops for a period of time. Commuters can purchase tickets and season passes at stations or through [[UTS Mobile Ticketing|UTS]] mobile apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in/RDS/login?1|title=UTS Mobile Ticketing|website=www.utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in|access-date=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108163922/http://utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in/RDS/login?1|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA valid proof for the purchase of ticket along with photo identification is required to board the train.\n\nIndia has some of the lowest train fares in the world, and passenger traffic is subsidised by higher-class fares.<ref name=\"Joshi\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r31MYIrISFMC&pg=PA184&dq=indian+rail|title=India's Economic Reforms, 1991\u20132001|last=Joshi|first=V|author2=I. M. D. Little|date=17 October 1996|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-829078-0|location=USA|page=184|chapter=Industrial Policy and Factor Markets|accessdate=25 June 2007}}</ref> Discounted tickets are available for [[senior citizen]]s (over age 60), the differently-abled, students, athletes, and those taking competitive examinations. One compartment of the lowest class of accommodation is earmarked for women on every passenger train. Some berths or seats are also reserved for women or senior citizens.<ref name=\"reserverules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/resrules.html |title=Reservation Rules |accessdate=25 June 2007 |publisher=Indian Railways |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624105628/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/resrules.html |archivedate=24 June 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Freight services}}Freight services ===\n{{See also|Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|label 1=Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India}}\nIn the freight segment, IR ferries various commodities and fuels in industrial, consumer, and agricultural segments across the length and breadth of India. IR has historically subsidised the passenger segment with income from the freight business. As a result, freight services are unable to compete with other modes of transport on both cost and speed of delivery, leading to continuous erosion of market share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/2.pdf|title=Indian Railways White Paper 2016|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032211/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/2.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> To counter this downward trend, IR has started new initiatives in freight segments including upgrading of existing goods sheds, attracting private capital to build multi-commodity multi-modal logistics terminals, changing container sizes, operating time-tabled freight trains, and tweaking with the freight pricing/product mix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/Railways%20Presentation.pdf|title=INDIAN RAILWAYS 2017\u20132019 VISION & PLANS|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118230400/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/Railways%20Presentation.pdf|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, end-to-end integrated transport solutions such as [[Konkan Railway Corporation#RORO|roll-on, roll-off]] (RORO) service, a [[Rolling highway|road-rail system]] pioneered by [[Konkan Railway Corporation]] in 1999 to carry trucks on [[flatbed truck|flatbed]] trailers,<ref name=\"pibroro\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page1.asp?relid=949|work=Press release, Press Information Bureau, dated 2004-20-05|title=Road-Rail Synergy System|accessdate=22 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605172834/http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page1.asp?relid=949|archive-date=5 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> is now being extended to other routes across India.\n\nPerhaps the game changer for IR in the freight segment are the new [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|dedicated freight corridors]] that are expected to be completed by 2020. When fully implemented, the new corridors, spanning around 3300&nbsp;km, could support hauling of trains up to 1.5&nbsp;km in length with 32.5 ton axle-load at speeds of {{convert|100|km/h|}}. Also, they will free-up capacity on dense passenger routes and will allow IR to run more trains at higher speeds. Additional corridors are being planned to augment the freight infrastructure in the country.\n\n=== {{anchor|UNESCO world heritage sites}}UNESCO World Heritage Sites ===\nIR has two UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]]s: the [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus]], Mumbai,<ref>{{cite web | title=Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus (formerly Victoria Terminus) | work=World Heritage List | publisher=[[World Heritage Committee]] | year=2004 | url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/945 | accessdate=5 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219072551/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/945 | archive-date=19 December 2008 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the \"[[mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways of India]]\".<ref name=\"Mountain Railways of India\">{{cite web | title=Mountain Railways of India | work=World Heritage List | publisher=[[World Heritage Committee]] | year=1999 | url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944/ | accessdate=5 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219024051/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944/ | archive-date=19 December 2008 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The latter are three rail lines in different parts of India: the [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]], a {{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}} [[narrow-gauge railway]] in the [[Lesser Himalayas]] of [[West Bengal]]; the [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]], a {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}} [[rack railway]] in the [[Nilgiri Hills]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], and the [[Kalka-Shimla Railway]], a {{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}} narrow-gauge railway in the [[Siwalik Hills]] of [[Himachal Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Mountain Railways of India\"/>\n\n== Issues ==\nIR carries an annual debt of over {{INRConvert|200|b}}. The passenger division lost {{INRConvert|300|b}} in FY 2013\u20132014, leading to a {{INRConvert|0.23}} loss per passenger-km and a cash surplus of {{INRConvert|6.9|b}}.<ref name=\"budget2014-15\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/2014-15_Final/Budget%20Speech%202014-15%20Highlights%20_English_PDF.pdf|title=Railway Budget 2014\u201315|access-date=20 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710222712/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/2014-15_Final/Budget%20Speech%202014-15%20Highlights%20_English_PDF.pdf|archive-date=10 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Its [[operating ratio]] was 109 percent from April to December 2016.<ref name=loss1>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/pP70AXtpAMAHqsoxyFaFtL/Railways-operating-ratio-touches-a-record-109-in-AprilDec.html|title=Railways' operating ratio touches a record 109% in April\u2013December|last=Sood|first=Jyotika|date=16 February 2017|newspaper=Livemint|access-date=19 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218181348/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/pP70AXtpAMAHqsoxyFaFtL/Railways-operating-ratio-touches-a-record-109-in-AprilDec.html|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It's accounting systems are allegedly outdated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/jvDzOl95sfbjnt43QU6xnI/Railways-moves-towards-accounting-reforms.html|title=Railways moves towards accounting reforms|last=Lohumi|first=Manasi|date=20 December 2016|work=livemint.com|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032337/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/jvDzOl95sfbjnt43QU6xnI/Railways-moves-towards-accounting-reforms.html|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2014, 99 new rail projects were announced in the annual [[Rail Budget]]s without additional funding. One project has been completed; the remaining 98 will require {{INRConvert|5|t}}, including four projects which were 30 years old in 2014.<ref name=\"budget2014-15\"/> IR is losing passenger and freight market share to other modes of transport.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2014/07/08/Photos/w_Rail_Budget_Precursor_grfx.jpg |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708110953/http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2014/07/08/Photos/w_Rail_Budget_Precursor_grfx.jpg |archive-date=8 July 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Report of High Level Safety Review Committee'' of 2012, from 2007\u201308 to October 2011, casualties in train accidents accounted for 1,019 deaths and 2,118 injuries. In the same period, 1,600 railway staff were killed and 8,700 were injured. The committee estimated that almost 15,000 people are killed each year by what is called unlawful trespassing.<ref>[http://irsme.nic.in/files/FINAL-BOOK-HLSRC_latest-17-02-2012.pdf ''Report of High Level Safety Review Committee''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213810/http://irsme.nic.in/files/FINAL-BOOK-HLSRC_latest-17-02-2012.pdf |date=14 July 2014 }}, Railway Ministry, February 2012</ref> A ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' article<ref>''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', Wednesday 18 April 2012 issue, page 14, rightmost column)</ref> stated that IR officials believe that a large proportion of bodies found dead on railways died elsewhere and were put on the railway in dishonest attempts to get compensation from the railway authorities and companies.\n\nIR carries out various activities that are essentially uneconomic in nature, where it is either not able to recover the costs (capital investments/operating costs) it incurs to deliver such services, or ends up foregoing revenues. Such activities, termed by IR as Social Service Obligations, include concessional tariffs for a few passenger segments or essential commodities and services in uneconomical train routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://niti.gov.in/writereaddata/files/document_publication/Social-Costs.pdf|title=Reviewing the Impact of Social Service Obligations by Indian Railways|last=Bibek Debroy and Kishore Desai|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215030114/http://niti.gov.in/writereaddata/files/document_publication/Social-Costs.pdf|archive-date=15 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> While the assessment of actual losses to meet social service obligations requires a scientific study, the estimation of such losses from IR for the fiscal year 2016\u201317 is {{INRConvert|296.3|b|lk=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/18.pdf|title=Indian Railways Year Book 2016\u201317, Social Service Obligations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225210117/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/18.pdf|archive-date=25 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\n{{Main|Future of rail transport in India}}\n\nIR's [[Research Design and Standards Organisation]] (RDSO) undertakes research, design and standardisation. The railway has undertaken several initiatives to upgrade its ageing infrastructure and improve its quality of service. The Indian government plans to invest {{INRConvert|9.05|t}} to upgrade IR by 2020.<ref name=\"Economic Times\">{{cite web|title=GE, Alstom land $5.6-billion deals to supply locomotives for railways|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ge-alstom-land-5-6-billion-deals-to-supply-locomotives-for-railways/articleshow/49733686.cms|work=Economic Times|date=10 November 2015|accessdate=13 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112021946/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ge-alstom-land-5-6-billion-deals-to-supply-locomotives-for-railways/articleshow/49733686.cms|archive-date=12 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nInfrastructure modernisation projects include [[High-speed rail in India|high-speed rail]], with the first Ahmedabad-Mumbai train in operation in 2022;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/diamond-quadrilateral-of-high-speed-trains/ |title=Diamond quadrilateral of high-speed trains \u2013 A Dastidar, Indian Express, 10 June 2014 |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813222712/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/diamond-quadrilateral-of-high-speed-trains/ |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-sign-deal-with-japan-to-get-first-bullet-train/article7961724.ece |title=India to sign deal with Japan to get first bullet train \u2013 The Hindu<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802071232/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-sign-deal-with-japan-to-get-first-bullet-train/article7961724.ece |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/indian-cabinet-agrees-to-pick-japan-for-high-speed-rail-project-1449744059 |title=India Said to Pick Japan for High-Speed Rail Project \u2013 WSJ<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518014556/https://www.wsj.com/articles/indian-cabinet-agrees-to-pick-japan-for-high-speed-rail-project-1449744059 |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> redevelopment of 400 stations by monetizing {{convert|2700|acre|km2}} of spare railway land under a {{INRConvert|1070000|c|0}} plan;<ref name=sta1>[http://www.livemint.com/Companies/NV9ujsKfuh92SnrxtiC86H/Railways-appoints-IRSDC-as-nodal-agency-for-station-redevelo.html Railways appoints IRSDC as nodal agency for station redevelopment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102226/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/NV9ujsKfuh92SnrxtiC86H/Railways-appoints-IRSDC-as-nodal-agency-for-station-redevelo.html |date=23 December 2017 }}, Livemint, 5 December 2017.</ref> [[Double-track railway|doubling tracks]] to reduce congestion and delays while improving safety (15,000&nbsp;km of double track existed in 2016, and funding for 12,500&nbsp;km more was approved that year);<ref name=bg1/> the refurbishing of 12- to 15-year-old coaches at the Carriage Rehabilitation Workshop in Bhopal to enhance passenger amenities and fire safety;<ref>{{cite news|title=Indian Railways gets first model rake of luxury 'Make in India' coaches|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/infrastructure/indian-railways-gets-first-model-rake-of-luxury-make-in-india-coaches/led-reading-lights/slideshow/50527595.cms|accessdate=13 January 2016|agency=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.|work=The Economic Times|date=11 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215143/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/infrastructure/indian-railways-gets-first-model-rake-of-luxury-make-in-india-coaches/led-reading-lights/slideshow/50527595.cms|archive-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Indian Railways unveils 'Make in India' train coaches with new look|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/business-gallery/192582/indian-railways-unveils-make-in-india-train-coaches-with-new-look-check-irctc-co-in/2/|accessdate=13 January 2016|agency=The Indian Express Group|work=The Financial Express|date=13 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115052117/http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/business-gallery/192582/indian-railways-unveils-make-in-india-train-coaches-with-new-look-check-irctc-co-in/2/|archive-date=15 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS)-enabled tracking of trains to improve safety and service;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/business/report-just-like-your-cabs-you-can-soon-track-trains-in-real-time-via-gps-2563623|title=Just like your cabs, you can soon track trains in real time via GPS {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=30 November 2017|work=DNA India|access-date=30 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202071947/http://www.dnaindia.com/business/report-just-like-your-cabs-you-can-soon-track-trains-in-real-time-via-gps-2563623|archive-date=2 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Digital India]]-driven {{INRConvert|3500000|m|currency_formatting=c|to=USD|year=2017}} digitalisation of the railway to improve efficiency and reduce cost;<ref name=bg1/> [[Rainwater harvesting#India|rainwater harvesting]], with 1885 systems installed by December 2016;<ref name=rain1>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=155020 Rain Water Harvesting System In Indian Railway] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102329/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=155020 |date=23 December 2017 }}, 7 December 2016.</ref> and [[reforestation]] of railway land and along the tracks.<ref name=forest1>[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2016/07/india-plants-50-million-trees-uttar-pradesh-reforestation/ India Plants 50 Million Trees in One Day, Smashing World Record] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102536/https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2016/07/india-plants-50-million-trees-uttar-pradesh-reforestation/ |date=23 December 2017 }}, [[National Geographic]], July 2016.</ref>\n\n=== Electrification and power ===\nAll routes will be [[Central Organisation for Railway Electrification|electrified]] to save on imported-fuel costs. 57.91 percent of the network was electrified as of November 2019, with full electrification planned by March 2021.<ref name=bg1>[http://railengdigest.com/project-news/asia/indian-railways-converts-broad-gauge/ Indian Railways orders conversion to Broad Gauge] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102927/http://railengdigest.com/project-news/asia/indian-railways-converts-broad-gauge/ |date=23 December 2017 }}, Rail Digest, 12 April 2017.</ref> [[Off-the-grid]] solar-powered trains are planned with the installation of one gigawatt of [[Solar power|solar]] and 130 megawatts of [[wind power]] between 2017 and 2022; India introduced the world's first solar-powered train and 50 coaches with rooftop solar farms in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/indias-first-solar-powered-demu-train-launched/article19281625.ece|title=India\u2019s first solar-powered DEMU train launched|work=The Hindu|access-date=23 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/indias-first-solar-powered-demu-train-launched/article19281625.ece|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130808115946/http://www.eco-business.com/news/railways-iit-madras-tie-power-ac-coaches-solar-energy/ Railways, IIT-Madras tie up to power AC coaches with solar energy]. ''The Times of India'' (5 August 2013). Retrieved on 17 August 2013.</ref><ref name=solar1>[https://www.curbed.com/2017/7/19/15995536/solar-power-train-india-railways India\u2019s new solar-powered train is the first in the world] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102640/https://www.curbed.com/2017/7/19/15995536/solar-power-train-india-railways |date=23 December 2017 }}, June 2017</ref> Initial assessments of this experiment has been positive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309625965_Rail_coaches_with_rooftop_solar_photovoltaic_systems_A_feasibility_study |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309625965_Rail_coaches_with_rooftop_solar_photovoltaic_systems_A_feasibility_study |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>[[Rooftop photovoltaic power station|Rooftop solar electricity]] is planned at stations to reduce long-term fuel costs and protect the environment,<ref>{{cite news|title=NORTHERN RAILWAYS TO INSTALL 5 MW ROOFTOP SOLAR IN FOUR OF ITS STATIONS|url=http://mercomcapital.com/northern-railways-to-install-5-mw-rooftop-solar-in-four-of-its-stations#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf|access-date=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303201130/http://mercomcapital.com/northern-railways-to-install-5-mw-rooftop-solar-in-four-of-its-stations#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf|archive-date=3 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Sustainable lighting|sustainable]] [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] lighting at all stations is planned by March 2018 to cut electricity costs.<ref name=led1>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/all-railway-stations-to-be-100-pc-led-lit-by-april-2018-rlys/articleshow/62138170.cms Indian Railways plans to make all stations 100% LED lit by 31 March 2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518114500/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/all-railway-stations-to-be-100-pc-led-lit-by-april-2018-rlys/articleshow/62138170.cms |date=18 May 2018 }}, [[Times of India]], 19 December 2017.</ref> Locomotive factories have been modernised, including two new factories in Bihar: an [[electric locomotive]] factory in [[Madhepura]] and a diesel locomotive factory in [[Marhaura]], and 2,285 bio-toilets were introduced from April to July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locomotive Factories in Bihar: In cold storage for years, two Railway projects to start soon|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/locomotive-factories-in-bihar-in-cold-storage-for-years-two-railway-projects-to-start-soon/|work=Indian Express|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031004858/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/locomotive-factories-in-bihar-in-cold-storage-for-years-two-railway-projects-to-start-soon/|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=GE Gets $2.6 Billion Indian Railways Contract|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ge-to-help-modernize-indias-rail-system-1447080903|work=Wall Street Journal|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109183451/http://www.wsj.com/articles/ge-to-help-modernize-indias-rail-system-1447080903|archive-date=9 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rail ministry awards Rs 14,656-cr Marhowra locomotive project to GE|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/rail-ministry-awards-rs-14-656-cr-marhowra-locomotive-project-to-ge-115110900795_1.html|work=Business Standard|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112014526/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/rail-ministry-awards-rs-14-656-cr-marhowra-locomotive-project-to-ge-115110900795_1.html|archive-date=12 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A {{INRConvert|200|b}} partnership with [[Alstom]] to supply 800 electric locomotives from 2018 to 2028 was announced.<ref name=\"Economic Times\"/>\n\n=== Safety ===\nSafety projects include the elimination of an average of 1,217 unguarded [[level crossing]]s per year by building an average of 1,066 overpasses and underpasses per year;<ref name=umc1>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=145324 Indian Railways commissions around 4800 kilometer of broad gauge track in last two financial years which is a record performance ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611154206/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=145324 |date=11 June 2016 }}, 12 May 2016.</ref><ref name=bg1/> the extension of an automated [[fire alarm system]], first introduced on Rajdhani Express trains in 2013, to all air-conditioned coaches;<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Railways develops Automatic Fire and Smoke Detection System|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-railways-develops-automatic-fire-and-smoke-detection-system/|accessdate=5 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908145221/http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-railways-develops-automatic-fire-and-smoke-detection-system/|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and 6,095 GPS-enabled [[Inertial navigation system|Fog Pilot Assistance System]] [[railway signalling]] devices (replacing the practice of placing firecrackers on tracks to alert train drivers) installed in 2017 in four zones: [[Northern Railway zone|Northern]], [[North Central Railway zone|North Central]], [[North Eastern Railway zone|North Eastern]] and [[North Western Railway zone|North Western]]; and replacing ICF coaches with LHB coaches.\n\n=== Effects of COVID-19===\nIn an unprecedented move, the railways had suspended the services of 13,523 trains for 21 days after the lockdown was announced by the PM on March 24.\n\nIts freight trains however continued to run during this period.<ref>https://www.livemint.com/news/india/railways-issues-restoration-plan-asks-to-prepare-for-resumption-of-services-11585981517025.html</ref> This was the first time in its 167 year history the lifeline of the nation was stopped.\n\n==Trivia==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n*[[Vivek Express]] has the longest route in India, which covers 4,286&nbsp;km in about 82 hours and 30 minutes. The train runs between Dibrugarh and Kanyakumari.\n*[[Howrah\u2013Amritsar Express]] 13049/50 has the record for maximum stops by an Express/Mail train in India. The train has 115 stops en route.\n*[[Vande Bharat Express]] is the fastest train by average speed in India and runs between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi Station]] and [[Varanasi Junction]]. Another train runs between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi Station]] and [[Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra railway station|Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra Station]]\n*[[Gorakhpur Junction railway station|Gorakhpur Junction]] in [[Gorakhpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] has the longest platform in the world measuring 1,366m.\n*[[Puratchi Thalaivar Dr. M.G. Ramachandran Central Railway Station]] in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]] is the longest station name in India and second-longest in the world followed by [[Bangalore City railway station|Krantivira Sangolli Rayanna Bengaluru Railway Station]] in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]], the third-longest station name in the world.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of railway stations in India]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{div col}}\n* Aguiar, Marian. ''Tracking Modernity: India's Railway and the Culture of Mobility''  (University of Minnesota Press; 2011) 226 pages; draws on literature, film, and other realms to explore the role of the railway in the Indian imagination. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0816665613/ excerpt and text search]\n* Bear, Linda. ''Lines of the Nation: Indian Railway Workers, Bureaucracy, and the Intimate Historical Self'' (2007)  [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0231140029/  excerpt and text search]\n* [https://thefactsone.com/interesting-facts-about-indian-railways/ Top 51 Interesting Facts about Indian railways]\n* Kerr, Ian J. ''Railways in Modern India'' (2001) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0195648285 excerpt and text search]\n* Kerr, Ian J. ''Engines of Change: The Railroads That Made India'' (2006)\n* Kumar, Sudhir, and Shagun Mehrotra. ''Bankruptcy to Billions: How the Indian Railways Transformed Itself'' (2009)\n* {{cite web|title=IRFCA : FAQ - Table of Contents|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/index.html|accessdate=19 June 2005}}\n* {{cite web|title=IRCTC|url=https://www.irctc.co.in|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=19 June 2005}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Indian Railways.ogg|2006-03-15}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130402130639/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/  Ministry of Indian Railways, Official website]\n\n<!--ATTENTION! PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY LINKS RELATED TO CHECKING PNR STATUS ETC, SUCH EDITS WILL BE REMOVED. READ THE EXTERNAL LINKS GUIDELINE-->\n\n{{Indian Railways}}\n{{Urban rail transit in India}}\n{{THBSOIR}}\n{{Asia in topic|Rail transport in}}\n{{Transport in India}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Railways}}\n[[Category:Indian Railways|*]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of India]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of India]]\n[[Category:1845 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1845]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the organisation|general information on railways in India|Rail transport in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox company|\n| logo = Indian railways.webp\n| logo_size = 125px\n| logo_alt = Red-and-white Indian Railways logo\n| logo_caption = \n| image = Indian Railways Headquarters.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = [[Rail Bhavan]], [[New Delhi]]\n| type = Government\n| industry = [[Rail transport]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|p=y|1845|5|08}}<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: IR History: Early Days \u2013 1|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=3 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307181407/http://irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|archive-date=7 March 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> <!-- Indian railways traces its history back to Madras Railway which was incorporated on 8 May 1845 by . See the ref, http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html. The first passenger line albeit was by GIPR in 1853. This article is about the company and not about rail transport. Hence the foundation year is 1845 and not 1853. -->\n| hq_location_city = [[New Delhi]]\n| hq_location_country = India\n| area_served = [[India]]\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list| [[Piyush Goyal]] ([[Minister of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]])| [[Suresh Angadi]] (Minister of State for Railways)| [[Vinod Kumar Yadav]] ([[Chairman]], [[Railway Board]])}}\n| services = [[Passenger railway]]s<br />[[Freight]] services<br />[[Parcel carrier]]<br />Catering and tourism services<br />[[Parking lot]] operations<br />Other related services\n| revenue = {{Increase}} {{INRConvert|1.97214|t}}<ref name=\"financial-summary\">{{cite web|url=http://indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/Budget_2019-20_Final/Statement%20of%20Railway%20Receipts%20and%20Expenditure_Regular%20Budget%202019-20.pdf|title=Indian Railways Budget Documents 2019\u201320|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue_year = 2018\u201319\n| profit = {{Increase}} {{INRConvert|60.14|b}}<ref name=\"financial-summary\" />\n| profit_year = 2018\u201319\n| owner = [[Government of India]] (100%)\n| num_employees = 1.30  million<ref name=\"stats-summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/Statistical_Summary.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Statistical summary \u2013 Indian Railways|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=22 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222170734/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/Statistical_Summary.pdf|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]\n| divisions = [[Zones and divisions of Indian Railways|18 zones]]\n| subsid = [[Centre for Railway Information Systems|CRIS]], [[Container Corporation of India|CONCOR]], [[RITES]], [[Ircon International|IRCON]], [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]], [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|DFCCI]], [[RailTel Corporation of India|RailTel]], [[Mumbai Railway Vikas Corporation|MRVC]], \n[[Rail Vikas Nigam|RVNL]], [[High-speed rail in India|NHSRCL]], [[Indian Railway Finance Corporation|IRFC]]\n| module = \n| footnotes = \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.indianrail.gov.in/}}<br />{{URL|http://indianrailways.gov.in/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox rail\n|railroad_name     =\n|logo_filename     =\n|logo_size         =\n|system_map        = India railway schematic map.svg\n|map_caption       = Railway network map of India - schematic\n|map_size          =\n|marks             = IR\n|image             = \n|image_size        =\n|image_caption     = Railway network map of India - schematic\n|locale            = India\n|start_year        = {{Start date|1845|5|8|df=y}}<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\"/> <!-- Indian railways traces its history back to Madras Railway which was incorporated on 8 May 1845. See the ref, http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html. The first [[passenger]] line albeit was by GIPR in 1853. This article is about the company and not about rail transport. Hence the foundation year is 1845 and not 1853. -->\n|end_year          = present\n|predecessor_line  =\n|successor_line    =\n|gauge             = {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|1000mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}}<br />{{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}}\n|length            = {{convert|67368|km}} (route)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> <br />{{convert|93902|km}} (running track)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> <br /> {{convert|121407|km}} (total track)<ref name=\":4\"/>\n|electrification   = {{convert|37359|km}}(as of March 2020 approx.)<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Indian Railways plans to end the pain of waitlist tickets |url=https://zeenews.india.com/economy/indian-railways-plans-to-end-the-pain-of-waitlist-tickets-2230519.html |website=Zee News |accessdate=29 August 2019 |language=en |date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Indian Railways''' ('''IR''') is [[India]]'s national railway system operated by the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]. It is one of the public facilities given by the government and manages the [[List of countries by rail transport network size|fourth largest railway network in the world]] by size, with a route length of {{convert|67368|km||adj=on|abbr=}} as of March 2017. About 57.91% of the routes are electrified with [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25 kV 50 Hz AC]] electric traction while 33% of them are double or multi-tracked.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/10.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Statistics for Track and Bridges \u2013 Indian Railways|format=PDF|work=Ministry of Railway|accessdate=22 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222225514/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/10.pdf|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the fiscal year ending March 2018, IR carried 8.26&nbsp;billion passengers and transported 1.16&nbsp;billion tonnes of freight.<ref name=\"financial-summary\" /> In the fiscal year 2017\u201318, IR is projected to have revenue of {{INRConvert|1.874|t|lk=}}, consisting of {{INRConvert|1.175|t|lk=}} in freight revenue and {{INRConvert|501.25|b|lk=}} in passenger revenue, with an [[operating ratio]] of 96.0 percent.<ref name=\"financial-summary\" />\n\n[https://thefactsone.com/interesting-facts-about-indian-railways/ Indian Railway] (IR) runs more than 20,000 passenger trains daily, on both [[Rail transport in India|long-distance]] and [[Suburban rail in India|suburban routes]], from 7,349 stations across India.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> The trains have five-digit and four-digit numbering system. [[Express trains in India|Mail or Express trains]], the most common types, run at an average speed of {{convert|50.6|km/h|}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/5.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317: Passenger Business|work=Ministry of Railway|page=23|format=PDF|accessdate=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050611/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/5.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Most premium passenger trains like [[Rajdhani Express]] and [[Shatabdi Express]] run at a peak speed of {{convert|140-150|km/h|abbr=on|}} with [[Gatimaan Express|Gatiman Express]] between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] and [[Jhansi Junction railway station|Jhansi]] touching a peak speed of {{convert|160|km/h|abbr=on}}. Indian railways also runs indigenously built semi-high speed train called [[Vande Bharat Express|Vande Bharat]] (also known as [[Vande Bharat Express|Train-18]])\" between [[Delhi Junction railway station|Delhi]] and [[Varanasi Junction railway station|Varanasi]] or [[Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra railway station|Katra]] which clocks a maximum track speed of {{convert|180|km/h|abbr=on}}. In the freight segment, IR runs more than 9,200 trains daily. The average speed of freight trains is around {{convert|24|km/h||abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/2.pdf|title=extrastats-summary|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223174343/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/2.pdf|archive-date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Maximum speed of freight trains varies from {{convert|60 to 75|km/h|abbr=on}} depending on their axle load with \"container special\" trains running at a peak speed of {{convert|100|km/h|abbr=on}}.\n\nAs of March 2017, Indian Railways' [[rolling stock]] consisted of 277,987 [[Freight rail transport|freight wagons]], 70,937 [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger coaches]] and 11,452 [[locomotive]]s.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> IR owns [[locomotive]] and [[coach (rail)|coach-production]] facilities at several locations in India. Being the world's [[List of companies by employees|eighth-largest employer]], it had 1.30&nbsp;million employees as of March 2016.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" />\n\nThe government has committed to [[Central Organisation for Railway Electrification|electrify its entire rail network]] by 2023, and become a \"net-zero railway\" by 2030.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/thumbs-up-indian-railways-to-go-eco-friendly-by-becoming-worlds-1st-100-electrified-and-net-zero-railway/1737339/|title=Thumbs up! Indian Railways to go eco-friendly by becoming world\u2019s 1st 100% electrified and \u2018Net-Zero\u2019 railway|date=2019-10-16|website=TheFinancial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of rail transport in India}}\n\nThe first railway proposals for India were made in [[Madras]] in 1832.<ref name=\"irfca.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/docs/history/india-first-railways.html|title=[IRFCA] India's First Railways|website=www.irfca.org}}</ref> The country's first train, ''Red Hill Railway'' (built by [[Arthur Cotton]] to transport granite for road-building), ran from [[Red Hills, Chennai|Red Hills]] to the [[Chintadripet]] bridge in Madras in 1837.<ref name=\"irfca.org\"/> In 1845, the ''Godavari Dam Construction Railway'' was built by Cotton at [[Dowleswaram]] in [[Rajahmundry]], to supply stone for the construction of a dam over the [[Godavari River]]. In 1851, the ''Solani Aqueduct Railway'' was built by [[Proby Cautley]] in [[Roorkee]] to transport construction materials for an [[aqueduct (bridge)|aqueduct]] over the Solani River.<ref name=\"irfca.org\" />\n\nIndia's first passenger train, operated by the [[Great Indian Peninsula Railway]] and hauled by three steam locomotives (''Sahib'', ''Sindh'' and ''Sultan''), ran for {{convert|34|km}} with 400 people in 14 carriages on {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}} [[broad gauge]] track between [[Bori Bunder railway station|Bori Bunder]] ([[Mumbai]]) and [[Thane]] on 16 April 1853.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/164-years-ago-on-this-day-india-s-first-train-ran-from-mumbai-to-thane-275748.html|title=164 Years Ago On This Day, India's First Train Ran From Mumbai To Thane|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729114445/http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/164-years-ago-on-this-day-india-s-first-train-ran-from-mumbai-to-thane-275748.html|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Indias-1st-train-When-Sahib-Sindh-Sultan-blew-steam/articleshow/19717248.cms|title=India\u2019s 1st train: When Sahib, Sindh & Sultan blew steam \u2013 Times of India|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808221221/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Indias-1st-train-When-Sahib-Sindh-Sultan-blew-steam/articleshow/19717248.cms|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Thane viaducts, India's first [[railway bridge]]s, were built over the [[Thane creek]] when the Mumbai-Thane line was extended to [[Kalyan]] in May 1854.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/docs/history/railway-times.html|title=Extracts from the Railway Times|date=1854|publisher=Railway Times|access-date=1 Jan 2019}}</ref> Eastern India's first passenger train ran {{convert|24|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Howrah]], near [[Kolkata]], to [[Hugli-Chinsura|Hoogly]] on 15 August 1854.<ref name=\"IRFCA-history-page\"/> The first passenger train in [[South India]] ran {{convert|60|mi|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Royapuram]]- Veyasarapady ([[Madras]]) to Wallajah Road ([[Arcot]]) on 1 July 1856.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railnews.in/royapuram-railway-station-legacy-through-the-ages/|title=Legacy of First Railway Station of South India|website=RailNews Media India Ltd|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729092115/http://www.railnews.in/royapuram-railway-station-legacy-through-the-ages/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 1873, a [[Horsecar|horse-drawn]] {{convert|3.8|km||abbr=on}} [[tram]] opened in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] between [[Sealdah]] and Armenian Ghat Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturebowl.com/kolkatas-trams-a-ride-through-history/|title=Kolkata\u2019s trams \u2013 A ride through history|date=2 March 2016|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729094331/http://www.culturebowl.com/kolkatas-trams-a-ride-through-history/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 May 1874, a horse-drawn tramway began operation in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] between [[Colaba]] and [[Parel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dighist.fas.harvard.edu/courses/2015/HUM54/exhibits/show/mumbai_development/trams|title=The Evolution of Trams in Mumbai|website=The Urban Imagination \u2013 Faculty of Arts and Sciences|publisher=[[Harvard University]]|access-date=18 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011232644/http://dighist.fas.harvard.edu/courses/2015/HUM54/exhibits/show/mumbai_development/trams|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1897, lighting in passenger coaches was introduced by many railway companies. On 3 February 1925, the first electric passenger train in India ran between [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus railway station|Victoria Terminus]] and [[Kurla]].<ref name=\"core.indianrailways.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,530|title=Welcome to Official Website of CORE|website=www.core.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=26 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807073445/http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,530|archive-date=7 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe organization of Indian railways into regional zones began in 1951,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in/index.php/history-of-railways|title=History of Railways|website=www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721211938/http://www.kportal.indianrailways.gov.in/index.php/history-of-railways|archive-date=21 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> when the [[Southern Railway zone|Southern]] (14 April 1951), [[Central Railway zone|Central]] (5 November 1951), and [[Western Railway zone|Western]] (5 November 1951) zones were created.<ref name=\"indianrail.gov.in\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319003737/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |archive-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Fans and lights were mandated for all compartments in all passenger classes in 1951, and sleeping accommodations were introduced in coaches. In 1956, the first fully air-conditioned train was introduced between [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]] and Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/NAT-TOP-160-years-of-indian-railways-watch-how-ac-trains-were-kept-cool-4224130-PHO.html|title=160 years of Indian Railways: Here's how AC trains were kept cool|date=2 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Ten years later, the first containerized freight service began between Mumbai and [[Ahmedabad]].\n\nIn 1974, Indian Railways endured a [[1974 railway strike in India|20 day strike]], which damaged the nation's economy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/08/archives/strike-of-indian-rail-workers-begins-tension-high-with-food.html|title=Strike of Indian Rail Workers Begins|date=1974-05-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2019/jan/30/better-jail-than-rail-george-fernandes-slogan-that-led-to-asias-biggest-railway-strike-in-1974-1931637.html|title=Better jail than rail: George Fernandes' slogan that led to Asia's biggest railway strike in 1974|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, computerized ticketing and reservations were introduced in New Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://icisa.cag.gov.in/audit_report/2/15db5cf8539e7f66e05214564e6b5d01.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712231120/http://icisa.cag.gov.in/audit_report/2/15db5cf8539e7f66e05214564e6b5d01.pdf |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 1988, the first [[Shatabdi Express]] was introduced between New Delhi and Jhansi; it was later extended to [[Bhopal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-railways/trains/shatabdi-express.html|title=Shatabdi Express \u2013 Shatabdi Express Train, Shatabadi Express Timetable, Shatabadi Express Schedule Booking India|website=www.iloveindia.com|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715191922/http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-railways/trains/shatabdi-express.html|archive-date=15 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years later, the first self-printing ticket machine (SPTM) was introduced in New Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/happy-birthday-indian-railways-first-passenger-train-started-165-years-ago-unknown-facts-about-the-network/1134650/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528051814/https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/happy-birthday-indian-railways-first-passenger-train-started-165-years-ago-unknown-facts-about-the-network/1134650/ |archive-date=28 May 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 1993, air-conditioned three-tier coaches and a sleeper class (separate from second class) were introduced on IR. The CONCERT system of computerized reservations was deployed in New Delhi, Mumbai and [[Chennai Central railway station|Chennai]] in September 1996. In 1998, coupon validating machines (CVMs) were introduced at [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus|Mumbai Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus]]. The nationwide concierge system began operation on 18 April 1999. In February 2000, the Indian Railways website went online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/index_new.html|title=Indian Railway|website=www.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724071557/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/index_new.html|archive-date=24 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 August 2002, IR began online train reservations and ticketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irctc.co.in/eticketing/loginHome.jsf|title=IRCTC Next Generation eTicketing System|website=www.irctc.co.in|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724151246/https://www.irctc.co.in/eticketing/loginHome.jsf|archive-date=24 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Railway Budget was presented every year, a few days before the Union budget, till 2016. Modi government on 21 September 2016 approved [[Railway budget of India|merger of the Rail and General budgets]] from next year, ending a 92-year-old practice of a separate budget for the nation's largest transporter. Railways Minister Suresh Prabhu said that his merger proposal was in the long term interest of railways as well as the country's economy\n\nOn 31 March 2017, Indian Railways announced that the country's entire rail network would be electrified by 2022 or 2023, and become a net-zero railway by 2030.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/48-per-cent-rail-tracks-electrified-aim-to-double-it-in-5-years-govt-4594389/|title=48 per cent rail tracks electrified, aim to double it in 5 years: Govt|date=31 March 2017|access-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718224354/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/48-per-cent-rail-tracks-electrified-aim-to-double-it-in-5-years-govt-4594389/|archive-date=18 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Tanna Village and Smaller Viaduct (12671597053).jpg|alt=A stone bridge|The smaller railway viaduct near Thane in 1855\nFile:Tanna Railway Viaduct (9142699593).jpg|alt=Train on a stone bridge with girder|The longer railway viaduct near Thane in 1855\nFile:India railways1909a.jpg|alt=Railway map|Railway map of India in 1909\n</gallery>On 22 March 2020, Indian Railways announced a nationwide shutdown of passenger rail service to combat the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]. This became part of a [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] to slow the spread of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/03/23/coronavirus-indian-railways-cancels-passenger-train-services/|title=Indian Railways cancels passenger train services|website=Business Traveller|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The railway shutdown was initially scheduled to last from 23 to 31 March,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrosaga.com/indian-railways-suspends-all-passenger-trains-but-theres-some-good-news/|title=Indian Railways Suspends All Passenger Trains But There\u2019s Some Good News|last=HP|first=Akarsh|date=2020-03-22|website=MetroSaga|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> but the nationwide lockdown, as announced by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 24 March, was to last 21 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/coronavirus-puts-over-1-billion-people-in-india-on-21-day-lockdown-to-combat-spread.html|title=Coronavirus puts over 1 billion people in India on 21-day lockdown to combat spread|last=Miller|first=Adam Jeffery,Hannah|date=2020-03-26|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The national rail network is maintaining its freight operations during the lockdown, to transport essential goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/indian-railways-continuing-its-freight-operations-post-22-march-lockdown-11585314775866.html|title=How Indian Railways continuing its freight operations post lockdown|last=Nandi|first=Tamal|date=2020-03-27|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> On 29 March, Indian Railways announced that it would start service for special parcel trains to transport essential goods, in addition to regular freight service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-railways-resumes-parcel-trains-to-transport-essential-goods-11585504148683.html|title=Covid-19: Railways resumes parcel trains to transport essential goods|last=Nandi|first=Shreya|date=2020-03-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail operator has also announced plans to convert coaches into isolation wards for patients of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-indian-railways-converts-non-ac-train-coach-into-isolation-ward-on-trial-basis-8201221.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Indian Railways converts non-AC train coach into isolation ward on trial basis|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n=== {{anchor|Organisational structure}}Structure ===\n{{Main|Indian Railways organisational structure|Zones and divisions of Indian Railways}}\n\nIndian Railways is headed by a seven-member [[Railway Board]] whose chairman reports to the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]]. Railway Board also acts as the Ministry of Railways. The officers manning the office of Railway Board are mostly from organised Group A Railway Services and [[Railway Board Secretariat Service]]. IR is divided into 18 zones, headed by general managers who report to the Railway Board.<ref name=\"IRStruct\">{{cite web|title=Organization Structure|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Organisation_Structure_Eng_pdf.pdf|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=2 March 2017|format=PDF|date=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517005226/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Organisation_Structure_Eng_pdf.pdf|archive-date=17 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Railways Report|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=2 March 2017|format=PDF|date=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517103428/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2015-16/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|archive-date=17 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The zones are further subdivided into 68 operating [[Zones and divisions of Indian Railways|divisions]], headed by divisional railway managers (DRM).<ref>{{cite news | first = Vijay Pratap | last = Singh | title = SMS complaint system: A Northern Railway brainwave spreads | date = 27 February 2010 | url = http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sms-complaint-system-a-northern-railway-brainwave-spreads/585107/0 | work = [[Indian Express]] | accessdate = 19 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Stats_2012\">{{cite book| title = Indian Railways Facts and Figures (2011\u20132012)| url = http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,554,1275| publisher = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]], [[Government of India]]| year = 2012| page = personnel| accessdate = 21 July 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014175900/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,554,1275| archive-date = 14 October 2013| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Zones and their Divisions in Indian Railways |url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |publisher=Indian Railways |accessdate=26 August 2011 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319003737/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/ir_zones.pdf |archivedate=19 March 2015  }}</ref> The divisional officers of the engineering, mechanical, electrical, signal and telecommunication, stores, accounts, personnel, operating, commercial, security and safety branches report to their respective DRMs and are tasked with the operation and maintenance of assets. Station masters control individual stations and train movements through their stations' territory. In addition, there are a number of production units, training establishments, public sector enterprises and other offices working under the control of the Railway Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|title=stats-network|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619112957/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/9.pdf|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Subsidiaries and undertakings ===\nIR is a major shareholder in 16 [[State-owned enterprise|public sector undertakings (PSU)]] and other organizations that are related to rail transport in India. Notable among this list include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/25.pdf|title=Indian Railways Annual Publication 2016\u201317 \u2013 Undertakings|date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301171434/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/25.pdf|archive-date=1 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFinancing, construction and project implementation: [[Indian Railway Finance Corporation|IRFC]], [[RITES]], [[Ircon International|IRCON]], [[Mumbai Railway Vikas Corporation|MRVC]], [[Rail Vikas Nigam Limited|RVNL]]\n\nLand and station development: [[Rail Land Development Authority|RLDA]], [[Indian Railway Stations Development Corporation|IRSDC]]\n\nRail infrastructure: [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|DFCCIL]], PRCL<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pipavavrailway.com/ |title=PRCL |access-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024204707/http://www.pipavavrailway.com/ |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nPassenger and freight train operations: [[Konkan Railway Corporation|KRCL]], [[Container Corporation of India|CONCOR]]\n\nIT and communications: [[Centre for Railway Information Systems|CRIS]], [[RailTel Corporation of India|RCIL]]\n\nCatering and tourism: [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]]\n\n=== Human resources ===\n{{Main|Centralised Training Institutes of the Indian Railways}}\n\nStaff are classified into [[Gazetted Officer (India)|gazetted]] (Groups A and B) and non-gazetted (Groups C and D) employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,388|title=Railway Board Directorates|work=INDIAN RAILWAY ESTABLISHMENT CODE|publisher=Indian Railways|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530064841/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,388|archive-date=30 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Gazetted employees carry out executive / managerial / officer level tasks. As of March 2017, the number of personnel (Groups A & B) constitutes 1.2% of the total strength, while Group C & D account for 92.6%  and 6.2% respectively.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/16.pdf|title=stats-personnel|last=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 \u2013 Personnel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223051733/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/16.pdf|archive-date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere is no direct recruitment of Group B employees in Indian Railways and they are recruited by departmental promotional exams of Group C employees. Recruitment of Group A employees is carried out by the [[Union Public Service Commission]] Civil Service exam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irts.org.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,409|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802173355/http://www.irts.org.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,409|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 August 2012|title=Indian Railways level which constitutes the Governing Council of Association|publisher=irts.org.in}}</ref> Recruitment of Group C junior engineers and depot material superintendents is conducted by the Railway Recruitment Board. Group C employees are recruited by 21 Railway Recruitment Board or RRB, which are controlled by the [[Railway Recruitment Control Board]] (RRB).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rrcb.gov.in/rrbs.html|title=Indian Railways Establishment Manual|publisher=rrcb.gov.in|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525103317/http://rrcb.gov.in/RRBS.HTML|archive-date=25 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/education/rrb-ntpc-exam-2016-postponed-new-dates-to-release-soon/|title=RRB NTPC exam 2016|publisher=indianexpress.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720032851/http://indianexpress.com/article/education/rrb-ntpc-exam-2016-postponed-new-dates-to-release-soon/|archive-date=20 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Group D staffs are recruited by 16 Railway Recruitment Cells or RRCs.\n\nThe training of all groups is shared among seven centralized zonal training institutes and 295 training centers all over India.\n\nIR offers housing and runs its own hospitals, schools and sports facilities for the welfare of its staff.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Rolling stock ==\n\n=== Locomotives ===\n{{Main|Locomotives of India}}\n[[File:11308 WAP7 030418.jpg|alt=Light-coloured electric locomotive|thumb|Ajni Loco Shed [[WAP-7]]-class [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] [[Alternating current|AC]] electric locomotive]]\n[[File:WDM-3D class Locomotive of Indian Railway.jpg|thumb|alt=Blue diesel locomotive hauling a passenger train|[[ALCO DL560C|WDM-3D]] broad-gauge diesel locomotive]]\n[[File:Steam Locomotive, Nilgiri Mountain Railway, May 2010.JPG|alt=Black steam locomotive at a station|thumb|The [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]], which uses one of India's few running steam locomotives]]\n\nIndia uses [[Electric locomotive|electric]] and [[diesel locomotive]]s, along with a few [[Compressed natural gas|CNG]] (compressed natural gas) locomotives.<ref>{{cite news |title=India's first CNG train flagged off |url=http://www.rediff.com/business/report/pix-indias-first-cng-train-flagged-off/20150115.htm |access-date=26 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226164505/http://www.rediff.com/business/report/pix-indias-first-cng-train-flagged-off/20150115.htm |archive-date=26 February 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Steam locomotive]]s are no longer in use, except in [[restored train|heritage trains]]. [[Locomotive]]s in India are classified by gauge, motive power, the work they are suited for, and their power or model number. Their four- or five-letter class name includes this information. The first letter denotes the track gauge, the second their motive power (diesel or electric), and the third their suitable traffic (goods, passenger, multi or shunting). The fourth letter denoted the locomotive's chronological model number, but in 2002, a new classification was adopted in which the fourth letter in newer diesel locomotives indicate [[horsepower]] range.\n\nA locomotive may have a fifth letter in its name, denoting a technical variant, subclass, or sub-type (a variation in the basic model (or series) or a different motor or manufacturer). In the new diesel-locomotive classification, the fifth letter refines the horsepower in 100-hp increments: A for 100&nbsp;hp, B for 200&nbsp;hp, C for 300&nbsp;hp and so on. In this classification, a WDM-3A is a 3100&nbsp;hp, a WDM-3D a 3400&nbsp;hp and a WDM-3F a 3600&nbsp;hp locomotive.{{efn|This classification system does not apply to steam locomotives, which retained their original class names (such as M class or [[Indian locomotive class WP|WP class]]).}} Diesel locomotives are fitted with auxiliary power units, which save almost 88 percent of fuel during idle time when a train is not running.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology allows Railways to save Rs 20 Lakhs Diesel per Engine|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/new-technology-allows-railways-to-save-rs-20-lakhs-diesel-per-engine/|accessdate=6 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908145226/http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/new-technology-allows-railways-to-save-rs-20-lakhs-diesel-per-engine/|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Goods wagons ===\n{{see also|Wagon numbering system in India|label 2=Wagon numbering system}}\nAs of March 2017, IR fleet consisted of 277,987 [[goods wagon]]s. They carried 1,110&nbsp;million tonnes of freight in Fiscal Year 2016\u201317.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" /> [[Wagon numbering system in India|Wagon types used by IR]] include BCACBM, BCCN, BCNA, BCNHL, BOBRN, BOBYN, BOXN (BOXN-HL, BOXN-HS, BOXN-HL, BOXN-CR, BOXN-LW, BOXN-AL, BOXN-EL), BRH, BTPGLN, BTPN and VVN.\n\nIR's bulk requirement of wagons is met by wagon manufacturing units both in public and private sectors as well as other Public Sector Units under the administrative control of Ministry of Railways.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/12.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 : Rolling Stock Summary|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032243/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/12.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Passenger coaches ===\nOn long-distance routes and also on some shorter routes, IR uses 2 primary types of coach design types. [[ICF coaches]], in production from 1955 until Jan 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/railminindia/status/956485140451962881?lang=en|title=End of an Era - The historic last ICF Coach was flagged off by Senior Techcnician Shri Bhaskar P in the presence of Railway Board Chairman Shri @AshwaniLohani. The 1st ICF coach had been flagged by Prime Minister Shri Lal Bahadur Shastri on 2 October, 1955.pic.twitter.com/qCfl8tVrQy|last=Railways|first=Ministry of|date=25 January 2018|website=@railminindia|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://twitter.com/railminindia/status/956485140451962881?lang=en|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> constitute the bulk of the current stock. These coaches, considered to be having inadequate safety features, are slowly being phased out. As of September 2017, around 40,000 coaches are still in operation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/after-spate-of-accidents-indian-railways-speeds-up-safety-plan-check-out-the-massive-task-and-big-numbers-involved/844454/|title=After spate of accidents, Indian Railways speeds up safety plan; check out the massive task and big numbers involved|date=7 September 2017|work=The Financial Express|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041740/http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/after-spate-of-accidents-indian-railways-speeds-up-safety-plan-check-out-the-massive-task-and-big-numbers-involved/844454/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The older coaches are being replaced with [[LHB coaches]]. Introduced in mid '90s, these coaches are lighter, safer and are capable of speeds up to {{convert|160|km/h||abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=April 2017|title=Indian Railways Passenger Coaches: Safety Features and Technologies Adopted|url=http://www.ijetsr.com/images/short_pdf/1492945632_nitttr232_Ijetsr_skype.pdf|journal=International Journal of Engineering Technology Science and Research|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041703/http://www.ijetsr.com/images/short_pdf/1492945632_nitttr232_Ijetsr_skype.pdf|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIR has announced that two new self-propelled train set designs will be introduced starting from mid 2018. These two train types, termed as [[Vande Bharat Express|Train-18]] and [[Train 20|Train-20]], are expected to replace locomotive-hauled trains on long-distance routes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/128617/train-18-train-20-indian-railways/|title=At 176 Kmph, These Two Upcoming Trains May Be India's Fastest Ever!|date=22 January 2018|work=The Better India|access-date=27 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100703/https://www.thebetterindia.com/128617/train-18-train-20-indian-railways/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn regional short-distance routes, IR runs [[MEMU|Mainline Electrical Multiple Unit (MEMU)]] or [[DEMU|Diesel Electrical Multiple Unit (DEMU)]] trains, depending on the traction available. These train sets are self-propelled with capability for faster acceleration or deceleration and are expected to reduce congestion on dense routes. Passenger locomotive-hauled trains, having frequent stops, are slowly being replaced with train sets across India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Loco-hauled-commuter-trains-to-be-replaced-with-DEMU/MEMU/articleshow/54680592.cms|title=Loco hauled commuter trains to be replaced with DEMU/MEMU \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226042551/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Loco-hauled-commuter-trains-to-be-replaced-with-DEMU/MEMU/articleshow/54680592.cms|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn suburban commuter routes around the large urban centers, IR runs trains with [[Electric multiple unit|Electric Multiple Unit (EMU)]] coaches. As of March 2017, about 9100 coaches are in operation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/13.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications 2016\u201317 \u2013 Rolling Stock|date=25 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041530/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/13.pdf|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Manufacturing ==\n\nIndian Railways is a [[Vertical integration|vertically-integrated]] organization that produces majority of its locomotives & rolling stock at in-house production units, with a few recent exceptions.\n\n'''Locomotives:'''\n* [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]] in [[Chittaranjan]], [[West Bengal]] manufactures electric locomotives.\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] in [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] manufactures diesel & electric locomotives. \n* [[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra|Diesel Locomotive Factory]] in [[Marhowra]], [[Bihar]], a [[Joint Venture]] of [[Indian Railway]]s & [[General Electric]] manufactures high capacity diesel locomotives, used especially for freight transportation.\n* [[Electric Locomotive Factory, Madhepura|Electric Locomotive Factory]] in [[Madhepura]], [[Bihar]], a [[Joint Venture]] of [[Indian Railway]]s and [[Alstom|Alstom SA]] manufactures electric locomotives.\n*[[Diesel-Loco Modernisation Works]] in [[Patiala]], [[Punjab]] upgrades and overhauls locomotives. They also manufacture electric locomotives\n\n'''Rolling Stock:'''\n* [[Integral Coach Factory]] in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Rail Coach Factory]] in [[Kapurthala]], [[Punjab]] \n* [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]] in [[Raebareli]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n*[[Integral Coach Factory|Coach Manufacturing Unit]] in [[Haldia]], [[West Bengal]]\n\n'''Wheel & Axle:'''\n\n* [[Rail Wheel Factory]] in [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Plant, Bela]] in [[Chhapra]], [[Bihar]]\n\nThe repair and maintenance of this vast fleet of rolling stock is carried out at 44 loco sheds, 212 carriage & wagon repair units and 45 periodic overhaul workshops across various zones of IR.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Network ==\n\n=== Tracks ===\n[[File:Project Unigauge (India).svg|thumb|Comparison of gauges in India with the standard gauge]]\n{{see also|Project Unigauge}}\n\nAs of March 2017, IR network spans {{convert|121,407|km||abbr=on}} of track length, while the route length is {{convert|67,368|km||abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Indian Railways, as of 1 April 2019, had a broad-gauge network of {{cvt|64,298|km}}. Of this, {{cvt|35,488|km}} was electrified. Track sections are rated for speeds ranging from {{convert|80|to|200|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, though the maximum speed attained by passenger trains is 180&nbsp;km/h (110&nbsp;mph) during trial runs. As of March 2017, most of the broad-gauge network is equipped with [[Track (rail transport)#Continuous welded rail|long-welded]], high-tensile strength [[Rail profile#Rail weights and sizes|52kg/60kg 90 UTS]] rails and [[prestressed concrete|pre-stressed concrete (PSC)]] sleepers with elastic fastenings.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n{{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}} [[broad gauge]] is the predominant [[track gauge|gauge]] used by IR and spans {{convert|61,680|km|abbr=on}} of route (92% of total route network). It is among the broadest gauge in use across the world for passenger movement.<ref name=\":4\" /> Broad gauge generated 100% of the freight output (Net tonne-Kilometres) and more than 99% of the passenger output (Passenger Kilometres) in the fiscal year 2016\u201317.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}} tracks and {{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}} and {{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}} [[narrow gauge]] tracks are present on fewer routes. All of these routes, except the heritage routes, are being converted to broad gauge. The metre gauge tracks were {{convert|3479|km|}} (5% of total route network) and narrow gauges tracks were {{convert|2208|km||abbr=on}} (3% of total route network) {{as of|2017|March|31|lc=y|post=.}}<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Electrification ===\n{{Main|Central Organisation for Railway Electrification}}\n\nAs of 31 March 2019, IR has electrified 50% or {{convert|35,442|km||abbr=on}} of the route kilometers and 46% or {{convert|55,240|km||abbr=on}} of the total running track. India uses [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25 kV 50 Hz AC]] traction on all its electrified tracks.<ref name=\"stats-summary\" />\n\n[[File:State Wise Position of Electric Traction of Rail Network in India.png|thumb|right|Total Route Kilometers Covered in the State as on 2018 (In Percentage).]]\n\nRailway electrification in India began with the first electric train, between [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus]] and [[Kurla]] on the Harbour Line, on 3 February 1925 on the [[Great Indian Peninsula Railway]] (GIPR) at 1500 V DC. Heavy gradients in the [[Western Ghats]] necessitated the introduction of electric traction on the GIPR to [[Igatpuri]] on the North East line and [[Pune]] on the South East line. On 5 January 1928 1500 V DC traction was introduced on the suburban section of the [[Bombay, Baroda and Central India Railway]] between [[Colaba]] and [[Borivili]], and between [[Madras]] Beach and [[Tambaram]] of the [[Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway]] on 11 May 1931, to meet growing traffic needs.<ref name=\"ELECT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,532 |title=Brief on Railway Electrification |access-date=1 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926072829/http://www.core.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,294,302,532 |archive-date=26 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The 3000 V DC electrification of the [[Howrah]]-[[Burdwan]] section of the [[Eastern Railway Zone (India)|Eastern Railway]] was completed in 1958. The first 3000 V DC [[electric multiple unit|EMU]] service began on the [[Howrah]]-[[Sheoraphuli]] section on 14 December 1957.<ref name=\"ELECT\"/>\n\nResearch and trials in [[Europe]], particularly on French Railways ([[SNCF]]), indicated that 25 kV AC was an economical electrification system. Indian Railways decided in 1957 to adopt 25 kV AC as its standard, with SNCF their consultant in the early stages. The first 25 kV AC section was Raj Kharswan\u2013Dongoaposi on the [[South Eastern Railway Zone, India|South Eastern Railway]] in 1960. The first 25 kV AC [[electric multiple unit|EMUs]], for [[Kolkata]] suburban service, began service in September 1962. For continuity, the Howrah\u2013Burdwan section of the Eastern Railway and the Madras Beach\u2013Tambaram section of the Southern Railway were converted to 25 kV AC by 1968. Because of limitations in the DC traction system, a decision was made to convert the electric traction system of the Mumbai suburban rail network of WR and CR from 1.5kV DC to 25 kV AC in 1996\u201397. The conversion from DC to AC traction was completed in 2012 by Western Railway, and in 2016 by Central Railway. Since then, the entire electrified mainline rail network in India uses 25 kV AC, and DC traction is used only for metros and trams.<ref name=\"ELECT\"/>\n\n[[File:Railway Electrification Rate for Leading & Laggard State\u2019s of India 2018.png|thumb|left|Railway electrification rate for leading and laggard states of India]]\n[[File:Railway-Electrification-Trend-&-Roadmap-for-India-till-FY-2022.png|thumb|right|Railway electrification trend and road map for India until FY 2022]]\n\nIndian Railways announced on 31 March 2017 that the country's entire rail network would be electrified by 2022.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\"/><ref name=\"enincon1\">{{cite web|url=https://enincon.com/report/railway-electrification-market-opportunities-in-india-2018/|title=Railway Electrification Market in India 2018|date=20 February 2018|publisher=Enincon|access-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320230336/https://enincon.com/report/railway-electrification-market-opportunities-in-india-2018/|archive-date=20 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThough not a nascent concept, the electrification in India now has been committed with a fresh investment of {{INRConvert|35000|c}} to electrify the entire network and eliminate the cost of fuel under transportation which will amount to a massive savings of {{INRConvert|10500|c}} overall. This will be a boon for savings for the Government to channelize the investments in modernization of the railway infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enincon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Railway-Electrification-Market-in-India-2018_Flyer.pdf|title=Railway Electrification Market in India 2018|date=20 February 2018|publisher=Enincon|access-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320170538/https://enincon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Railway-Electrification-Market-in-India-2018_Flyer.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClose to 30&nbsp;billion units of electricity will be required for railway electrification on an annual basis by 2022, leading to excellent opportunities for IPPs of conventional power.<ref name=\"enincon1\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n=== Signaling and telecommunication ===\n{{See also|Railway signal|Railway signalling}}\nIR uses a range of signalling technologies and methods to manage its train operations based on traffic density and safety requirements.\n\nAs of March 2017, around {{convert|2850|km|abbr=on}} of the route uses [[Automatic block signaling|automatic block signalling]] for train operations \u2013 concentrated in high density routes, large cities and junctions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/10.pdf|title=Indian Railways \u2013 Statistical Publication 2016\u201317 \u2013 Signalling and Telecom|date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044403/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/10.pdf|archive-date=1 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Remaining routes are based on [[absolute block signalling]] with trains manually controlled by signal men from the signal boxes typically located at stations. Few low density routes still use [[North American railway signaling#Absolute or manual block|manual block signalling]] methods with communication on track clearance based on physical exchange of tokens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://railscapestravel.com/2017/07/25/art-of-the-token-exchange/|title=Art of the token exchange|date=25 July 2017|work=Railscapes|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228233429/http://railscapestravel.com/2017/07/25/art-of-the-token-exchange/|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a few sections, intermediate block signalling is provided to further enhance line capacity with minimal investment. As of March 2017, 501 block sections have intermediate block signals on IR.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIR primarily uses [[railway signal#Color light signals|coloured signal lights]], which replaced [[railway signal#Mechanical signals|semaphores and disc-based signalling]] (dependent on position or colour).<ref name=\"irfcasignal\">{{cite web |title=Signalling System |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-signal.html |accessdate =4 June 2007 |work=IRFCA.org |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> IR uses two-aspect, three-aspect and four (or multiple) aspect color signalling across its network.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-signal2.html |title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Signal Aspects and Indications \u2013  Principal Running Signals |website=www.irfca.org|access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSignals at most stations are interlocked using [[Interlocking#Electro-mechanical interlocking|panel interlocking]], [[Interlocking#Relay interlocking|route-relay interlocking]] or [[Interlocking#Electronic interlocking|electronic interlocking]] methods that eliminate scope for human signalling errors. IR uses [[track circuit]]ing, and block proving [[axle counter]]s for train detection.\n\nAs of March 2017, 5584 stations across IR (about 90% of stations on broad gauge) have interlocked stations and multi-aspect signalling. Around 99% of key routes (A, B, C and D) have track circuitry or block proving axle counters for automated train detection. Also, IR has about 51,000 route kilometers of [[optical fiber cable]] network across India, that is used for train control, voice and data communication. Around {{convert|2500|km|abbr=on}} of the route is covered by [[GSM-R]] based Mobile Train Radio Communication.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2017, IR announced that it will implement [[European Train Control System|ETCS Level 2]] system for signalling and control on key routes with an investment of {{INRConvert|12000|c|lk=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/tech/news-analysis/indian-railways-clears-proposal-to-equip-electric-locomotives-with-european-train-protection-systems-4263417.html|title=Indian Railways clears proposal to equip electric locomotives with European train protection systems- Technology News, Firstpost|website=Tech2|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203235730/http://www.firstpost.com/tech/news-analysis/indian-railways-clears-proposal-to-equip-electric-locomotives-with-european-train-protection-systems-4263417.html|archive-date=3 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently IR uses [[Centralized traffic control|Centralised Traffic Control (CTC)]] on the busy Ghaziabad \u2013 Kanpur route and real-time train monitoring systems on [[Mumbai]] and [[Kolkata]] suburban routes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== {{anchor|Rail links with adjacent countries}}Links with adjacent countries ===\nRail links between India and neighboring countries are not well developed.\n\nTwo trains operate to [[Transport in Pakistan|Pakistan]]: the ''[[Samjhauta Express]]'' between [[Delhi]] and [[Lahore]] and the ''[[Thar Express]]'' between [[Jodhpur]] and [[Karachi]]. However, as of August 2019, they have been cancelled due to the [[Kashmir conflict|tension over Kashmir]]. [[Transport in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]] is connected by the four times a week ''[[Maitree Express]]'' that runs from [[Kolkata]] to [[Dhaka]] and weekly ''[[Bandhan Express]]'' which began running commercial trips between [[Kolkata]] and [[Khulna]] in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kolkata-khulna-bandhan-express-new-passenger-train-between-west-bengal-and-bangladesh-launched-5-poi-1773162 |title=Bandhan Express, New Train Between Bengal And Bangladesh: 10 Facts |work=NDTV.com |access-date=16 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116133418/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kolkata-khulna-bandhan-express-new-passenger-train-between-west-bengal-and-bangladesh-launched-5-poi-1773162 |archive-date=16 November 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/bandhan-express-makes-its-first-run-between-kolkata-khulna-india-bangladesh-on-thursday-4939545/|title=Bandhan Express makes its first commercial run between Kolkata and Khulna today|date=24 November 2019|work=The Indian Express|access-date=16 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116063408/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/bandhan-express-makes-its-first-run-between-kolkata-khulna-india-bangladesh-on-thursday-4939545/|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTwo rail links to [[Transport in Nepal|Nepal]] exist: passenger service between [[Jainagar, Bihar|Jainagar]] and [[Bijalpura]] and freight services between [[Raxaul]] and [[Birganj]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[India]]n and [[Bangladeshi]] governments has started work on a new rail link to ease surface transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inserbia.info/today/2014/06/construction-work-of-new-india-bangladesh-railway-link-to-begin-in-2015/|title=Construction Work Of New India-Bangladesh Railway Link To Begin In 2015|author=Das, Koushik |work=InSerbia News|access-date=26 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909150606/http://inserbia.info/today/2014/06/construction-work-of-new-india-bangladesh-railway-link-to-begin-in-2015/|archive-date=9 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> India will build a {{convert|13|km||adj=on|abbr=on}} railway linking [[Tripura]]'s capital [[Agartala]] with Bangladesh's southeastern city of [[Akhaura]], an important railway junction connected to [[Chittagong port]], resource-rich [[Sylhet]] and [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.ibnlive.com/news/work-on-new-indiabangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/480099-61.html |title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015-INews \u2013 IBNLive Mobile |date=18 June 2014 |work=IBNlive |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081939/http://m.ibnlive.com/news/work-on-new-indiabangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/480099-61.html |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> An agreement to implement the railway project was signed between the then Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] and Bangladesh Premier [[Sheikh Hasina]] during the latter's visit to India in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/indian-railway-to-build-a-15-km-track-linking-agartala-with-bangladesh/1/235817.html |title=Indian Railway to build a 15-km track linking Agartala with Bangladesh |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131837/http://m.indiatoday.in/story/indian-railway-to-build-a-15-km-track-linking-agartala-with-bangladesh/1/235817.html |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Total cost of the proposed project is estimated at {{INRConvert|252|c}}. The Indian Railway Construction Company (IRCON) is constructing the new railway tracks on both sides of the border. Of the {{convert|13|km|abbr=on}} rail line, {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} of tracks fall in Indian territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/guwahati/Work-on-Agartala-Akhaura-rail-link-to-commence-soon/articleshow/36756922.cms|title=Work on Agartala-Akhaura rail link to commence soon|work=The Times of India|access-date=26 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006122942/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/guwahati/Work-on-Agartala-Akhaura-rail-link-to-commence-soon/articleshow/36756922.cms|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms |title=Work on new India-Bangladesh railway link from 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718085020/http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Work-on-new-India-Bangladesh-railway-link-from-2015/articleshow/36725087.cms |archive-date=18 July 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Northeast Frontier Railways]] (NFR) is laying the connecting tracks for the new rail link on the Indian side, up to Tripura's southern-most border town, [[Sabroom railway station|Sabroom]] \u2013 {{convert|135|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Agartala]]. From [[Sabroom]], the [[Chittagong]] international sea port is {{convert|72|km|abbr=on}} away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meghalayatimes.info/index.php/region/13394-india-bangladesh-align-rail-link-in-tripura |title=India, Bangladesh align rail link in Tripura |work=Meghalaya Times |access-date=26 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006100230/http://www.meghalayatimes.info/index.php/region/13394-india-bangladesh-align-rail-link-in-tripura |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNo rail link currently exist with [[Transport in Myanmar|Myanmar]], but a railway line is to be built from [[Jiribam]] (in Manipur) to [[Tamu, Myanmar|Tamu]] through [[Imphal]] and [[Moreh, India|Moreh]].<ref name=\"imphalmorehline\">{{cite news |url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/IA03Df01.html |title=India's rail-building challenge |date=3 January 2007 |work=By Sudha Ramachandran|publisher=[[Asia Times]] |page=2 |accessdate=16 April 2009}}</ref> The construction of this missing link, as per the feasibility study conducted by the Ministry of External Affairs through [[RITES]] Ltd, is estimated to cost {{INRConvert|29.41|b}}.<ref name=\"tamujiribamrail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.siliconindia.com/shownews/India_signs_transAsian_railways_pact-nid-36316.html |title=India signs trans-Asian railways pact |date=2 July 2007 <!-- , 12:30 hrs -->|publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]|page=1|accessdate=16 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn {{convert|18|km|adj=on|abbr=on}} railway link with [[Transport in Bhutan|Bhutan]] is being constructed from [[Hashimara]] in West Bengal to Toribari in Bhutan.\n\nNo rail link currently exist with either [[China]] or [[Transport in Sri Lanka|Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-inter.html |title=IRFCA:Indian Railways FAQ:Geography:International |publisher=IRFCA, website of the Indian Railway Fan Club |accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n=== {{anchor|Passenger services}}Passenger service ===\n\n==== {{anchor|Categories of stations| Station categories |Types of stations| Station types}} Station categories ====\nFrom December 2017, stations are categorised into the Non-Suburban Groups NSG1 to NSG6, the Suburban Groups SG1 to SG3, and the Halt Groups HG1 to HG3 based on the earnings, passenger footfall, and strategic importance.<ref name=stac1/>\n\nBefore December 2017, stations were classified into A1, A, B, C, D, E, and F categories, based only on the passenger earnings from the sales of platform tickets, thus limiting the ability of IR to better focus its investments in passenger amenities.<ref name=stac1>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/railways-revise-station-categories-to-improve-services/articleshow/62280609.cms Railways revise station categories to improve services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317035551/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/railways-revise-station-categories-to-improve-services/articleshow/62280609.cms |date=17 March 2018 }}, [[The Economic Times|Economic Times]], 28 December 2017.</ref>\n\n==== {{anchor|Classes of service | Travel class| Travel type category}} Travel classes ====\n{{Main|Indian Railways coaching stock}}\n[[File:Rajdhani First AC1.jpg|thumb|alt=See caption|Interior of a first-class compartment on the [[Rajdhani Express]]]]\n[[File:Inside a 3-tier AC Compartment Dakshin Express.jpg|thumb|alt=Train compartment with two seats and a bed|Interior of a three-tier compartment on the Dakshin Express]]\n[[File:Habibganj-JabalpurJS.jpg|thumb|alt=Train car with many passenger seats|Interior of an air-conditioned chair-car coach on the [[Jan Shatabdi Express]]]]\n[[File:Inside an Indian Railways Train - Sleeper Coach.jpg|thumb|Interior of a sleeper coach]]\n\nIR has several classes of travel, with or without air-conditioning. A train may have one or several classes. Slow passenger trains have only unreserved seating, and the [[Rajdhani Express]], [[Shatabdi Express]], [[Garib Rath Express]], [[Double Decker Express]], [[Tejas Express]], [[Humsafar Express]] , [[Duronto Express]] , [[Yuva Express]], and [[Vande Bharat Express]] have only air-conditioned classes. Fares for all classes differ, and unreserved seating is the least expensive. Fares for the Rajdhani, Duronto Shatabdi and Vande Bharat Express trains include food. In September 2016, IR introduced dynamic fares for the Rajdhani, Duronto and Shatabdi trains (except 1AC and EC classes) to increase revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/indian-railways-ticket-price-hike-50-percent-rajdhani-shatabdi-3019567/|title=Premium railway fares hiked up to 50 per cent in new dynamic pricing model|date=8 September 2016|access-date=8 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909054512/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/indian-railways-ticket-price-hike-50-percent-rajdhani-shatabdi-3019567/|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Long-distance trains usually include a [[pantry car]], and food is served at the passengers' berth or seat. Luxury trains (such as [[Palace on Wheels]]) have separate dining cars, but these trains cost as much as\u2014or more than\u2014a five-star hotel room.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eman |first1=Borhan |title=Indian railway ready for 'privatization to run trains'! Meramaal Wiki |url=https://www.wiki.meramaal.com/2019/06/20/indian-railway-knockout-of-privatization/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=Meramaal News |date=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nA standard passenger rake has four unreserved (general) compartments, two at the front and two at the rear (one of which may be for women). The number of other coaches varies by demand and route. A luggage compartment may be at the front or the rear. On some mail trains, a separate mail coach is attached. Lavatories are communal, and [[Squat toilet|Indian-]] and Western-style. The classes in operation are (although a train may not have all these classes):\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\"\n! Class<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/class_Code.html|title=Accommodation Classes in Indian Railways|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=15 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426000003/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/class_Code.html|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! Description<ref name=irfcatravel>{{cite web| title = General Information on travelling by IR|work=IRFCA.org| url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-travel.html| accessdate =3 June 2007|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref><ref name=indrailuk>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiarail.co.uk/indrail.htm |title=Class of Travel |accessdate=3 June 2007 |work=indiarail.co.uk |publisher=S.D. Enterprises Ltd |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513200442/http://www.indiarail.co.uk/indrail.htm |archive-date=13 May 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Saloon''' \n|IR has started to operate saloon coaches to give hotel ambience on trains. These coaches operate on charter basis i.e. booking is required. These have a master bedroom, one normal bedroom, one kitchen and window trailing. Four to six extra beds are given to accommodate more people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianluxurytrains.com/home-on-wheels/|title=Home on Wheels - Luxury Train Travel in an Exclusive Railway Saloon|website=www.indianluxurytrains.com}}</ref> First of these coach was attached to [[Jammu Mail]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ready-to-shell-out-more-now-you-can-travel-in-railways-luxury-saloons/jammu-mail/slideshow/63554248.cms|title=Ready to shell out more! Now you can travel in Railways' luxury saloons - Jammu Mail|website=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''1A'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''AC first class''': The most luxurious and expensive class of Indian Railways, with fares almost at par with airfares. There are eight cabins (including two coupes) in a full AC first class coach and three cabins (including one coupe) in a half AC first class coach. The coach has a dedicated attendant and bedding is included in the fare. This air-conditioned coach, present only on popular routes, can carry 18 (full coach) or 10 passengers (half coach).\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''2A'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC two tier''': These air-conditioned coaches have sleeping berths across eight bays (full coach). Berths are usually arranged in two tiers in bays of six: four across the width of the coach and two lengthwise across the corridor, with curtains along the corridor. Bedding is included in the fare. A coach can carry 48 (full coach) or 20 passengers (half coach).\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''3A'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC three tier''': Air-conditioned coaches with 64 sleeping berths. Berths are similar to 2A, but with three tiers across the width and two lengthwise for eight bays of eight. They are slightly less well-appointed, usually with no reading lights or curtains. Bedding is included in the fare.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |'''3E'''\n| valign=\"top\" |'''AC three tier (economy)''': Air-conditioned coaches with 81 sleeping berths on the [[Garib Rath Express]]. Berths are usually arranged as in 3A, but with three tiers across the width and three lengthwise. Appointments are similar to 3A, but bedding is not included. These coaches are also present in some [[Duronto Express]] trains as well.\n|-\n|'''Vistadome'''\n|IR operates Vistadome glass roof coaches on some tourist routes. These include Araku Valley, [[Konkan Railway]], [[Kalka\u2013Shimla railway|Kalka-Shimla Railway]], Kashmir Valley, Kangra Valley and Neral-Matheran Route. These coaches' fares are equivalent to AC Executive Chair Car. IR also has plans to start Vistadome on [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyoooz.com/news/chennai/858438/icf-to-design-airconditioned-coach-for-nilgiri-mountain-railway/|title=ICF to design air-conditioned coach for Nilgiri Mountain Railway &#124; Chennai NYOOOZ|website=NYOOOZ}}</ref>\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''EA'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Anubhuti''': Air-conditioned top-end class of [[Shatabdi Express]]. These coaches were introduced in January 2018. The first train to get these coaches was the [[Chennai Central\u2013Mysuru Shatabdi Express]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''EC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Executive chair car''': An air-conditioned coach with spacious seats and legroom. With four seats in a row, it is used for intercity day travel and is available on the [[Tejas Express|Tejas]] , [[Shatabdi Express]] and [[Vande Bharat Express]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''CC'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''AC chair car''': An air-conditioned coach with five seats in a row, used for intercity day travel. Air-conditioned double-deck coaches are used on the [[Double Decker Express]], Shatabdi Express, Vande Bharat Express, and Intercity services.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''SL'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Sleeper class''': The sleeper class is the most common coach on IR, with ten or more SL coaches attached to a train rake. They are sleeping coaches with three berths across the width and two lengthwise, without air-conditioning. They carry 72 passengers per coach.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''2S'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Second seater''': similar to CC, but without air-conditioning. Double-deck second seaters are used on the [[Flying Ranee]].\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''UR/GEN'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Unreserved/General''': The least-expensive accommodation, with a seat not guaranteed. Tickets are valid on any train on a route if used within 24 hours of purchase.\n|}\n\nAt the rear of the train is the [[Brake van#India|guard's cabin]]. It contains a [[transceiver]], and is where the guard usually gives the all-clear signal before the train departs.\n\n==== {{anchor|Types of passenger trains}}Train types ====\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2018}}<!--most of the table is not cited-->\n{{main|Train numbering in India| List of named passenger trains in India| Longest train services of Indian Railways | Longest non-stop run in Indian Railways | label 1 =  Train numbering | label 2 = Named passenger trains | label 3 = Longest train services  | label 4 = Longest non-stop run}}\n[[File:NewDeli Mumbai Rajdhani AC 2 tier new livery.jpg|thumb|alt=Red-and-silver passenger train|The [[Mumbai Rajdhani Express]]. The long-distance, high-speed [[Rajdhani Express]]es connect state capitals and large cities with [[New Delhi]].]]\n[[File:Garib Rath.JPG|thumb|alt=Green-and-yellow passenger train|[[Secunderabad]]-[[Yeswanthpur|Yeshwanthpur]] [[Garib Rath Express]], an economy air-conditioned train]]\n\nTrains are sorted into categories which dictate the number of stops on a route, their priority on the network, and their fare structure. Each express train is identified by a five-digit number. If the first digit in the train number is 1 or 2, they are long-distance express trains. If the first digit is 0, the train is a special train which will operate for a limited period of time with a different fare structure. A first digit of 5 denotes a passenger train.\n\nThe second digit indicates the zone operating the train. However, for high-speed trains, the second digit is either 0 or 2 (the first remains 1 or 2).<ref name=irfcanumber/> The third digit denotes the division within the zone which is responsible for maintenance and cleanliness, and the last two digits are the train's serial number.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\">{{cite web | title = The system of train numbers |work=IRFCA.org\n | url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-number.html | accessdate = 3 June 2007 |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> The train numbering system was changed from four digits from December 2010,<ref name=\"fiveDigitNumer\">{{cite web |title        = New Train Number Enquiry\n |work         = Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Inquiry |url          = http://www.indianrail.gov.in/inet_trnno_enq.html\n |accessdate   = 5 February 2011 |publisher    = Centre For Railway Information Systems |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101124132548/http://indianrail.gov.in/inet_trnno_enq.html |archive-date = 24 November 2010\n |url-status     = live |df           = dmy-all}}</ref> to accommodate the increasing number of trains.\n\nTrains traveling in opposite directions along the same route are usually labelled with consecutive numbers.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\" /> However, there is considerable variation in train numbers; some zones, such as [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]], have a less-systematic method of numbering trains.<ref name=\"irfcanumber\" />\n\nTrains are classified by average speed.<ref name=\"irfcarailops\">{{cite web | title = railway operations&nbsp;\u2014 I | url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-ops.html | accessdate =11 June 2007 |work=IRFCA.org |publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club}}</ref> A faster train has fewer stops (halts) than a slower one, and is usually used for long-distance travel. Most express trains have special names to identify them easily. The names of the trains usually denote the regions they connect, the routes they traverse, or a famous person or tourist spot connected with the train.<ref name=\"irfcaname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-name.html|title=Train names|work=IRFCA.org|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|accessdate=3 June 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"namehindu\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blonnet.com/life/2005/06/24/stories/2005062400010100.htm|title=What's in a Train Name?|last=Sekhsaria|first=Pankaj|date=24 June 2005|accessdate=4 June 2007|publisher=The Hindu Business Line|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608015032/http://www.blonnet.com/life/2005/06/24/stories/2005062400010100.htm|archivedate=8 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable toccolours\" style=\"border:1px solid black;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n! '''Train types'''\n! '''Description'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Vande Bharat Express]]'''\n|A semi-high-speed, air-conditioned day time journey train with facilities such as [[Wi-Fi]], snack tables, CCTV cameras, hydraulic-pressure doors, and a fire and smoke detection and extinguishing system. It can run at a speed of 200&nbsp;km/h. It is the first hi-tech locomotive-less (EMU) train set made in India. It was flagged off on 15 February 2019 by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]. The model number for this particular train set is [[Train 18]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Tejas Express]]\n|A semi-high-speed, air-conditioned train which had its [[Mumbai CST - Karmali Tejas Express|inaugural run]] on 24 May 2017, covering {{convert|551.7|km|0|abbr=on}} in 8 hours 30 minutes. Coaches have bio-vacuum toilets, water-level indicators, tap sensors, hand dryers, integrated Braille displays, an LED TV for each passenger with a phone jack, local cuisine, [[Wi-Fi]], tea and [[coffee vending machine]]s, magazines, snack tables, CCTV cameras, and a fire and smoke detection and extinguishing system. It can run at a speed of 200&nbsp;km/h but it is restricted to 130&nbsp;km/h due to some technical reasons.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Gatimaan Express]]'''\n|The first [[Higher-speed rail|semi-high-speed]], air-conditioned train running between [[Delhi]] and [[Jhansi]] with a top speed of {{convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Shatabdi Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, intercity trains for daytime travel. Unlike the Rajdhani or Duronto Expresses, the Shatabdi expresses make a round trip on the same day. The Bhopal Shatabdi Express (train number 12001/12002) is India's second-fastest train between New Delhi and Agra, with an average speed of {{convert|90|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and a top speed of {{convert|150|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. The limited-stop trains have Wi-Fi.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rajdhani Express]]'''\n|Limited-stop, air-conditioned trains linking state capitals to the national capital, New Delhi, with a top speed of {{convert|130|-|140|km/h|abbr=on|mph}}. The 2014 railway budget proposed increasing the numbers of Rajdhani and Shatabdi Expresses to {{convert|180|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''[[Duronto Express]]'''\n|Non-stop (except for technical halts) service introduced in 2009. In January 2016, it became possible to book tickets from those technical stops. They connect India's metros and major state capitals, and were introduced to equal (or exceed) the speed of the Rajdhani Express. With air-conditioned one-, two-, or three-tier seating, some have non-air-conditioned sleeper-class accommodations.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Humsafar Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, three-tier coach trains with [[LED screen]]s displaying information about stations and train speed, a PA system, [[vending machines]] for tea and coffee, charging ports for electronic devices, bio-toilets, smoke alarms, CCTV cameras, curtains, and heating and refrigeration facilities for food. Its inaugural run was between [[Gorakhpur Junction railway station|Gorakhpur]] to [[Anand Vihar Terminal railway station|Anand Vihar Terminal]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[AC Express (Indian Railways)|AC Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, limited-stop trains linking major cities, with a speed of about {{convert|130|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Double Decker Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, limited-stop, two-tier express trains for daytime travel\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Uday Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned double decker train for overnight travel.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Garib Rath Express]]'''\n|Air-conditioned, economy, three-tier trains with a top speed of {{convert|130|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Yuva Express]]'''\n|Introduced with the Duronto Express to provide air-conditioned travel to young Indians, 60 percent of its seats were reserved for passengers between 18 and 45 years of age. The trains were unsuccessful, and operate only on the Delhi-Howrah and Delhi-Mumbai routes.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Jan Shatabdi Express]]'''\n|A more-economical version of the Shatabdi Express, with air-conditioned and non-air-conditioned classes and a top speed of {{convert|110|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Sampark Kranti Express]]'''\n|Express service to New Delhi.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Kavi Guru Express]]'''\n|Introduced in honor of [[Rabindranath Tagore]], four pairs of the trains operate on the network.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Vivek Express]]'''\n|Introduced to commemorate the 150th birth Anniversary of [[Swami Vivekananda]] in 2013, four pairs of Vivek Expresses run in the country.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rajya Rani Express]]'''\n|Introduced to connect state capitals to major cities in that state.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mahamana Express]]'''\n| Superfast train with Indian Railways' model rake coaches.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Intercity Express (Indian Railways)|Intercity Express]]'''\n|Introduced to connect major cities on short routes with high and semi-high speeds. Trains include the [[Deccan Queen]], [[Flying Ranee]] and [[Bilaspur \u2013 Nagpur Intercity Express|Bilaspur Nagpur Intercity Express]].\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Antyodaya Express]]'''\n|Non-reserved, high-speed [[LHB coaches]] on peak routes to ease congestion.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Jan Sadharan Express]]'''\n|Non-reserved express trains on peak routes to ease congestion.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Suvidha Express]]'''\n|High priority trains with dynamic pricing on high demand routes.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Express trains in India#Superfast Express|Superfast Express]]'''\n|Trains with a max speed greater than {{convert|100|-|110|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and an average speed greater than {{convert|55|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. With stops at very few stations, the tickets for these trains have a superfast surcharge.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Express trains in India|Express]]'''\n|Trains with a max speed greater than {{convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} and an average speed greater than {{convert|36|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, with stops at few stations.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mail trains in India|Mail]]'''\n|These trains earlier had separate [[mail]] coaches. Nowadays, mail is carried in the [[Baggage car|luggage coach]] like all other trains.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Slow and fast passenger trains in India|Passenger]]''' \n|Slow, economical trains which stop at every (or almost every) station on a route. With generally-unreserved seating, these trains travel at about {{convert|40|-|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Suburban rail in India|Suburban]]'''\n|These trains operate in [[Mumbai]], [[Delhi]], [[Kolkata]], [[Chennai]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Vadodara]], [[Surat]], [[Bengaluru]], [[Pune]] and between [[Kanpur]] and [[Lucknow]], usually stop at every station, and have unreserved seating.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Rapid transit in India|Metro]]'''\n|Designed for urban transport, the first metro was the [[Kolkata Metro]] in 1984.<ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/indias-first-underwater-metro-nears-completion-after-costs-double/articleshow/73686059.cms</ref> 13 metro systems currently exist, in a total of 21 cities. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''[[Mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways]]'''\n|Three of the lines were declared a [[World Heritage Site]] as \"[[Mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways of India]]\" by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web |title        = Toy Trains of India |url          = http://www.triptoindia.com/toy-trains-of-india-royal-train-tours-of-india-calling-tours-trip-to-india.html |accessdate   = 12 May 2007 |work         = Our Trips&nbsp;\u2013 Royal Train Tours |publisher    = India Calling Tours (P) Limited\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070808012804/http://www.triptoindia.com/toy-trains-of-india-royal-train-tours-of-india-calling-tours-trip-to-india.html |archive-date = 8 August 2007 |url-status     = live |df           = dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==== {{anchor|Luxury trains}}Tourism ====\n\nIndian Railway operates tourist train or coach services on popular tourist circuits in different regions of the country. The service offers tour packages inclusive of rail travel, local transportation, accommodation, food and guided tours. IR offers various tourist services in this segment including Luxury tourist trains, Semi luxury trains, Buddhist special trains, Bharat Darshan trains, Aastha Circuit trains, and Steam trains.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe ''[[Palace on Wheels]]'' is a luxury-train service, frequently hauled by a steam locomotive, to promote tourism in [[Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/travel/Palace+wheels/7386580/story.html|title=NPalace on wheels \u2013 Exclusive Indian train was originally used by royalty|publisher=Times of India|date=13 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017234123/http://www.vancouversun.com/travel/Palace+wheels/7386580/story.html|archivedate=17 October 2012}}</ref> The train has a seven-night, eight-day itinerary on a round trip from [[New Delhi]] via [[Jaipur]], [[Sawai Madhopur]] and [[Chittaurgarh]], [[Udaipur]], [[Jaisalmer]], [[Jodhpur]], [[Bharatpur, India|Bharatpur]] and [[Agra]].\n\n''[[Royal Rajasthan on Wheels]]'' covers a number of tourist destinations in Rajasthan. The seven-day, eight-night tour is a round trip from New [[Delhi]]'s [[Safdarjung railway station|Safdarjung station]] via [[Jodhpur]], [[Udaipur]] and [[Chittaurgarh]], [[Ranthambore National Park]] and [[Jaipur]], [[Khajuraho]], [[Varanasi]] and [[Sarnath]], and Agra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalsrajasthanonwheels.com/itinerary.html |title=Royal Rajasthan on Wheels Itinerary &#124; Tour Program for 2014\u201315 |publisher=Royalsrajasthanonwheels.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331033949/http://www.royalsrajasthanonwheels.com/itinerary.html |archive-date=31 March 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n''[[Maharajas' Express]]'', a luxury train operated by the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation]] (IRCTC), runs on five routes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themaharajasexpressindia.com/booking.php |title=The Maharajas' Express Train Journeys Season 2014\u20132015 |publisher=The-maharajas.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228004518/http://www.themaharajasexpressindia.com/booking.php |archive-date=28 February 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> to about 12 destinations across northwest and central India (centered around Rajasthan) from October to April.\n\nThe ''[[Deccan Odyssey]]'' covers tourist destinations in [[Maharashtra]] and [[Goa]]. Its seven-night, eight-day tour begins in [[Mumbai]] and stops at [[Jaigad Fort]], [[Ganapatipule]] and [[Ratnagiri]], [[Sindhudurg]], [[Tarkarli]] and [[Sawantwadi]], Goa, [[Kolhapur]] and [[Pune]] (Day 5), [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] and [[Ellora Caves]], and [[Ajanta Caves]] and [[Nashik]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1063 |title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board) |access-date=26 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105054339/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1063 |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Golden Chariot]]'' is a luxury train service running on two tours: Pride of the South<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/tour-itinerary.html |title=Tour Itinerary \u2013 Tour Itinerary of Golden Chariot Train, Itinerary of Golden Chariot Train |publisher=Goldenchariottrain.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414112147/http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/tour-itinerary.html |archive-date=14 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and Splendor of the South.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/southern-splendour-tour-itinerary.html |title=Southern Splendour Tour \u2013 South India Tour and South India Tour Package |publisher=Goldenchariottrain.com |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414125105/http://www.goldenchariottrain.com/southern-splendour-tour-itinerary.html |archive-date=14 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Mahaparinirvan Express]]'', an air-conditioned service also known as the Buddhist Circuit Train, is run by the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation|IRCTC]] for [[Buddhist]] pilgrims. Its seven-night, eight-day tour begins in New Delhi and visits [[Bodh Gaya]], [[Rajgir]] and [[Nalanda]], [[Varanasi]] and [[Sarnath]], [[Kushinagar]] and [[Lumbini]], [[Sravasti]], and the [[Taj Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1066 |title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board) |publisher=Indianrailways.gov.in |accessdate=27 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410173012/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,320,378,1066 |archive-date=10 April 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Fairy Queen (locomotive)|Fairy Queen]]'', a tourist attraction also known as the world's oldest operating steam engine, hauls a luxury train from Delhi to [[Alwar]].\n\n==== Ticketing ====\n{{see also| Tatkal scheme}}\n[[File:Railway ticket from Bangalore City junction to Pune junction.jpg|right|thumb|An Indian Railway ticket from [[Bangalore]] to [[Pune]] on Lokmanya Tilak Terminus - Coimbatore Express]]\nUntil the late 1980s, Indian Railways ticket reservations were made manually. In late 1987, IR began using a computerized ticketing system. The system went online in 1995 to provide current information on status and availability. The ticketing network at stations is computerized with the exception of remote areas. As of March 2017, close to 6000 stations are networked with reserved or unreserved ticketing systems across India.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/6.pdf|title=Indian Railways Statistical Publications \u2013 Passenger Business|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302173243/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/6.pdf|archive-date=2 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  IR now provides multiple channels for passengers to book tickets between any two train stations in the country.\n\nReserved tickets may be booked up to 120 days in advance on the [[Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation]] website, smartphone apps, [[SMS]], rail reservation counters at train stations, or through private ticket booking counters. A [[Tatkal scheme|Tatkal train ticket]] can be booked by passengers who want to travel at short notice with a reserved seat or berth, but such tickets are sold at higher fares than regular advance reservation tickets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/tatkal-ticket-booking-charges-timings-cancellation-and-more/articleshow/63095041.cms|title=Tatkal Ticket Booking: Charges, timings, cancellation and more \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612105406/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/tatkal-ticket-booking-charges-timings-cancellation-and-more/articleshow/63095041.cms|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nConfirmed reservation tickets will show the passenger and fare details along with berth or seat number(s) allocated to them on the ticket. If the reservation is not available on a particular train, the ticket has a wait-list number. A person with a wait-listed ticket must wait for enough cancellations to obtain a confirmed ticket. If their ticket is not confirmed on the day of departure, they cannot board the train. [[Reservation against Cancellation|Reservation against cancellation tickets]], between the waiting and confirmed lists, allow a ticket holder to board the train and obtain a seat chosen by a ticket collector after the collector has found a vacant seat.<ref name=\"reserve rules\" /><ref name=\"irfcatravel\" />\n\nUnreserved tickets for short distance or unplanned travels may be purchased at stations at any time before departure. Holders of such tickets may only board the general compartments. Suburban networks issue unreserved tickets valid for a limited time or season passes with unlimited travel between two stops for a period of time. Commuters can purchase tickets and season passes at stations or through [[UTS Mobile Ticketing|UTS]] mobile apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in/RDS/login?1|title=UTS Mobile Ticketing|website=www.utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in|access-date=2 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108163922/http://utsonmobile.indianrail.gov.in/RDS/login?1|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA valid proof for the purchase of ticket along with photo identification is required to board the train.\n\nIndia has some of the lowest train fares in the world, and passenger traffic is subsidised by higher-class fares.<ref name=\"Joshi\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r31MYIrISFMC&pg=PA184&dq=indian+rail|title=India's Economic Reforms, 1991\u20132001|last=Joshi|first=V|author2=I. M. D. Little|date=17 October 1996|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-829078-0|location=USA|page=184|chapter=Industrial Policy and Factor Markets|accessdate=25 June 2007}}</ref> Discounted tickets are available for [[senior citizen]]s (over age 60), the differently-abled, students, athletes, and those taking competitive examinations. One compartment of the lowest class of accommodation is earmarked for women on every passenger train. Some berths or seats are also reserved for women or senior citizens.<ref name=\"reserverules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/resrules.html |title=Reservation Rules |accessdate=25 June 2007 |publisher=Indian Railways |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624105628/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/resrules.html |archivedate=24 June 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Freight services}}Freight services ===\n{{See also|Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|label 1=Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India}}\nIn the freight segment, IR ferries various commodities and fuels in industrial, consumer, and agricultural segments across the length and breadth of India. IR has historically subsidised the passenger segment with income from the freight business. As a result, freight services are unable to compete with other modes of transport on both cost and speed of delivery, leading to continuous erosion of market share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/2.pdf|title=Indian Railways White Paper 2016|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032211/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Annual_Report_Accounts_Eng/2.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> To counter this downward trend, IR has started new initiatives in freight segments including upgrading of existing goods sheds, attracting private capital to build multi-commodity multi-modal logistics terminals, changing container sizes, operating time-tabled freight trains, and tweaking with the freight pricing/product mix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/Railways%20Presentation.pdf|title=INDIAN RAILWAYS 2017\u20132019 VISION & PLANS|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118230400/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/Railways%20Presentation.pdf|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, end-to-end integrated transport solutions such as [[Konkan Railway Corporation#RORO|roll-on, roll-off]] (RORO) service, a [[Rolling highway|road-rail system]] pioneered by [[Konkan Railway Corporation]] in 1999 to carry trucks on [[flatbed truck|flatbed]] trailers,<ref name=\"pibroro\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page1.asp?relid=949|work=Press release, Press Information Bureau, dated 2004-20-05|title=Road-Rail Synergy System|accessdate=22 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605172834/http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page1.asp?relid=949|archive-date=5 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> is now being extended to other routes across India.\n\nPerhaps the game changer for IR in the freight segment are the new [[Dedicated Freight Corridor Corporation of India|dedicated freight corridors]] that are expected to be completed by 2020. When fully implemented, the new corridors, spanning around 3300&nbsp;km, could support hauling of trains up to 1.5&nbsp;km in length with 32.5 ton axle-load at speeds of {{convert|100|km/h|}}. Also, they will free-up capacity on dense passenger routes and will allow IR to run more trains at higher speeds. Additional corridors are being planned to augment the freight infrastructure in the country.\n\n=== {{anchor|UNESCO world heritage sites}}UNESCO World Heritage Sites ===\nIR has two UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]]s: the [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus]], Mumbai,<ref>{{cite web | title=Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus (formerly Victoria Terminus) | work=World Heritage List | publisher=[[World Heritage Committee]] | year=2004 | url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/945 | accessdate=5 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219072551/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/945 | archive-date=19 December 2008 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the \"[[mountain railways of India|Mountain Railways of India]]\".<ref name=\"Mountain Railways of India\">{{cite web | title=Mountain Railways of India | work=World Heritage List | publisher=[[World Heritage Committee]] | year=1999 | url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944/ | accessdate=5 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219024051/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944/ | archive-date=19 December 2008 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The latter are three rail lines in different parts of India: the [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]], a {{RailGauge|610mm|lk=on}} [[narrow-gauge railway]] in the [[Lesser Himalayas]] of [[West Bengal]]; the [[Nilgiri Mountain Railway]], a {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}} [[rack railway]] in the [[Nilgiri Hills]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], and the [[Kalka-Shimla Railway]], a {{RailGauge|762mm|lk=on}} narrow-gauge railway in the [[Siwalik Hills]] of [[Himachal Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Mountain Railways of India\"/>\n\n== Issues ==\nIR carries an annual debt of over {{INRConvert|200|b}}. The passenger division lost {{INRConvert|300|b}} in FY 2013\u20132014, leading to a {{INRConvert|0.23}} loss per passenger-km and a cash surplus of {{INRConvert|6.9|b}}.<ref name=\"budget2014-15\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/2014-15_Final/Budget%20Speech%202014-15%20Highlights%20_English_PDF.pdf|title=Railway Budget 2014\u201315|access-date=20 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710222712/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/finance_budget/2014-15_Final/Budget%20Speech%202014-15%20Highlights%20_English_PDF.pdf|archive-date=10 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Its [[operating ratio]] was 109 percent from April to December 2016.<ref name=loss1>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/pP70AXtpAMAHqsoxyFaFtL/Railways-operating-ratio-touches-a-record-109-in-AprilDec.html|title=Railways' operating ratio touches a record 109% in April\u2013December|last=Sood|first=Jyotika|date=16 February 2017|newspaper=Livemint|access-date=19 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218181348/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/pP70AXtpAMAHqsoxyFaFtL/Railways-operating-ratio-touches-a-record-109-in-AprilDec.html|archive-date=18 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It's accounting systems are allegedly outdated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/jvDzOl95sfbjnt43QU6xnI/Railways-moves-towards-accounting-reforms.html|title=Railways moves towards accounting reforms|last=Lohumi|first=Manasi|date=20 December 2016|work=livemint.com|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032337/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/jvDzOl95sfbjnt43QU6xnI/Railways-moves-towards-accounting-reforms.html|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2014, 99 new rail projects were announced in the annual [[Rail Budget]]s without additional funding. One project has been completed; the remaining 98 will require {{INRConvert|5|t}}, including four projects which were 30 years old in 2014.<ref name=\"budget2014-15\"/> IR is losing passenger and freight market share to other modes of transport.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2014/07/08/Photos/w_Rail_Budget_Precursor_grfx.jpg |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708110953/http://www.livemint.com/r/LiveMint/Period1/2014/07/08/Photos/w_Rail_Budget_Precursor_grfx.jpg |archive-date=8 July 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Report of High Level Safety Review Committee'' of 2012, from 2007\u201308 to October 2011, casualties in train accidents accounted for 1,019 deaths and 2,118 injuries. In the same period, 1,600 railway staff were killed and 8,700 were injured. The committee estimated that almost 15,000 people are killed each year by what is called unlawful trespassing.<ref>[http://irsme.nic.in/files/FINAL-BOOK-HLSRC_latest-17-02-2012.pdf ''Report of High Level Safety Review Committee''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213810/http://irsme.nic.in/files/FINAL-BOOK-HLSRC_latest-17-02-2012.pdf |date=14 July 2014 }}, Railway Ministry, February 2012</ref> A ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' article<ref>''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', Wednesday 18 April 2012 issue, page 14, rightmost column)</ref> stated that IR officials believe that a large proportion of bodies found dead on railways died elsewhere and were put on the railway in dishonest attempts to get compensation from the railway authorities and companies.\n\nIR carries out various activities that are essentially uneconomic in nature, where it is either not able to recover the costs (capital investments/operating costs) it incurs to deliver such services, or ends up foregoing revenues. Such activities, termed by IR as Social Service Obligations, include concessional tariffs for a few passenger segments or essential commodities and services in uneconomical train routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://niti.gov.in/writereaddata/files/document_publication/Social-Costs.pdf|title=Reviewing the Impact of Social Service Obligations by Indian Railways|last=Bibek Debroy and Kishore Desai|date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215030114/http://niti.gov.in/writereaddata/files/document_publication/Social-Costs.pdf|archive-date=15 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> While the assessment of actual losses to meet social service obligations requires a scientific study, the estimation of such losses from IR for the fiscal year 2016\u201317 is {{INRConvert|296.3|b|lk=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/18.pdf|title=Indian Railways Year Book 2016\u201317, Social Service Obligations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225210117/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/directorate/stat_econ/IRSP_2016-17/Year_Book_Eng/18.pdf|archive-date=25 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\n{{Main|Future of rail transport in India}}\n\nIR's [[Research Design and Standards Organisation]] (RDSO) undertakes research, design and standardisation. The railway has undertaken several initiatives to upgrade its ageing infrastructure and improve its quality of service. The Indian government plans to invest {{INRConvert|9.05|t}} to upgrade IR by 2020.<ref name=\"Economic Times\">{{cite web|title=GE, Alstom land $5.6-billion deals to supply locomotives for railways|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ge-alstom-land-5-6-billion-deals-to-supply-locomotives-for-railways/articleshow/49733686.cms|work=Economic Times|date=10 November 2015|accessdate=13 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112021946/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/ge-alstom-land-5-6-billion-deals-to-supply-locomotives-for-railways/articleshow/49733686.cms|archive-date=12 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nInfrastructure modernisation projects include [[High-speed rail in India|high-speed rail]], with the first Ahmedabad-Mumbai train in operation in 2022;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/diamond-quadrilateral-of-high-speed-trains/ |title=Diamond quadrilateral of high-speed trains \u2013 A Dastidar, Indian Express, 10 June 2014 |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813222712/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/diamond-quadrilateral-of-high-speed-trains/ |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-sign-deal-with-japan-to-get-first-bullet-train/article7961724.ece |title=India to sign deal with Japan to get first bullet train \u2013 The Hindu<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802071232/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-to-sign-deal-with-japan-to-get-first-bullet-train/article7961724.ece |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/indian-cabinet-agrees-to-pick-japan-for-high-speed-rail-project-1449744059 |title=India Said to Pick Japan for High-Speed Rail Project \u2013 WSJ<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=22 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518014556/https://www.wsj.com/articles/indian-cabinet-agrees-to-pick-japan-for-high-speed-rail-project-1449744059 |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> redevelopment of 400 stations by monetizing {{convert|2700|acre|km2}} of spare railway land under a {{INRConvert|1070000|c|0}} plan;<ref name=sta1>[http://www.livemint.com/Companies/NV9ujsKfuh92SnrxtiC86H/Railways-appoints-IRSDC-as-nodal-agency-for-station-redevelo.html Railways appoints IRSDC as nodal agency for station redevelopment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102226/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/NV9ujsKfuh92SnrxtiC86H/Railways-appoints-IRSDC-as-nodal-agency-for-station-redevelo.html |date=23 December 2017 }}, Livemint, 5 December 2017.</ref> [[Double-track railway|doubling tracks]] to reduce congestion and delays while improving safety (15,000&nbsp;km of double track existed in 2016, and funding for 12,500&nbsp;km more was approved that year);<ref name=bg1/> the refurbishing of 12- to 15-year-old coaches at the Carriage Rehabilitation Workshop in Bhopal to enhance passenger amenities and fire safety;<ref>{{cite news|title=Indian Railways gets first model rake of luxury 'Make in India' coaches|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/infrastructure/indian-railways-gets-first-model-rake-of-luxury-make-in-india-coaches/led-reading-lights/slideshow/50527595.cms|accessdate=13 January 2016|agency=Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.|work=The Economic Times|date=11 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215143/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/slideshows/infrastructure/indian-railways-gets-first-model-rake-of-luxury-make-in-india-coaches/led-reading-lights/slideshow/50527595.cms|archive-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Indian Railways unveils 'Make in India' train coaches with new look|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/business-gallery/192582/indian-railways-unveils-make-in-india-train-coaches-with-new-look-check-irctc-co-in/2/|accessdate=13 January 2016|agency=The Indian Express Group|work=The Financial Express|date=13 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115052117/http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/business-gallery/192582/indian-railways-unveils-make-in-india-train-coaches-with-new-look-check-irctc-co-in/2/|archive-date=15 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS)-enabled tracking of trains to improve safety and service;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/business/report-just-like-your-cabs-you-can-soon-track-trains-in-real-time-via-gps-2563623|title=Just like your cabs, you can soon track trains in real time via GPS {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=30 November 2017|work=DNA India|access-date=30 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202071947/http://www.dnaindia.com/business/report-just-like-your-cabs-you-can-soon-track-trains-in-real-time-via-gps-2563623|archive-date=2 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Digital India]]-driven {{INRConvert|3500000|m|currency_formatting=c|to=USD|year=2017}} digitalisation of the railway to improve efficiency and reduce cost;<ref name=bg1/> [[Rainwater harvesting#India|rainwater harvesting]], with 1885 systems installed by December 2016;<ref name=rain1>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=155020 Rain Water Harvesting System In Indian Railway] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102329/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=155020 |date=23 December 2017 }}, 7 December 2016.</ref> and [[reforestation]] of railway land and along the tracks.<ref name=forest1>[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2016/07/india-plants-50-million-trees-uttar-pradesh-reforestation/ India Plants 50 Million Trees in One Day, Smashing World Record] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102536/https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2016/07/india-plants-50-million-trees-uttar-pradesh-reforestation/ |date=23 December 2017 }}, [[National Geographic]], July 2016.</ref>\n\n=== Electrification and power ===\nAll routes will be [[Central Organisation for Railway Electrification|electrified]] to save on imported-fuel costs. 57.91 percent of the network was electrified as of November 2019, with full electrification planned by March 2021.<ref name=bg1>[http://railengdigest.com/project-news/asia/indian-railways-converts-broad-gauge/ Indian Railways orders conversion to Broad Gauge] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102927/http://railengdigest.com/project-news/asia/indian-railways-converts-broad-gauge/ |date=23 December 2017 }}, Rail Digest, 12 April 2017.</ref> [[Off-the-grid]] solar-powered trains are planned with the installation of one gigawatt of [[Solar power|solar]] and 130 megawatts of [[wind power]] between 2017 and 2022; India introduced the world's first solar-powered train and 50 coaches with rooftop solar farms in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/indias-first-solar-powered-demu-train-launched/article19281625.ece|title=India\u2019s first solar-powered DEMU train launched|work=The Hindu|access-date=23 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/indias-first-solar-powered-demu-train-launched/article19281625.ece|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130808115946/http://www.eco-business.com/news/railways-iit-madras-tie-power-ac-coaches-solar-energy/ Railways, IIT-Madras tie up to power AC coaches with solar energy]. ''The Times of India'' (5 August 2013). Retrieved on 17 August 2013.</ref><ref name=solar1>[https://www.curbed.com/2017/7/19/15995536/solar-power-train-india-railways India\u2019s new solar-powered train is the first in the world] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102640/https://www.curbed.com/2017/7/19/15995536/solar-power-train-india-railways |date=23 December 2017 }}, June 2017</ref> Initial assessments of this experiment has been positive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309625965_Rail_coaches_with_rooftop_solar_photovoltaic_systems_A_feasibility_study |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726225212/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309625965_Rail_coaches_with_rooftop_solar_photovoltaic_systems_A_feasibility_study |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>[[Rooftop photovoltaic power station|Rooftop solar electricity]] is planned at stations to reduce long-term fuel costs and protect the environment,<ref>{{cite news|title=NORTHERN RAILWAYS TO INSTALL 5 MW ROOFTOP SOLAR IN FOUR OF ITS STATIONS|url=http://mercomcapital.com/northern-railways-to-install-5-mw-rooftop-solar-in-four-of-its-stations#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf|access-date=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303201130/http://mercomcapital.com/northern-railways-to-install-5-mw-rooftop-solar-in-four-of-its-stations#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf#sthash.5S8zaJPl.dpuf|archive-date=3 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Sustainable lighting|sustainable]] [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] lighting at all stations is planned by March 2018 to cut electricity costs.<ref name=led1>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/all-railway-stations-to-be-100-pc-led-lit-by-april-2018-rlys/articleshow/62138170.cms Indian Railways plans to make all stations 100% LED lit by 31 March 2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518114500/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/all-railway-stations-to-be-100-pc-led-lit-by-april-2018-rlys/articleshow/62138170.cms |date=18 May 2018 }}, [[Times of India]], 19 December 2017.</ref> Locomotive factories have been modernised, including two new factories in Bihar: an [[electric locomotive]] factory in [[Madhepura]] and a diesel locomotive factory in [[Marhaura]], and 2,285 bio-toilets were introduced from April to July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locomotive Factories in Bihar: In cold storage for years, two Railway projects to start soon|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/locomotive-factories-in-bihar-in-cold-storage-for-years-two-railway-projects-to-start-soon/|work=Indian Express|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031004858/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/locomotive-factories-in-bihar-in-cold-storage-for-years-two-railway-projects-to-start-soon/|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=GE Gets $2.6 Billion Indian Railways Contract|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ge-to-help-modernize-indias-rail-system-1447080903|work=Wall Street Journal|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109183451/http://www.wsj.com/articles/ge-to-help-modernize-indias-rail-system-1447080903|archive-date=9 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rail ministry awards Rs 14,656-cr Marhowra locomotive project to GE|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/rail-ministry-awards-rs-14-656-cr-marhowra-locomotive-project-to-ge-115110900795_1.html|work=Business Standard|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112014526/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/rail-ministry-awards-rs-14-656-cr-marhowra-locomotive-project-to-ge-115110900795_1.html|archive-date=12 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A {{INRConvert|200|b}} partnership with [[Alstom]] to supply 800 electric locomotives from 2018 to 2028 was announced.<ref name=\"Economic Times\"/>\n\n=== Safety ===\nSafety projects include the elimination of an average of 1,217 unguarded [[level crossing]]s per year by building an average of 1,066 overpasses and underpasses per year;<ref name=umc1>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=145324 Indian Railways commissions around 4800 kilometer of broad gauge track in last two financial years which is a record performance ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611154206/http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=145324 |date=11 June 2016 }}, 12 May 2016.</ref><ref name=bg1/> the extension of an automated [[fire alarm system]], first introduced on Rajdhani Express trains in 2013, to all air-conditioned coaches;<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Railways develops Automatic Fire and Smoke Detection System|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-railways-develops-automatic-fire-and-smoke-detection-system/|accessdate=5 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908145221/http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-railways-develops-automatic-fire-and-smoke-detection-system/|archive-date=8 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and 6,095 GPS-enabled [[Inertial navigation system|Fog Pilot Assistance System]] [[railway signalling]] devices (replacing the practice of placing firecrackers on tracks to alert train drivers) installed in 2017 in four zones: [[Northern Railway zone|Northern]], [[North Central Railway zone|North Central]], [[North Eastern Railway zone|North Eastern]] and [[North Western Railway zone|North Western]]; and replacing ICF coaches with LHB coaches.\n\n=== Effects of COVID-19===\nIn an unprecedented move, the railways had suspended the services of 13,523 trains for 21 days after the lockdown was announced by the PM on March 24.\n\nIts freight trains however continued to run during this period.<ref>https://www.livemint.com/news/india/railways-issues-restoration-plan-asks-to-prepare-for-resumption-of-services-11585981517025.html</ref> This was the first time in its 167 year history the lifeline of the nation was stopped.\n\n==Trivia==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n*[[Vivek Express]] has the longest route in India, which covers 4,286&nbsp;km in about 82 hours and 30 minutes. The train runs between Dibrugarh and Kanyakumari.\n*[[Howrah\u2013Amritsar Express]] 13049/50 has the record for maximum stops by an Express/Mail train in India. The train has 115 stops en route.\n*[[Vande Bharat Express]] is the fastest train by average speed in India and runs between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi Station]] and [[Varanasi Junction]]. Another train runs between [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi Station]] and [[Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra railway station|Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Katra Station]]\n*[[Gorakhpur Junction railway station|Gorakhpur Junction]] in [[Gorakhpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] has the longest platform in the world measuring 1,366m.\n*[[Puratchi Thalaivar Dr. M.G. Ramachandran Central Railway Station]] in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]] is the longest station name in India and second-longest in the world followed by [[Bangalore City railway station|Krantivira Sangolli Rayanna Bengaluru Railway Station]] in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]], the third-longest station name in the world.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of railway stations in India]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{div col}}\n* Aguiar, Marian. ''Tracking Modernity: India's Railway and the Culture of Mobility''  (University of Minnesota Press; 2011) 226 pages; draws on literature, film, and other realms to explore the role of the railway in the Indian imagination. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0816665613/ excerpt and text search]\n* Bear, Linda. ''Lines of the Nation: Indian Railway Workers, Bureaucracy, and the Intimate Historical Self'' (2007)  [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0231140029/  excerpt and text search]\n* Kerr, Ian J. ''Railways in Modern India'' (2001) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0195648285 excerpt and text search]\n* Kerr, Ian J. ''Engines of Change: The Railroads That Made India'' (2006)\n* Kumar, Sudhir, and Shagun Mehrotra. ''Bankruptcy to Billions: How the Indian Railways Transformed Itself'' (2009)\n* {{cite web|title=IRFCA : FAQ - Table of Contents|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/index.html|accessdate=19 June 2005}}\n* {{cite web|title=IRCTC|url=https://www.irctc.co.in|publisher=Indian Railways|accessdate=19 June 2005}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Indian Railways.ogg|2006-03-15}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130402130639/http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/  Ministry of Indian Railways, Official website]\n\n<!--ATTENTION! PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY LINKS RELATED TO CHECKING PNR STATUS ETC, SUCH EDITS WILL BE REMOVED. READ THE EXTERNAL LINKS GUIDELINE-->\n\n{{Indian Railways}}\n{{Urban rail transit in India}}\n{{THBSOIR}}\n{{Asia in topic|Rail transport in}}\n{{Transport in India}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Railways}}\n[[Category:Indian Railways|*]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of India]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of India]]\n[[Category:1845 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1845]]\n", "name_user": "Bhaveshbharwani9", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Railways"}
{"title_page": "NCIS (season 17)", "text_new": "{{short description|Season of television series}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number = 17\n |bgcolour      = #36454F\n |image         = NCISSeason17.jpg\n |caption       = \n |starring      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Harmon]]\n* [[Sean Murray (actor)|Sean Murray]]\n* [[Wilmer Valderrama]]\n* [[Emily Wickersham]]\n* [[Maria Bello]]\n* [[Brian Dietzen]]\n* [[Diona Reasonover]]\n* [[Rocky Carroll]]\n* [[David McCallum]]\n}}\n |country       = United States\n |num_episodes  = 20<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n |network       = [[CBS]]\n |first_aired   = {{Start date|2019|9|24}}\n |last_aired    = {{End date|2020|4|14}}\n |episode_list  = List of NCIS episodes\n}}\nThe seventeenth season of ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'', an American [[Police procedural|police procedural drama]] television series, originally aired on [[CBS]] from September 24, 2019 through April 14, 2020. The season was produced by Belisarius Productions and [[CBS Television Studios]].\n\n''NCIS'' revolves around a fictional team of [[special agent]]s from the [[Naval Criminal Investigative Service]], which conducts criminal investigations involving the [[U.S. Navy]] and [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]].\n\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Mark Harmon]] as [[Leroy Jethro Gibbs]], NCIS Supervisory Special Agent (SSA) of Major Case Response Team (MCRT) assigned to Washington's Navy Yard\n* [[Sean Murray (actor)|Sean Murray]] as [[Timothy McGee]], NCIS Senior Field Agent, second in command\n* [[Wilmer Valderrama]] as [[Nicholas Torres|Nicholas \"Nick\" Torres]], NCIS Field Agent and former Undercover Agent\n* [[Emily Wickersham]] as [[Ellie Bishop|Eleanor \"Ellie\" Bishop]], NCIS Field Agent\n* [[Maria Bello]] as [[List of NCIS characters#Jacqueline Sloane|Dr. Jacqueline \"Jack\" Sloane]], NCIS Senior Resident Agent and operational psychologist\n* [[Brian Dietzen]] as [[Jimmy Palmer|Dr. Jimmy Palmer]] Chief Medical Examiner for NCIS\n* [[Diona Reasonover]] as [[List of NCIS characters#Kasie Hines|Kasie Hines]], Forensic Scientist for NCIS\n* [[Rocky Carroll]] as [[List of NCIS characters#Leon Vance|Leon Vance]], NCIS Director\n* [[David McCallum]] as [[Dr. Donald \"Ducky\" Mallard|Dr. Donald Mallard]], NCIS Historian and former Chief Medical Examiner\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Cote de Pablo]] as [[Ziva David]], former NCIS Special Agent\n* [[Laura San Giacomo]] as [[List of NCIS characters#Grace Confalone|Dr. Grace Confalone]]\n* [[Megan Gallagher]] as Jennifer Leo, Under Secretary of the Navy\n* [[Don Lake]] as Phillip Brooks, Navy Captain\n* [[Louise Barnes]] as Mira Sahar Azam / Sarah, Gibbs' Neighbour and terrorist\n* Jack Fisher as Phineas, Sarah's son\n* [[Usman Ally]] as Victor Mir, NCIS target\n* Damon Dayoub as [[List of NCIS characters#Adam Eshell|Adam Eshel]], Mossad Officer\n* Elayn J. Taylor as Odette Malone, former CIA Operative\n* Kate Hamilton as Faith Tolliver, Jack Sloane's biological daughter\n\n===Guest===\n* [[Devale Ellis]] as Dante Brown, Kasie's childhood best-friend\n* [[Patrick Duffy]] as Jack Briggs, Retired Navy Lieutenant Commander\n* [[Kevin Kilner]] as Patrick Norian, NSA Access Manager\n* [[Lisa LoCicero]] as Elena Devol, Torres's girlfriend\n* [[Camryn Grimes]] as Laney Alimonte, Marine Corporal\n* [[Ellen Geer]] as Esther Daniels\n* [[Karri Turner]] as Micki Kaydar, Phineas' aunt\n* [[Daphne Zuniga]] as Stacy Gordon, Navy Commander\n* [[Christopher Lloyd]] as Joseph \"Joe\" Smith\n\n==Episodes==\n<onlyinclude>\n{{#invoke:Episode table|main\n|background  = #36454F\n|overall     = 5\n|season      = 5\n|title       = 24\n|director    = 15\n|writer      = 32\n|airdate     = 12\n|viewers     = 8\n|country     = U.S.\n|episodes    =\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|NCIS (season 17)\n |EpisodeNumber   = 379\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Out of the Darkness\n |DirectedBy      = [[Terrence O'Hara]]\t\